{"title_page": "Arese", "text_new": "''For people, see [[Arese family]].''{{Infobox Italian comune\n| name                = Arese\n| official_name       = Citt\u00e0 di Arese\n| native_name         = \n| image_skyline       = AreseVillaRicottiLaValera001.JPG\n| imagesize           = \n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = Villa Ricotti.\n| image_shield        = Arese-Stemma.svg\n| shield_alt          = \n| image_map           = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|45|33|N|9|4|E|type:city(19,333)_region:IT|display=inline}}\n| coordinates_footnotes = \n| region              = [[Lombardy]]\n| metropolitan_city            = [[Metropolitan City of Milan|Milan]] (MI)\n| frazioni            = Valera\n| mayor_party         = \n| mayor               = Michela Palestra\n| area_footnotes      = \n| area_total_km2      = 6.5\n| population_footnotes = <ref name=\"istat\">All demographics and other statistics: Italian statistical institute [[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|Istat]].</ref>\n| population_total    = 19235\n| population_as_of    = 30 June 2015\n| pop_density_footnotes = \n| population_demonym  = Aresini\n| elevation_footnotes = \n| elevation_m         = 160\n| twin1               = \n| twin1_country       = \n| saint               = Ss. Pietro e Paolo\n\n| day                 = \n| postal_code         = 20020\n| area_code           = 02\n| website             = {{official website|http://www.comune.arese.mi.it/}}\n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Arese''' ({{lang-lmo|Ares}} {{IPA-lmo|a\u02c8re\u02d0s|}}) is a ''[[comune]]'' (municipality) in the [[Metropolitan City of Milan]] in the [[Italy|Italian]] region [[Lombardy]], located about {{convert|12|km|mi|0}} northwest of [[Milan]].\n\nArese borders the following municipalities: [[Lainate]], [[Garbagnate Milanese]], [[Bollate]], [[Rho (Italy)|Rho]], [[Milan]].\n\nArese received the honorary title of city with a presidential decree of October 25, 1985.\n\nFor what concerns the historical center, of particular interest is the [[Church of St. Peter and Paul, Arese|Church of St. Peter and Paul]], located in the city center.\n\n== Alfa Romeo ==\n[[File:AlfaRomeoAreseTec1.jpg|thumb|left|The Technical Center of Alfa Romeo in 2011.]]\nStarting in 1960, Arese hosted the main seat of [[Alfa Romeo]], partly in the territories of [[Lainate]] and [[Garbagnate Milanese]]. After three years of construction, the [[Alfa Romeo Arese Plant]] first began vehicle production in 1963, which would continue for decades, becoming the biggest production facility for Alfa Romeo. The factory became known simply as \"Arese\" as most of the industrial area and its main entrance are in this municipality. Following a gradual decrease in production activities, the factory finished manufacturing activities in 2005. Today the factory is almost totally closed and abandoned, since the Alfa Romeo owners ([[FIAT]]) have almost completely moved design and production to other factories inside and outside [[Italy]]. The few remaining employees (about 500) have often demonstrated against their dismissal. At the moment, most of the factory buildings are abandoned and the local administrations are looking for projects to use the huge area in a proper way, given its location. Arese and the factory are in fact very close to the newest services of [[Milan]] town, such as the [[High-speed rail in Italy|high speed railway]] and the new exhibition centre [[FieraMilano]].\n\n=== Historical Museum ===\n{{main|Alfa Romeo Museum}}\nOne of the few activities which is still located in the Alfa Romeo old factories is the Museo Storico Alfa Romeo, which is hosted in a dedicated building of great architectural value. In early 2011, Fiat announced the closure of the museum for renovations after the Ministry for Cultural Activities had declared the building and the collection of national cultural interest, on Arese municipality's request. \nAfter four years, the museum officially reopened in June 2015.\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\nArese is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n* {{flagicon|HUN}} [[Mosonmagyar\u00f3v\u00e1r]], Hungary (1989)\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Campolieto]], Italy (2006)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.comune.arese.mi.it/}} {{in lang|it}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.alfaromeo.com|Alfa Romeo official website}}\n* [https://www.museoalfaromeo.com Museo Storico Alfa Romeo]\n\n{{clear}}\n{{Province of Milan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Alfa Romeo]]\n\n\n{{Milan-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Italian comune\n| name                = Arese\n| official_name       = Citt\u00e0 di Arese\n| native_name         = \n| image_skyline       = AreseVillaRicottiLaValera001.JPG\n| imagesize           = \n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = Villa Ricotti.\n| image_shield        = Arese-Stemma.svg\n| shield_alt          = \n| image_map           = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|45|33|N|9|4|E|type:city(19,333)_region:IT|display=inline}}\n| coordinates_footnotes = \n| region              = [[Lombardy]]\n| metropolitan_city            = [[Metropolitan City of Milan|Milan]] (MI)\n| frazioni            = Valera\n| mayor_party         = \n| mayor               = Michela Palestra\n| area_footnotes      = \n| area_total_km2      = 6.5\n| population_footnotes = <ref name=\"istat\">All demographics and other statistics: Italian statistical institute [[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|Istat]].</ref>\n| population_total    = 19235\n| population_as_of    = 30 June 2015\n| pop_density_footnotes = \n| population_demonym  = Aresini\n| elevation_footnotes = \n| elevation_m         = 160\n| twin1               = \n| twin1_country       = \n| saint               = Ss. Pietro e Paolo\n\n| day                 = \n| postal_code         = 20020\n| area_code           = 02\n| website             = {{official website|http://www.comune.arese.mi.it/}}\n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Arese''' ({{lang-lmo|Ares}} {{IPA-lmo|a\u02c8re\u02d0s|}}) is a ''[[comune]]'' (municipality) in the [[Metropolitan City of Milan]] in the [[Italy|Italian]] region [[Lombardy]], located about {{convert|12|km|mi|0}} northwest of [[Milan]].\n\nArese borders the following municipalities: [[Lainate]], [[Garbagnate Milanese]], [[Bollate]], [[Rho (Italy)|Rho]], [[Milan]].\n\nArese received the honorary title of city with a presidential decree of October 25, 1985.\n\nFor what concerns the historical center, of particular interest is the [[Church of St. Peter and Paul, Arese|Church of St. Peter and Paul]], located in the city center.\n\n== Alfa Romeo ==\n[[File:AlfaRomeoAreseTec1.jpg|thumb|left|The Technical Center of Alfa Romeo in 2011.]]\nStarting in 1960, Arese hosted the main seat of [[Alfa Romeo]], partly in the territories of [[Lainate]] and [[Garbagnate Milanese]]. After three years of construction, the [[Alfa Romeo Arese Plant]] first began vehicle production in 1963, which would continue for decades, becoming the biggest production facility for Alfa Romeo. The factory became known simply as \"Arese\" as most of the industrial area and its main entrance are in this municipality. Following a gradual decrease in production activities, the factory finished manufacturing activities in 2005. Today the factory is almost totally closed and abandoned, since the Alfa Romeo owners ([[FIAT]]) have almost completely moved design and production to other factories inside and outside [[Italy]]. The few remaining employees (about 500) have often demonstrated against their dismissal. At the moment, most of the factory buildings are abandoned and the local administrations are looking for projects to use the huge area in a proper way, given its location. Arese and the factory are in fact very close to the newest services of [[Milan]] town, such as the [[High-speed rail in Italy|high speed railway]] and the new exhibition centre [[FieraMilano]].\n\n=== Historical Museum ===\n{{main|Alfa Romeo Museum}}\nOne of the few activities which is still located in the Alfa Romeo old factories is the Museo Storico Alfa Romeo, which is hosted in a dedicated building of great architectural value. In early 2011, Fiat announced the closure of the museum for renovations after the Ministry for Cultural Activities had declared the building and the collection of national cultural interest, on Arese municipality's request. \nAfter four years, the museum officially reopened in June 2015.\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\nArese is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n* {{flagicon|HUN}} [[Mosonmagyar\u00f3v\u00e1r]], Hungary (1989)\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Campolieto]], Italy (2006)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.comune.arese.mi.it/}} {{in lang|it}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.alfaromeo.com|Alfa Romeo official website}}\n* [https://www.museoalfaromeo.com Museo Storico Alfa Romeo]\n\n{{clear}}\n{{Province of Milan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Alfa Romeo]]\n\n\n{{Milan-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nicsimares", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arese"}
{"title_page": "Pamela Nadell", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|American historian and academic}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Pamela Nadell\n| image              = Pamela Nadell (Capitol Jewish Museum).png\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place        = [[Newark, New Jersey]], US\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Historian, Researcher, Author, and Lecturer\n| alma_mater         = [[Rutgers University|State University of New Jersey]] (BA)<br/>[[Ohio State University]] (MA), (PhD)\n| workplaces          = [[American University]]\n| thesis_title        = The Journey to America by Steam: The Jews of Eastern Europe in Transition\n| thesis_year        = 1982\n|awards=[[List of winners of the National Jewish Book Award|National Jewish Book Award]] (2019)\n}}\n\n'''Pamela S. Nadell''' (born 1951) is an [[Americans|American]] [[historian]], researcher, [[author]], and [[lecturer]] focusing on [[Jewish history]]. Former President of the [[Association for Jewish Studies]], she currently holds the Patrick Clendenen Chair in [[Women's history|Women's]] and [[Gender history|Gender History]] at [[American University]]. Nadell has focused her research on Jewish women and their role within Jewish history as well as in shaping the history of the [[United States]] through their role in various [[Social movement|social]] and [[Political movement|political movements]].\n\n== Life and education ==\nNadell was born to Alice and Irwin M. Nadell in 1951 and grew up in [[Livingston, New Jersey]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=America's Jewish Women: A History from Colonial Times to Today|last=Nadell|first=Pamela|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2019|isbn=9780393651249|location=New York|pages=|chapter=Introduction}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from [[Livingston High School (New Jersey)|Livingston High School]] in 1969,<ref name=\"Award\"/> she attended [[Douglass Residential College|Douglass College]] of Rutgers, the [[Rutgers University|State University of New Jersey]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Area students receive degrees from Rutgers |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/528529899/?terms=%22Pamela%2BNadell%22 |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=The Herald-News |date=June 7, 1973 |location=Passaic, New Jersey |page=38}}</ref> where she majored in [[Hebraic studies|Hebraic Studies]] graduating with high honors.<ref name=\"Award\"/> Nadell spent her junior year abroad studying at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem|Hebrew University]] in [[Jerusalem]].<ref name=\"Award\"/>\n\nShe continued her studies at [[Ohio State University]] where she earned her Masters in Jewish History (1976) and doctorate in American Jewish History (1982).<ref name=\"Award\"/> While completing her doctorate on Eastern-European Jewish Migration patterns, Nadell received a fellowship from the [[American Jewish Archives]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Endelman Appointed Archives Fellow |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/530325872/?terms=%22Pamela%2BNadell%22 |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=The American Israelite |date=January 29, 1981 |location=Cincinnati, Ohio |page=P11}}</ref> and was honored by Ohio State President, [[Harold Leroy Enarson|Harold Enarson]], for her excellence as a teaching assistant.<ref name=\"Award\">{{Cite news|url=https://jhsnj-archives.org/?a=d&d=A19810611-NewJerseyJewishNews-19810611-01.1.40|title=Student Gets Teaching Award|last=|first=|date=June 11, 1981|work=New Jersey Jewish News|access-date=|page=40}}</ref>\n\n== Scholarship ==\nNadell's scholarship focuses on American Jewish history, especially the history of American Jewish women. \n\nIn 1995, she was guest editor of an issue of ''[[American Jewish History]]'' devoted to research about women.<ref name=\"Sorin\">{{cite journal |last1=Sorin |first1=Gerald |title=Women and American Judaism: Historical Perspectives/American Jewish Women's History: A Reader |journal=Jewish Quarterly Review |date=Spring 2005 |volume=95 |issue=2 |pages=413\u2013417 |doi=10.1353/jqr.2005.0026 |issn=0021-6682}}</ref> She subsequently edited volumes including ''Women and American Judaism:  Historical  Perspectives'' (2001; with Jonathan D. Sarna),<ref name=\"Sorin\" /><ref name=\"Orleck\">{{cite journal |last1=Orleck |first1=Annelise |title=Women and American Judaism (Book) |journal=Journal of American Ethnic History |date=Winter 2003 |volume=22 |issue=2 |page=94 |issn=0278-5927}}</ref> and ''American  Jewish  Women's  History:  A  Reader'',<ref name=\"Sorin\" />  and authored others, including ''Women Who Would be Rabbis: A History of Women's Ordination'' and ''America's Jewish Women: A History from Colonial Times to Today.''  \n\nHer work brings to the fore Jewish women previously ignored in most history books.<ref name=\"worldreligionnews_2019-04-25\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldreligionnews.com/religion-news/american-jewish-women-shaped-american-culture-interview-pamela-s-nadell|title=How American Jewish Women Shaped American Culture: An Interview with Pamela S. Nadell|date=2019-04-25|website=World Religion News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425173714/https://www.worldreligionnews.com/religion-news/american-jewish-women-shaped-american-culture-interview-pamela-s-nadell|archive-date=2019-04-25|url-status=live}}</ref>  She highlights the roles women have played in changing historically set precedents. In doing so she has publicized the names of the first women to push against the established male-only rabbinates of the United States,<ref name=\"Stetler\">{{cite news |last1=Stetler |first1=Kristin E. |title=Women in the rabbinate |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/554229857/?terms=%22Pamela%2BNadell%22 |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=York Daily Record |date=November 19, 1997 |pages=1C, 2C}}</ref> tracing the origins of that debate in the late 19th century to an 1889 short story in  the [[The Jewish Exponent|''Jewish Exponent'']], \"A Problem for Purim,\" by the journalist [[Mary M. Cohen]], a member of the historic [[Philadelphia]] synagogue, [[Congregation Mikveh Israel]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ashton|first=Dianne|date=1999|title=Book Reviews: Pamela S. Nadell, Women who Would be Rabbis|url=http://americanjewisharchives.org/publications/journal/PDF/1999_51_01_02_reviews.pdf|journal=The American Jewish Archives Journal|volume=51|pages=155\u2013158|access-date=2019-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617133624/http://americanjewisharchives.org/publications/journal/PDF/1999_51_01_02_reviews.pdf|archive-date=2019-06-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />  \n\nDedicating her work to advancing the scholarship laid down by historians of women's history, Nadell has ventured to explore the means in which women traditionally shut out of religious spaces continue to assert influence within and outside the religious domain.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Schneider|first=Rabbi Ilene|date=2000|title=Review of Women Who Would Be Rabbis: A History of Women's Ordination. 1889-1985|journal=Contemporary Jewry|volume=21|issue=1|pages=147\u2013148|issn=0147-1694|jstor=23455325}}</ref>\n\nIn ''America's Jewish Women: A History from Colonial Times to Today,'' religion becomes only one of the diverse commitments and activities of Jewish women. In this groundbreaking history, Nadell shows two threads binding the nation's Jewish women: a powerful sense of self and a deep commitment to making the world a better place.<ref name=\"Rothstein\">{{cite journal |last1=Rothstein |first1=Jane H. |title=American Jewish Women's History: A Reader (Book) |journal=History: Reviews of New Books |date=2004 |volume=32 |issue=2 |page=46 |doi=10.1080/03612759.2004.10528544}}</ref>  \n\nInformed by the shared values of America's founding and Jewish identity, Nadell highlights Jewish women's activism in the history of the nation they came to call home, from the 18th to the 20th century.<ref name=\"Rothstein\" />  She writes about the colonial era matriarch [[Grace Nathan]] and Nathan's great-granddaughter poet [[Emma Lazarus]], about labor organizer [[Bessie Abramowitz Hillman|Bessie Hillman]], and about Supreme Court Justice [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]]. \n\nShe discusses Jewish women's activism in the [[Labor rights|labor]], [[Birth control movement in the United States|birth control]], [[Women's suffrage|suffrage]], [[Civil rights movement|civil rights]],<ref name=\"Rothstein\" /> and [[Feminist movement|feminist movements]].<ref name=\"Rothstein\" />  She also discusses sexual assaults of [[sweatshop]] workers during the mid-20th century, as well as the hardships many women would endure as [[Agunah|agunot,]] women whose husbands cannot or will not grant them a religious divorce who can never remarry under Jewish law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-393-65123-2|title=America's Jewish Women: A History from Colonial Times to Today|date=2019-01-10|website=Publishers Weekly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503171645/https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-393-65123-2|archive-date=2019-05-03|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Role in public life ==\nNadell has shared her knowledge of Jewish women in America with the [[National Museum of American Jewish History]] in Philadelphia, including the stories of success highlighted in the \"Only In America\" gallery.<ref name=\"Denlinger\">{{cite news |last1=Denlinger |first1=Elizabeth |title=Jewish Museums Leave Nostalgia In The Dust |url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/jewish-museums-leave-nostalgia-in-the-dust/ |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=The New York Jewish Week |date=January 13, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714162555/https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/jewish-museums-leave-nostalgia-in-the-dust/ |archive-date=July 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter being elected in 2014, Nadell served as president of the [[Association for Jewish Studies]] from 2015 to 2017.<ref name=\"President\"/> While president, Nadell wrote an [[open letter]] to Hungarian President [[Zolt\u00e1n Balog (politician)|Zolt\u00e1n Balog]] in opposition of the controversial amendments being made to the [[Central European University#CEU and the Amendment to the National Higher Education law|National Higher Education Law]].<ref name=\"President\"/><ref name=\"Hungarian\">{{cite letter|first=Pamela|last=Nadell|recipient=Zolt\u00e1n Balog|subject=Letter to the Hungarian government|language=English|date=April 4, 2017|url=https://www.associationforjewishstudies.org/docs/default-source/letters-from-the-board/ajs-aajr-ceu-letter.pdf?sfvrsn=2|access-date=May 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622220116/https://www.associationforjewishstudies.org/docs/default-source/letters-from-the-board/ajs-aajr-ceu-letter.pdf?sfvrsn=2|archive-date=June 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The amendment would increase obstacles to universities operating outside [[European Union|European Union (EU)]] countries with sister-schools inside the EU. In her letter, Nadell expressed concern that such obstacles would encumber scholarship coming out of the [[Budapest]]-based [[Central European University]].<ref name=\"Hungarian\"/>\n\nNadell penned another letter as president, along with the Association for Jewish Studies executive board to Israeli ambassador to the United States [[Ron Dermer]] expressing concern over amendments made to the Israeli [[Amendment No. 28 to the Entry Into Israel Law|Entry into Israel Law]].<ref name=\"President\">{{cite journal |last1=Nadell |first1=Pamela S. |title=From the President. 2017 Transitions |journal=AJS News |date=2017 |url=https://www.associationforjewishstudies.org/publications-research/ajs-news/2017-transitions |accessdate=June 22, 2019 |publisher=Association for Jewish Studies |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622220104/https://www.associationforjewishstudies.org/publications-research/ajs-news/2017-transitions |archive-date=June 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The law would prohibit the issuing of visas to foreign nationals who have made \"public calls for boycotting Israel.\" For Nadell, who herself identifies as a [[Freedom of speech|free-speech advocate]], an attempt to suppress the speech of others would be seen as a deep concern.<ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\n\nNadell voiced similar free-speech concerns in 2017 before the House Judiciary Committee during a hearing on [[Antisemitism in the United States#Antisemitism on college campuses|antisemitism on college campuses]]. The hearing would come as Members of Congress debated adding language to a proposed bill defining [[antisemitism]] as language which would  \"demonize, delegitimize, or apply a double standard to Israel.\"<ref name=\"Lilith\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lilith.org/blog/2017/11/why-the-president-of-the-jewish-studies-association-opposes-the-anti-semitism-awareness-act/|title=Why the President of the Jewish Studies Association Opposes the Anti-Semitism Awareness Act|last=Korn|first=Sandra|date=November 14, 2017|website=Lilith Magazine|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171120093154/http://lilith.org/blog/2017/11/why-the-president-of-the-jewish-studies-association-opposes-the-anti-semitism-awareness-act/|archive-date=November 20, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref> In her testimony, Nadell alleged that such a definition would only limit free speech,<ref name=\"Schultz\">{{cite news |last1=Schultz |first1=Marisa |title=Leaders clash over tougher protections for Jewish college students |url=https://nypost.com/2017/11/07/leaders-clash-over-tougher-protections-for-jewish-college-students/ |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=New York Post |date=November 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714162556/https://nypost.com/2017/11/07/leaders-clash-over-tougher-protections-for-jewish-college-students/ |archive-date=July 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kampeas |first1=Ron |title=It's Jew vs. Jew as Congress weighs a new definition for anti-Semitism |url=https://www.jta.org/2017/11/08/politics/barbs-fly-in-congress-as-proponents-opponents-of-law-codifying-anti-semitism-definition-face-off |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |date=November 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714162557/https://www.jta.org/2017/11/08/politics/barbs-fly-in-congress-as-proponents-opponents-of-law-codifying-anti-semitism-definition-face-off |archive-date=July 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and stated that Jewish students \"feel safe on campus\" without restrictions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Antisemitism on College Campuses: Pamela Nadell's Testimony |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4795878/pamela-nadells-testimony |website=[[C-SPAN Video Library]] |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n=== Books === <!--Books written by Nadell-->\n*{{Cite book|title=Conservative Judaism in America: A Biographical Dictionary and Sourcebook|last=|first=|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=1988|isbn=978-0313242052|location=New York|pages=|oclc=906507190}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Women Who Would Be Rabbis: A History of Women's Ordination, 1889\u20131985|last=|first=|publisher=Beacon Press|year=1999|isbn=9780807036495|location=Boston|pages=|oclc=604018015}}\n*{{Cite book|title=America's Jewish Women: A History from Colonial Times to Today|last=|first=|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2019|isbn=9780393651232|location=New York|pages=|oclc=1037810222}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://pamelanadell.com/ Official Website]\n*[https://www.american.edu/cas/faculty/pnadell.cfm Faculty Profile]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w_6eX0IrFl4 Testimony to House Judiciary Committee]\n{{AJS Presidents}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nadell, Pamela S.}}\n[[Category:American University faculty and staff]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Newark, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Livingston High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Livingston, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Historians of Jews and Judaism]]\n[[Category:Jewish historians]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish feminists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American historians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|American historian and academic}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Pamela Nadell\n| image              = Pamela Nadell (Capitol Jewish Museum).png\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place        = [[Newark, New Jersey]], US\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Historian, Researcher, Author, and Lecturer\n| alma_mater         = [[Rutgers University|State University of New Jersey]] (BA)<br/>[[Ohio State University]] (MA), (PhD)\n| workplaces          = [[American University]]\n| thesis_title        = The Journey to America by Steam: The Jews of Eastern Europe in Transition\n| thesis_year        = 1982\n|awards=[[List of winners of the National Jewish Book Award|National Jewish Book Award]] (2019)\n}}\n\n'''Pamela S. Nadell''' (born 1951) is an American historian, researcher, author, and lecturer focusing on Jewish history. Former President of the [[Association for Jewish Studies]], she currently holds the Patrick Clendenen Chair in Women's and Gender History at [[American University]]. Nadell has focused her research on Jewish women and their role within Jewish history as well as in shaping the history of the United States through their role in various social and political movements.\n\n== Life and education ==\nNadell was born to Alice and Irwin M. Nadell in 1951 and grew up in [[Livingston, New Jersey]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=America's Jewish Women: A History from Colonial Times to Today|last=Nadell|first=Pamela|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2019|isbn=9780393651249|location=New York|pages=|chapter=Introduction}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from [[Livingston High School (New Jersey)|Livingston High School]] in 1969,<ref name=\"Award\"/> she attended [[Douglass Residential College|Douglass College]] of Rutgers, the [[Rutgers University|State University of New Jersey]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Area students receive degrees from Rutgers |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/528529899/?terms=%22Pamela%2BNadell%22 |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=The Herald-News |date=June 7, 1973 |location=Passaic, New Jersey |page=38}}</ref> where she majored in Hebraic Studies graduating with high honors.<ref name=\"Award\"/> Nadell spent her junior year abroad studying at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem|Hebrew University]] in Jerusalem.<ref name=\"Award\"/>\n\nShe continued her studies at [[Ohio State University]] where she earned her Masters in Jewish History (1976) and doctorate in American Jewish History (1982).<ref name=\"Award\"/> While completing her doctorate on Eastern-European Jewish Migration patterns, Nadell received a fellowship from the [[American Jewish Archives]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Endelman Appointed Archives Fellow |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/530325872/?terms=%22Pamela%2BNadell%22 |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=The American Israelite |date=January 29, 1981 |location=Cincinnati, Ohio |page=P11}}</ref> and was honored by Ohio State President, [[Harold Leroy Enarson|Harold Enarson]], for her excellence as a teaching assistant.<ref name=\"Award\">{{Cite news|url=https://jhsnj-archives.org/?a=d&d=A19810611-NewJerseyJewishNews-19810611-01.1.40|title=Student Gets Teaching Award|last=|first=|date=June 11, 1981|work=New Jersey Jewish News|access-date=|page=40}}</ref>\n\n== Scholarship ==\nNadell's scholarship focuses on American Jewish history, especially this history of American Jewish women. In 1995, she was guest editor of an issue of ''[[American Jewish History]]'' devoted to research about women.<ref name=\"Sorin\">{{cite journal |last1=Sorin |first1=Gerald |title=Women and American Judaism: Historical Perspectives/American Jewish Women's History: A Reader |journal=Jewish Quarterly Review |date=Spring 2005 |volume=95 |issue=2 |pages=413\u2013417 |doi=10.1353/jqr.2005.0026 |issn=0021-6682}}</ref> She subsequently edited volumes including ''Women and American Judaism:  Historical  Perspectives'' (2001; with Jonathan D. Sarna),<ref name=\"Sorin\"/><ref name=\"Orleck\">{{cite journal |last1=Orleck |first1=Annelise |title=Women and American Judaism (Book) |journal=Journal of American Ethnic History |date=Winter 2003 |volume=22 |issue=2 |page=94 |issn=0278-5927}}</ref> and ''American  Jewish  Women's  History:  A  Reader'',<ref name=\"Sorin\"/>  and authored others, including ''Women Who Would be Rabbis: A History of Women's Ordination'' and ''America's Jewish Women: A History from Colonial Times to Today.''  Her work brings to the fore Jewish women previously ignored in most history books.<ref name=\"worldreligionnews_2019-04-25\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldreligionnews.com/religion-news/american-jewish-women-shaped-american-culture-interview-pamela-s-nadell|title=How American Jewish Women Shaped American Culture: An Interview with Pamela S. Nadell|date=2019-04-25|website=World Religion News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425173714/https://www.worldreligionnews.com/religion-news/american-jewish-women-shaped-american-culture-interview-pamela-s-nadell|archive-date=2019-04-25|url-status=live}}</ref>  She highlights the roles women have played in changing historically set precedents. In doing so she has publicized the names of the first women to push against the established male-only rabbinates of the United States,<ref name=\"Stetler\">{{cite news |last1=Stetler |first1=Kristin E. |title=Women in the rabbinate |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/554229857/?terms=%22Pamela%2BNadell%22 |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=York Daily Record |date=November 19, 1997 |pages=1C, 2C}}</ref> tracing the origins of that debate in the late 19th century to an 1889 short story in  the [[The Jewish Exponent|''Jewish Exponent'']], \"A Problem for Purim,\" by the journalist [[Mary M. Cohen]], a member of the historic Philadelphia synagogue, [[Congregation Mikveh Israel]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ashton|first=Dianne|date=1999|title=Book Reviews: Pamela S. Nadell, Women who Would be Rabbis|url=http://americanjewisharchives.org/publications/journal/PDF/1999_51_01_02_reviews.pdf|journal=The American Jewish Archives Journal|volume=51|pages=155\u2013158|access-date=2019-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617133624/http://americanjewisharchives.org/publications/journal/PDF/1999_51_01_02_reviews.pdf|archive-date=2019-06-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />  Dedicating her work to advancing the scholarship laid down by historians of women's history, Nadell has ventured to explore the means in which women traditionally shut out of religious spaces continue to assert influence within and outside the religious domain.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Schneider|first=Rabbi Ilene|date=2000|title=Review of Women Who Would Be Rabbis: A History of Women's Ordination. 1889-1985|journal=Contemporary Jewry|volume=21|issue=1|pages=147\u2013148|issn=0147-1694|jstor=23455325}}</ref>\n\nIn ''America's Jewish Women: A History from Colonial Times to Today,'' religion becomes only one of the diverse commitments and activities of Jewish women. In this groundbreaking history, Nadell shows two threads binding the nation's Jewish women: a powerful sense of self and a deep commitment to making the world a better place.<ref name=\"Rothstein\">{{cite journal |last1=Rothstein |first1=Jane H. |title=American Jewish Women's History: A Reader (Book) |journal=History: Reviews of New Books |date=2004 |volume=32 |issue=2 |page=46 |doi=10.1080/03612759.2004.10528544}}</ref>  Informed by the shared values of America's founding and Jewish identity, Nadell highlights Jewish women's activism in the history of the nation they came to call home, from the 18th to the 20th century.<ref name=\"Rothstein\"/>  She writes about the colonial era matriarch Grace Nathan and Nathan's great-granddaughter poet Emma Lazarus, about labor organizer Bessie Hillman, and about Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg. She discusses Jewish women's activism in the labor, birth control, suffrage, civil rights,<ref name=\"Rothstein\"/> and feminist movements.<ref name=\"Rothstein\"/>  She also discusses sexual assaults of [[sweatshop]] workers during the mid-20th century, as well as the hardships many women would endure as [[Agunah|agunot,]] women whose husbands cannot or will not grant them a religious divorce who can never remarry under Jewish law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-393-65123-2|title=America's Jewish Women: A History from Colonial Times to Today|date=2019-01-10|website=Publishers Weekly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503171645/https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-393-65123-2|archive-date=2019-05-03|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Role in public life ==\nNadell has shared her knowledge of Jewish women in America with the [[National Museum of American Jewish History]] in Philadelphia, including the stories of success highlighted in the \"Only In America\" gallery.<ref name=\"Denlinger\">{{cite news |last1=Denlinger |first1=Elizabeth |title=Jewish Museums Leave Nostalgia In The Dust |url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/jewish-museums-leave-nostalgia-in-the-dust/ |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=The New York Jewish Week |date=January 13, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714162555/https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/jewish-museums-leave-nostalgia-in-the-dust/ |archive-date=July 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter being elected in 2014, Nadell served as president of the [[Association for Jewish Studies]] from 2015 to 2017.<ref name=\"President\"/> While president, Nadell wrote an open letter to Hungarian President [[Zolt\u00e1n Balog (politician)|Zolt\u00e1n Balog]] in opposition of the controversial amendments being made to the [[Central European University#CEU and the Amendment to the National Higher Education law|National Higher Education Law]].<ref name=\"President\"/><ref name=\"Hungarian\">{{cite letter|first=Pamela|last=Nadell|recipient=Zolt\u00e1n Balog|subject=Letter to the Hungarian government|language=English|date=April 4, 2017|url=https://www.associationforjewishstudies.org/docs/default-source/letters-from-the-board/ajs-aajr-ceu-letter.pdf?sfvrsn=2|access-date=May 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622220116/https://www.associationforjewishstudies.org/docs/default-source/letters-from-the-board/ajs-aajr-ceu-letter.pdf?sfvrsn=2|archive-date=June 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The amendment would increase obstacles to universities operating outside [[European Union]] (EU) countries with sister-schools inside the EU. In her letter, Nadell expressed concern that such obstacles would encumber scholarship coming out of the Budapest-based [[Central European University]].<ref name=\"Hungarian\"/>\n\nNadell penned another letter as president, along with the Association for Jewish Studies executive board to Israeli ambassador to the United States [[Ron Dermer]] expressing concern over amendments made to the Israeli [[Amendment No. 28 to the Entry Into Israel Law|Entry into Israel Law]].<ref name=\"President\">{{cite journal |last1=Nadell |first1=Pamela S. |title=From the President. 2017 Transitions |journal=AJS News |date=2017 |url=https://www.associationforjewishstudies.org/publications-research/ajs-news/2017-transitions |accessdate=June 22, 2019 |publisher=Association for Jewish Studies |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622220104/https://www.associationforjewishstudies.org/publications-research/ajs-news/2017-transitions |archive-date=June 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The law would prohibit the issuing of visas to foreign nationals who have made \"public calls for boycotting Israel.\" For Nadell, who herself identifies as a free-speech advocate, an attempt to suppress the speech of others would be seen as a deep concern.<ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\n\nNadell voiced similar free-speech concerns in 2017 before the House Judiciary Committee during a hearing on [[Antisemitism in the United States#Antisemitism on college campuses|antisemitism on college campuses]]. The hearing would come as Members of Congress debated adding language to a proposed bill defining antisemitism as language which would  \"demonize, delegitimize, or apply a double standard to Israel.\"<ref name=\"Lilith\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lilith.org/blog/2017/11/why-the-president-of-the-jewish-studies-association-opposes-the-anti-semitism-awareness-act/|title=Why the President of the Jewish Studies Association Opposes the Anti-Semitism Awareness Act|last=Korn|first=Sandra|date=November 14, 2017|website=Lilith Magazine|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171120093154/http://lilith.org/blog/2017/11/why-the-president-of-the-jewish-studies-association-opposes-the-anti-semitism-awareness-act/|archive-date=November 20, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref> In her testimony, Nadell alleged that such a definition would only limit free speech,<ref name=\"Schultz\">{{cite news |last1=Schultz |first1=Marisa |title=Leaders clash over tougher protections for Jewish college students |url=https://nypost.com/2017/11/07/leaders-clash-over-tougher-protections-for-jewish-college-students/ |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=New York Post |date=November 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714162556/https://nypost.com/2017/11/07/leaders-clash-over-tougher-protections-for-jewish-college-students/ |archive-date=July 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kampeas |first1=Ron |title=It's Jew vs. Jew as Congress weighs a new definition for anti-Semitism |url=https://www.jta.org/2017/11/08/politics/barbs-fly-in-congress-as-proponents-opponents-of-law-codifying-anti-semitism-definition-face-off |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |date=November 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714162557/https://www.jta.org/2017/11/08/politics/barbs-fly-in-congress-as-proponents-opponents-of-law-codifying-anti-semitism-definition-face-off |archive-date=July 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and stated that Jewish students \"feel safe on campus\" without restrictions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Antisemitism on College Campuses: Pamela Nadell's Testimony |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4795878/pamela-nadells-testimony |website=[[C-SPAN Video Library]] |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n=== Books === <!--Books written by Nadell-->\n*{{Cite book|title=Conservative Judaism in America: A Biographical Dictionary and Sourcebook|last=|first=|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=1988|isbn=978-0313242052|location=New York|pages=|oclc=906507190}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Women Who Would Be Rabbis: A History of Women's Ordination, 1889\u20131985|last=|first=|publisher=Beacon Press|year=1999|isbn=9780807036495|location=Boston|pages=|oclc=604018015}}\n*{{Cite book|title=America's Jewish Women: A History from Colonial Times to Today|last=|first=|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2019|isbn=9780393651232|location=New York|pages=|oclc=1037810222}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://pamelanadell.com/ Official Website]\n*[https://www.american.edu/cas/faculty/pnadell.cfm Faculty Profile]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w_6eX0IrFl4 Testimony to House Judiciary Committee]\n{{AJS Presidents}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nadell, Pamela S.}}\n[[Category:American University faculty and staff]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Newark, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Livingston High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Livingston, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Historians of Jews and Judaism]]\n[[Category:Jewish historians]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish feminists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American historians]]\n", "name_user": "Lemieuxn", "label": "safe", "comment": "internal linking and minor edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pamela_Nadell"}
{"title_page": "Asticlian Gambit", "text_new": "{{DnDmodule| module_title = ''Asticlian Gambit''\n|module_image = [[Image:DSQ3 TSR2412 Asticlian Gambit.jpeg|250px]]\n|module_code = DSQ3\n|module_rules = \n|module_character_levels = \n|module_campaign = \n|module_authors = \n|module_first_published = 1992\n|series = \n}}\n\n'''''Asticlian Gambit''''' is an adventure for the 2nd edition of the ''[[Dungeons & Dragons|Advanced Dungeons & Dragons]]'' [[fantasy]] [[role-playing game]], published in 1992.\n\n==Contents==\n{{Empty section|date=June 2011}}\n\n==Publication history==\n{{Empty section|date=June 2011}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n\nIt sounded like \u2018Ass-Tickling-gambit\u2019, and was rather popular with teenagers for that reason.\n\n==Reviews==\n*''White Wolf'' #36\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{D&D topics}}\n\n[[Category:Dark Sun]]\n\n\n{{D&D-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{DnDmodule| module_title = ''Asticlian Gambit''\n|module_image = [[Image:DSQ3 TSR2412 Asticlian Gambit.jpeg|250px]]\n|module_code = DSQ3\n|module_rules = \n|module_character_levels = \n|module_campaign = \n|module_authors = \n|module_first_published = 1992\n|series = \n}}\n\n'''''Asticlian Gambit''''' is an adventure for the 2nd edition of the ''[[Dungeons & Dragons|Advanced Dungeons & Dragons]]'' [[fantasy]] [[role-playing game]], published in 1992.\n\n==Contents==\n{{Empty section|date=June 2011}}\n\n==Publication history==\n{{Empty section|date=June 2011}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{Empty section|date=June 2011}}\n\n==Reviews==\n*''White Wolf'' #36\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{D&D topics}}\n\n[[Category:Dark Sun]]\n\n\n{{D&D-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2601:185:8300:7a0:586a:30ad:2971:8dab", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReception:Removed the tag for a section being empty)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asticlian_Gambit"}
{"title_page": "Immigration to Mexico", "text_new": "[[File:Naturalizados Mexicanos.jpg|thumbnail|250px|Immigrants at a [[naturalization]] ceremony in [[Los Pinos]].]]\nSince the early sixteenth century with the [[Spanish conquest of the Aztec empire|Spanish conquest]], [[Mexico]] has received immigrants from Europe, Africa (as colonial-era enslaved immigrants), the Americas (e.g., the United States, Canada, Colombia, Guatemala, Argentina, Honduras, Cuba, Brazil and El Salvador), the Middle East and from Asia. Today, millions of their descendants still live in Mexico and can be found working in different professions and industries. According to the 2010 [[Censo General de Poblaci\u00f3n y Vivienda|National Census]], there are 961,121 foreign-born people registered with the government as living in Mexico, the majority of whom are US citizens.<ref name=\"inegi.gob.mx\">{{cite web|url=http://www.inegi.gob.mx/inegi/contenidos/espanol/prensa/contenidos/Articulos/sociodemograficas/nacidosenotropais.pdf |title=Conociendonos todos |publisher=INEGI |accessdate=October 30, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130427100913/http://www.inegi.gob.mx/inegi/contenidos/espanol/prensa/contenidos/Articulos/sociodemograficas/nacidosenotropais.pdf |archivedate=April 27, 2013 }}</ref> This is almost double the 492,617 foreign-born residents counted in the 2000 Census.<ref name=\"inegi.gob.mx\" /> According to the [[intercensal estimate]] conducted in 2015, the foreign-born population was 1,007,063.<ref>{{cite web|title=Principales resultados de la Encuesta Intercensal 2015 Estados Unidos Mexicanos |url=http://www.inegi.org.mx/est/contenidos/proyectos/encuestas/hogares/especiales/ei2015/doc/eic2015_resultados.pdf |publisher=[[INEGI]] |accessdate=9 December 2015 |pages=1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210212235/http://www.inegi.org.mx/est/contenidos/proyectos/encuestas/hogares/especiales/ei2015/doc/eic2015_resultados.pdf |archivedate=10 December 2015 }}</ref> In 2017, the [[United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs|UN DESA]] Population Division gave a foreign born population in Mexico of 1,224,169.<ref name=\"UN2017\">{{cite web|title=Table 1: Total migrant stock at mid-year by origin and by major area, region, country or area of destination, 2017|url=http://www.un.org/en/development/desa/population/migration/data/estimates2/data/UN_MigrantStockByOriginAndDestination_2017.xlsx|publisher=United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs, Population Division |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref> Unofficial estimates put the total number of foreigners in Mexico closer to four million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Opini\u00f3n: \u00bfM\u00e9xico es un destino de inmigraci\u00f3n global?|url=http://www.adnpolitico.com/opinion/2013/10/07/opinion-auge-migratorio#comentarios|publisher=ADN Pol\u00edtico|accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> More than 45,000 migrants from [[Central America]] were deported from Mexico between January and April 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump announces tariffs on Mexico over immigration |url=https://thehill.com/latino/446269-trump-announces-5-percent-tariff-on-imports-from-mexico-starting-june-10 |work=The Hill |date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Immigration policy ==\n{{see also|Mexican nationality law}}\n[[File:Ni\u00f1os polacos de Santa Rosa, Guanajuato.jpg|thumbnail|Orphaned Polish children in Guanajuato that arrived with a larger group of refugees during the [[Second World War]].]]\n\nWith the Mexican government's intent to control migration flows and attract foreigners who can contribute to economic development, the new migration law simplifies foreigners\u2019 entrance and residency requirements. It replaces the two large immigration categories\u2014immigrant and nonimmigrant\u2014with the categories of \u201cvisitor\u201d and \u201ctemporary resident\u201d, while keeping the status of \u201cpermanent resident\u201d. In the General Law of Population the two categories incorporate over 30 different types of foreigners\u2014i.e. distinguished visitor, religious minister, etc.\u2014each with its own stipulations and requirements to qualify for entry and stay. Under the new law the requirements are simplified, basically differentiating those foreigners who are allowed to work and those who are not. The law also expedites the permanent resident application process for retirees and other foreigners. For granting permanent residency, the law proposes using a point system based on factors such as level of education, employment experience, and scientific and technological knowledge.<ref>Gonzalez-Murphy, Laura. \"Protecting Immigrant Rights in Mexico: Understanding the State-Civil Society Nexus,\"  Routledge, New York, Forthcoming 2013</ref>\n\nAccording to Article 81 of the Law and Article 70 of the regulations to the law\u2014published on 28 September 2012\u2014 immigration officials are the only ones that can conduct immigration procedures although the Federal Police may assist but only under the request and guidance of the Institute of Migration. Verification procedures cannot be conducted in migrant shelters run by civil society organizations or by individuals that engage in providing humanitarian assistance to immigrants.\n\nUndocumented immigration has been a problem for Mexico, especially since the 1970s. Although the number of deportations is declining with 61,034 registered cases in 2011, the Mexican government documented over 200,000 unauthorized border crossings in 2004 and 2005.<ref>\"Estad\u00edsticas\"</ref> In 2011, 93% of undocumented immigrants in Mexico came from three countries -[[Guatemala]], [[Honduras]] and [[El Salvador]]- however, there is an increasing number of immigrants from [[Asia]] and [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Indios, chinos, somal\u00edes\u2026 as\u00ed son los migrantes invisibles de M\u00e9xico|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mundo/noticias/2011/07/110722_mexico_migrantes_indios_chinos_irm.shtml|publisher=BBC Mundo|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== History of immigration policy ===\n[[File:Inmigraci\u00f3n en M\u00e9xico 2015.png|thumb|400px|right|<center>Immigrants in [[M\u00e9xico]], census [[OCDE]] 2015.<ref>[http://www.oecd.org/document/51/0,3343,en_2649_33931_34063091_1_1_1_1,00.html Immigrants in Mexico, census OCDE 2000] OCDE</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Japanese immigrants in Sonora.jpg|thumbnail|[[Japanese immigration to Mexico|Japanese]] immigrant workers at the mine of [[Cananea]], Sonora in the 1910s. The Japanese, unlike other Asian immigrants, came from a politically strong nation and were seen as industrious, so they were exempt from the discriminatory immigration policies.]]\n\nOverview of Mexican immigration policy in regards to ethnicity or nationality:\n\n* 1823 - Permanent settlement and naturalization is restricted to Catholics<ref name=FitzGerald>{{cite book|last1=FitzGerald|first1=David Scott|last2=Cook-Mart\u00edn|first2=David|title=Culling the Masses|date=2014|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=0674729048|page=220|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wXWWAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA219&dq=Culling+the+Masses+Mexico+table+6.1#v=onepage&q=Culling%20the%20Masses%20Mexico%20table%206.1&f=false|accessdate=16 December 2015}}</ref> (see also [[General Colonization Law]])\n* 1860 - Catholic favoritism ends with the establishment of freedom of religion<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1909 - First comprehensive immigration law rejects racial discrimination (enacted under the [[Porfiriato|Porfirian regime]], but ignored by the governments that followed the [[Mexican Revolution]])<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1917 - Shorter naturalization times for Latin Americans<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1921 - Confidential circular, followed by an accord between China and Mexico, restricts [[Chinese immigration to Mexico|Chinese immigration]]<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1923 - Confidential circular excludes [[Indian immigration to Mexico|Indians]]<ref name=FitzGerald /> (these confidential circulars were kept secretive in order to avoid diplomatic problems, such as with the British Empire or the United States)\n* 1924 - Confidential circular excludes [[Afro-Mexicans|blacks]]<ref name=FitzGerald /> (in practice, it excluded working class Afro-Latin Americans, but not elites)\n* 1926 - Confidential circular excludes [[Romani people in Mexico|gypsies]]<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1926 - Exclusion of those who \"constitute a danger of physical degeneration for our race\"<ref name=FitzGerald /> (see also [[Blanqueamiento#Blanqueamiento and national policy|Blanqueamiento and national policy]])\n* 1927 - Exclusion of Palestinians, [[Arab Mexicans|Arabs]], Syrians, [[Lebanese immigration to Mexico|Lebanese]], [[Armenian immigration to Mexico|Armenians]] and [[Turks in Mexico|Turks]]<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1929 - Confidential circular excludes [[Polish immigration to Mexico|Poles]] and [[Russian immigration to Mexico|Russians]]<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1931 - Confidential circular excludes Hungarians<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1933 - Exclusion or restrictions of blacks, Malays, Indians, the 'yellow race' (East Asians, except Japanese), Soviets, gypsies, Poles, Lithuanians, [[Czech immigration to Mexico|Czechs]], Slovacks, Syrians, Lebanese, Palestinians, Armenians, Arabs and Turks.<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1934 - Exclusion or restrictions extended to Aboriginals, Latvians, Bulgarians, Romanians, Persians, Yugoslavs, [[Greek immigration to Mexico|Greeks]], Albanians, Afghans, Ethiopians, Algerians, Egyptians, Moroccans and [[Judaism in Mexico|Jews]].<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1937 - Quotas establishes unlimited immigration from the Americas and Spain; 5,000 annual slots for each of thirteen Western European nationalities and the Japanese; and 100 slots for nationals of each other country of the world.<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1939 - Shorter naturalization times for [[Spanish Mexican|Spaniards]]<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1947 - Law rejects racial discrimination, but promotes a preference for \"assimilable\" foreigners<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1974 - Law eliminates assimilability as a gauge for admission<ref name=FitzGerald />\n* 1993 - Shorter naturalization times for [[Portuguese Mexican|Portuguese]]<ref name=FitzGerald /> (granted to Latin Americans and Iberians due to historical and cultural connections; requires two years of residence instead of five)\n\n=== Temporary Migrant Regularization Program ===\n[[File:Avenida_L\u00edbano,_M\u00e9rida,_Yucat\u00e1n_(01).JPG|thumb|right|250px|Avenida L\u00edbano (Avenue Libano) in [[M\u00e9rida, Yucat\u00e1n|M\u00e9rida]], [[Yucat\u00e1n]].]]\nThe ''Programa Temporal de Regularizaci\u00f3n Migratoria'' (PTRM) published on 12 January 2015 in the [[Official Journal of the Federation (Mexico)|Diario Oficial de la Federaci\u00f3n]], is directed at those foreigners who have made their permanent residence in Mexico but due to 'diverse circumstances' did not regularize their stay in the country and find themselves turning to 'third parties' to perform various procedures, including finding employment.<ref name=PTRM>{{cite web|title=Programa Temporal de Regularizaci\u00f3n Migratoria|url=http://www.inm.gob.mx/index.php/page/regularizacion_migratoria|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402101002/http://www.inm.gob.mx/index.php/page/regularizacion_migratoria|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 April 2015|publisher=[[Instituto Nacional de Migraci\u00f3n]]|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Inmigraci\u00f3n_En_M\u00e9xico_2010.png|thumb|left|250px|Immigration to Mexico 2010]]\nThe program is aimed at foreign nationals who entered the country before 9 November 2012.<ref name=PTRM /> Approved foreigners received through the PTRM the status of '[[temporary resident]]', document valid for four years,<ref name=PTRM /> and are eligible afterwards for [[permanent residency]].<ref name=\"PTRM 2017\" /> The temporary program ran from 13 January to 18 December 2015.<ref name=PTRM />\n\nIn accordance with the provisions of Articles: 1, 2, 10, 18, 77, 126 and 133 of the ''Ley de Migraci\u00f3n''; 1 and 143 of the ''Reglamento de la Ley de Migraci\u00f3n'', any foreign national wishing to regularize their immigration status within Mexican territory, under the PTRM will complete the payment of fees for the following:\n\nI. Proof of payment for receiving and examining the application of the procedure... ... [[MXN]] 1124.00 ([[USD]] 77.14 as of 12 January 2015)\n\nII. For the issuance of the certificate giving them the status of temporary stay for four years ...... MXN 7914.00 (US$514.17)\n\nThrough Article 16 of the ''Ley Federal de Derechos'', foreign national are exempt them from payment if it can be proven that they earn a wage at or below [[minimum wage]].<ref name=PTRM /> During the period that the PTRM is in effect, no fine is applied (as is the practice otherwise).<ref name=PTRM />\n\nThe PTRM was reenacted on 11 October 2016; eligibility was extended to undocumented migrants that entered the country before 9 January 2015.<ref name=\"PTRM 2017\">{{cite web|title=Apoya el INM a extranjeros a que regularicen su situaci\u00f3n migratoria, a trav\u00e9s del PTRM|url=http://www.gob.mx/inm/prensa/apoya-el-inm-a-extranjeros-a-que-regularicen-su-situacion-migratoria-a-traves-del-ptrm|website=gob.mx|language=es}}</ref> Migrants are assured that they will not be detained nor deported when inquiring for information or submitting their application at an INM office.<ref name=\"PTRM 2017\" /> Identification and proof of residency/entry date (such as bus or airplane tickets, utility bills, school records or expired visas) should be presented. If these proofs can not be provided, the legal testimony of two Mexicans/resident foreigners may also be accepted. The program runs until 19 December 2017.<ref name=\"PTRM 2017\" />\n\n== Public opinion ==\nThe 2019 survey found that 58% of Mexican respondents oppose immigration from Central America.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shocking photo of drowned father and daughter highlights migrants' border peril |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jun/25/photo-drowned-migrant-daughter-rio-grande-us-mexico-border |work=The Guardian |date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Immigrant groups in Mexico==\n[[File:Ni\u00f1os armenio-mexicanos 1911.jpg|thumbnail|Second generation [[Armenian Mexican]] children in 1911.]]\nImmigrants arrive in Mexico for many reasons, most of the documented immigrants have arrived for economic and/or work-related reasons. Many, such as executives, professionals, scientists, artists, or athletes working for either Mexican or foreign companies, arrive with secure jobs. Retirement is the main motivation for immigrants who tend to be more permanent. Aside from dual national descendants of Mexicans, naturalized Mexicans, or the undocumented, 262,672 foreign residents live on its soil. The majority of its foreign residents are from the U.S. followed by Spain and Guatemala.\n\n=== North American ===\n==== American ====\n{{main|American immigration to Mexico{{!}}American Mexican}}\nThe largest number of Americans outside the United States live in Mexico. According to Mexico 2010 Census, there are 738,103 Americans living in the Mexican Republic,<ref name=inegi.gob.mx /> while the US Embassy in Mexico City has at times given an estimate closer to 1 million (the disparity is due to non-permanent residents, notably the \"[[Snowbird (person)|snowbirds]]\").{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} Mostly, people who come from the USA are students, retirees, religious workers (missionaries, pastors, etc.), [[Mexican-American]]s, and spouses of Mexican citizens.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} A few are professors who come employed by Mexican companies to teach English, other English teachers, and corporate employees and executives.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nWhile significant numbers live in Mexico year round, it is probable that a majority of these residents do not stay the whole year.  Retirees may live half a year in the U.S. to keep retiree benefits.  Those called \"snowbirds\" come in fall and leave in spring. The American community in Mexico is found throughout the country, but there are significant concentrations of U.S. citizens in all the north of Mexico, especially in [[Tijuana]], [[Mexicali]], [[Los Cabos Municipality|Los Cabos]], [[San Carlos Nuevo Guaymas|San Carlos]], [[Mazatl\u00e1n]], [[Saltillo]], [[Monterrey]] and [[Nuevo Laredo]]. Also in the central parts of the country such as [[San Miguel de Allende]], [[Ajijic]], [[Chapala, Jalisco|Chapala]], [[Mexico City]] and [[Cuernavaca]], and along the Pacific coast, most especially in the greater [[Puerto Vallarta]] area. In the past few years, a growing American community has developed in [[M\u00e9rida, Yucat\u00e1n]].\n\n==== Central American ====\n[[File:Central american migrants mexico.jpg|thumbnail|235px|Transient migrants from Central America making their way to the U.S.-Mexico border. These migrants use a rail network known as ''[[El tren de la muerte|La Bestia]]'' to traverse Mexican territory.]]\nThe largest recent immigrant flows to Mexico are from Central America, with a total of 66,868 immigrants from Guatemala, Honduras, Belize, El Salvador, Costa Rica, Panama and Nicaragua living in Mexico in 2010.<ref>Insituto Nacional de Migraci\u00f3n \u201cEstad\u00edsticas.\u201d 2012. {http://www.inm.gob.mx/index.php/page/Estadisticas_Migratorias}</ref>\n\nRecently, Mexico has also become a transit route for Central Americans and others (from the Caribbean, Africa, Asia and Eastern Europe)<ref>{{cite web|title=Haitians, After Perilous Journey, Find Door to U.S. Abruptly Shut|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/24/world/americas/haitians-mexico-brazil-deport-united-states.html?_r=0|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref> into the United States. 2014 was the first year since records began when more non-Mexicans than Mexicans were apprehended trying to enter the United States illegally through the U.S.-Mexico border.<ref name =\"Pew2014\">{{cite web|url= http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2014/12/30/u-s-border-apprehensions-of-mexicans-fall-to-historic-lows/ |title= U.S. border apprehensions of Mexicans fall to historic lows|publisher=Pew Research |accessdate= 5 January 2015}}</ref> Non-Mexicans (vast majority of whom are Central American) were up from about 68,000 in 2007 to 257,000 in 2014; Mexicans dropped from 809,000 to 229,000 during the same period.<ref name =\"Pew2014\"/>\n\nIn 2014, Mexico began to more heavily crackdown on these transient migrants.<ref name=Lakhani>{{cite web|last1=Lakhani|first1=Nina|title=Mexico deports record numbers of women and children in US-driven effort|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/feb/04/mexico-deports-record-numbers-women-children-central-america|website=The Guardian|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> According to Mexican officials, the ''Plan Frontera Sur'' (Southern Border Plan) is designed to retake control of the historically porous [[Guatemala\u2013Mexico border|southern border]] and protect migrants from [[Organized crime|transnational crime groups]].<ref name=Lakhani/> However, the measures have been widely attributed to pressure from the [[United States]], who does not want a repeat of 2014, when a surge of tens of thousands of women and children clogged up American immigration courts and resulted in a severe lack of space in detention centers at the [[US-Mexico border]].<ref name=Lakhani/> In January 2020, Mexico detained 800 migrants who entered it illegally from Guatemala to reach the United States as part of the strict measures taken by the Mexican authorities to reduce migration to the United States through Mexico.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-immigration-caravan-mexico-idUSKBN1ZM270|title=Mexican security forces detain 800 Central American migrants|date=2020-01-24|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-01-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Cuban ====\n{{main|Cuban Mexican}}\nCuban immigration to Mexico has been on the rise in recent years. A large number of them use Mexico as a route to the U.S., and Mexico has been deporting a large number of Cubans who attempt to. About 63,000 Cubans live in Mexico<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cubanet.org/colaboradores/mexico-para-cubanos-destino-o-transito/|title=M\u00e9xico para cubanos: \u00bfdestino o tr\u00e1nsito? CubanetCubanet|website=www.cubanet.org}}</ref> The number of registered Cuban residents increased 560% between 2010 and 2016, from 4,033 to 22,604 individuals. During the same period, there was a 710% increase in the Cuban presence in Quintana Roo; a fourth of the population (5,569 individuals) live in that state.\n\n=== South American ===\n==== Colombian ====\n{{main|Colombian Mexican}}\n[[File:Colombia_en_Mexico.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Cultures Fair Friends of Mexico City.]]\nIt is estimated that a total of 73,000 Colombians reside in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.colombianewyork.com/Colombianos_en_el_Mundo.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101012937/http://www.colombianewyork.com/Colombianos_en_el_Mundo.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-11-01 |title=Data|website=colombianewyork.com}}</ref> It was not until the 1970s when the presence of Colombians increased under the protection of political asylum as refugees by the Mexican government because of the Colombian guerrilla problems fleeing from their country during the 80s and many of them were protected and kept anonymous to avoid persecution.\n\n==== Argentines ====\n{{main|Argentine Mexican}}\nArgentine immigration to Mexico started in small waves during the 1970s, when they started escaping dictatorship and war in Argentina.\n\nCurrently, the Argentine community is one of the largest in Mexico, with about 13,000 documented residents living in Mexico. However, extra-official estimates range the number from 40,000 to 150,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.record.com.mx/articulo/noticias/1785664/argentinos-en-mexico-disfrutan-la-final|title=Argentinos en M\u00e9xico vivieron la Final - R\u00c9CORD|date=8 April 2015|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408053053/http://www.record.com.mx/articulo/noticias/1785664/argentinos-en-mexico-disfrutan-la-final|archivedate=8 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/coberturaespecial/argentinos/mexico/index.asp|title=Wayback Machine|date=22 December 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070217072117/http://www.lanacion.com.ar/coberturaespecial/argentinos/mexico/index.asp|archivedate=17 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Quintana Roo]], the number of Argentines doubled between 2011 and 2015, and now make a total of 10,000, making up the largest number of foreigners in the state<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sipse.com/novedades/argentinos-encabezan-poblacion-de-extranjeros-en-playa-del-carmen-133013.html|title=Argentinos encabezan poblaci\u00f3n de extranjeros en Playa del Carmen|first=Grupo|last=SIPSE|date=18 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWith two main emigrant waves; during the [[Dirty War|1970s Dirty War]] and after the [[1998\u20132002 Argentine great depression|2001 economic crisis]]. The largest Argentine community is in [[Mexico City]] (with a sizeable congregation in the [[Condesa]] neighborhood) and there are smaller communities in Leon, Guadalajara, Puebla, Cancun, Playa del Carmen, Tulum, M\u00e9rida, Monterrey and Tampico. Most Argentines established in Mexico come from the provinces of Buenos Aires, Santa Fe, Cordoba and Tucuman. The Argentine community has participated in the opening of establishments such as restaurants, bars, boutiques, modeling consultants, foreign exchange interbank markets, among other lines of business.\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n{{main|Venezuelan Mexicans}}\n[[File:Calle de Bolivar, en la Ciudad de M\u00e9xico.JPG|thumb|Visit plate from [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar]] in Mexico City.]]\nThe most recent influx of immigrants has resulted from the [[Bolivarian diaspora]], a diaspora occurring due to the adverse effects of the [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] and his [[Bolivarian Revolution]] in Venezuela. Compared to the 2000 Census, there has been an increase from the 2,823 Venezuelan Mexicans in 2000 to 10,063 in 2010, a 357% increase of Venezuelan-born individuals living in Mexico.<ref name=EHM>{{cite web|title=Estad\u00edsticas Hist\u00f3ricas de M\u00e9xico|url=http://www.inegi.gob.mx/prod_serv/contenidos/espanol/bvinegi/productos/integracion/pais/historicas10/Tema1_Poblacion.pdf|publisher=[[National Institute of Statistics and Geography (Mexico)|National Institute of Statistics and Geography]]|accessdate=2 June 2015|pages=83, 86|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201212345/http://www.inegi.gob.mx/prod_serv/contenidos/espanol/bvinegi/productos/integracion/pais/historicas10/Tema1_Poblacion.pdf|archive-date=1 February 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMexico granted 975 Venezuelans permanent identification cards in the first 5 months of 2014 alone, a number that doubled that of Venezuelans granted ID cards altogether in 2013 and a number that would have represented 35% of all Venezuelan Mexicans in Mexico in the year 2000.<ref name=REUT15oct>{{cite news|last1=Symmes Cobb|first1=Julia|last2=Garcia Rawlins|first2=Carlos|title=Economic crisis, political strife drive Venezuela brain-drain|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/10/15/us-venezuela-migration-idUSKCN0I41C820141015|accessdate=15 October 2014|agency=Reuters|date=15 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=EHM />\n\nDuring June 2016, Venezuelans surpassed [[American immigration to Mexico|Americans]] (historically, first) for number of new work visas granted.<ref name=\"Flores\">{{cite web|last1=Flores|first1=Zenyazen|title=Venezolanos desplazan  a EU con m\u00e1s permisos para trabajar en M\u00e9xico|url=http://m.elfinanciero.com.mx/economia/venezolanos-desplazan-a-eu-con-mas-permisos-para-trabajar-en-mexico.html|website=El Financiero|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref> The 1,183 visas granted in June were a 20% increase from the 981 granted in May.<ref name=\"Flores\"/> The main destinations are [[Mexico City]], [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]] and [[Tabasco]] (due to the state's petroleum industry).<ref name=\"Flores\"/>\n\n===European===\n[[File:Hoja de registro de ingreso de inmigrantes judios a Puebla - Expediente 9321.jpg|thumbnail|Immigrant registration form of a Jewish Lithuanian woman that emigrated to Mexico in 1934. The restrictions applied to Eastern Europeans did not completely eliminate migration of affected groups.]]\nAlthough Mexico never received massive European immigration after its [[Mexican War of Independence|independence]], over 1 million Europeans immigrated to Spanish America during the colonial period, which relative to the population of the time, could be said to have been massive European immigration. Although they were in their majority from Spain, other Europeans immigrated illegally. They migrated to [[Mexico]] for the most part, and to a lesser extent, [[Peru]]. They were called \"inmigrantes clandestinos\", of which 100,000 were Spanish.{{Citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nTowards the end of the [[Porfiriato]], there were an estimated 100,000 to 200,000 foreigners in the country.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Meyer|first1=Jean|title=Los franceses en Mexico durante el siglo XIX|publisher=El Colegio de Michoac\u00e1n|url=http://etzakutarakua.colmich.edu.mx/relaciones/002/pdf/JeanMeyer.pdf|accessdate=26 April 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106032808/http://etzakutarakua.colmich.edu.mx/relaciones/002/pdf/JeanMeyer.pdf|archivedate=6 January 2014|page=17}}</ref> The three largest groups were the Spanish, Americans and Chinese.\n\nFrom 1911 to 1931, 226,000 immigrants arrived in Mexico,<ref name=\"BailyM\u00edguez2003\">{{cite book|author1=Samuel L. Baily|author2=Eduardo Jos\u00e9 M\u00edguez|title=Mass Migration to Modern Latin America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZQxkfvMJFgC&pg=PR14|accessdate=16 January 2015|year=2003|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-8420-2831-8|page=xiv}}</ref> the majority of which were from Europe.\n\n==== British ====\n{{main|British Mexican}}\nThere are many Mexicans of [[English people|English]], [[Welsh people|Welsh]] and [[Scottish people|Scottish]] descent. According to Mexico's Migration Institute in 2009 there were 3,761 British expatriates living in Mexico.<ref name=\"Ch\u00e1vez 2012\">{{citation|url=http://www.politicamigratoria.gob.mx/work/models/SEGOB/CEM/PDF/Estadisticas/Poblacion_Extranjera/ExtranjerosResMex.pdf |first=Ernesto |last=Rodr\u00edguez Ch\u00e1vez |first2=Salvador |last2=Cobo |title=Extranjeros residentes en M\u00e9xico: Una aproximaci\u00f3n cuantitativa con base en los registros administrativos del INM |location=M\u00e9xico |publisher=[[National Institute of Migration (Mexico)|Institution Nacional de Migraci\u00f3n]] |year=2012 |accessdate=2013-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130612235537/http://www.politicamigratoria.gob.mx/work/models/SEGOB/CEM/PDF/Estadisticas/Poblacion_Extranjera/ExtranjerosResMex.pdf |archivedate=June 12, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n[[Cornish people|Cornish]] culture still survives in local architecture and food in the state of [[Hidalgo (state)|Hidalgo]]. The Scottish and Welsh have also made their mark in Mexico, especially in the states of [[Hidalgo (state)|Hidalgo]], [[Jalisco]], [[Aguascalientes]], and [[Veracruz]]. British immigrants formed the first [[Association football|football]] teams in Mexico in the late 19th century. Northern [[Spaniards]] of ''[[Celts|Celtic]]'' ancestry like the [[Asturians]], [[Galicians]], and [[Cantabrian people|Cantabrians]], have also left an imprint in Mexican culture and their languages formed many distinct accents in various regions in Mexico, especially in the central and northern states.\n\n==== French ====\n{{main|French Mexican}}\n[[File:EBoban.jpg|thumb|left|250px|A French antique dealer in Mexico City.]]\nMexico received immigration from France in waves in the 19th and 20th centuries. According to the 2010 census, there were 7,163 French nationals living in Mexico. According to the French consulate general, there are 30,000 French citizens in Mexico as of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/services-aux-citoyens/preparer-son-expatriation/dossiers-pays-de-l-expatriation/mexique-22685/|title=Mexique|website=France Diplomatie : : Minist\u00e8re de l'Europe et des Affaires \u00e9trang\u00e8res}}</ref>\n\nThe French language is often taught and studied in secondary public education and in universities throughout the country. French may also be heard occasionally in the state of [[Veracruz]] in the cities of [[Jicaltepec]], [[San Rafael, Veracruz|San Rafael]], [[Mentideros]], and [[Los Altos, Veracruz|Los Altos]], where the architecture and food is also very French. These immigrants came from [[Haute-Sa\u00f4ne|Haute-Sa\u00f4ne d\u00e9partement]] in France, especially from [[Champlitte]] and [[Bourgogne (disambiguation)|Bourgogne]]{{Clarify|reason=|date=November 2018}}.\n\nAnother French group were the \"''[[Barcelonnette|Barcelonettes]]''\" from the [[Alpes-de-Haute-Provence]] d\u00e9partement, who migrated specifically to Mexico to find jobs and work in merchandising and are well known in [[Mexico City]], [[Puebla]], [[Veracruz]] and [[Yucat\u00e1n (state)|Yucat\u00e1n]].\n\nAn important French village in Mexico is [[Santa Rosal\u00eda, Baja California Sur]], where the French culture/architecture are still found. Other French cultural traits are in a number of regional cultures such as the states of [[Jalisco]] and [[Sinaloa]].\n\nThe national folk music ''[[mariachi]]'' is thought to have been named after the French word for \"marriage\" when the music developed in wedding parties held by French landowning families. It is the legacy of settlers brought in during the [[Napoleon|Napoleonic-era]] French occupation is found in Guadalajara, Jalisco. The [[Second Mexican Empire]], created another trend of refuge for French settlers.\n\nFor the Emperor [[Maximilian I of Mexico]] from the Habsburg dynasty brought with him French, Austrian, Italian and Belgian troops, and after the fall of the Second Empire, most scattered through the area of the Empire. The descendants of these soldiers can be found in the state of [[Jalisco]] in the region called [[Los Altos de Jalisco]] and in many towns around this region and in [[Michoac\u00e1n]] in cities like [[Coalcom\u00e1n de V\u00e1zquez Pallares|Coalcom\u00e1n]], [[Aguililla]], [[Zamora, Michoac\u00e1n|Zamora]], and [[Cotija de la Paz|Cotija]].\n\nThese refugees intermixed with the [[Austrians]], [[Galicians]], [[Basques]], [[Cantabrian people|Cantabrians]], [[Italians]], and Mexicans in those areas of Michoac\u00e1n and Jalisco, as well as neighboring states.\n\nDuring World War II, tens of thousands of French expatriates from Mexico participated in the [[Free France|Free French Forces]] and the [[French Resistance]], including Mexican-born Lieutenant Rene Luis Campeon of French parentage, was thought to be the first in command to enter Paris during the [[Liberation of Paris]] from the retreating Nazis in August 1944.\n\nOther Francophone peoples include those from [[Belgium]] such as the [[Walloons]] and [[Romands|Franco-Swiss]] from [[Switzerland]]. The Belgians, started by the veteran Ch. Loomans, tried to establish a [[Belgian colony]] in the state of [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] called [[Nueva B\u00e9lgica]], and hundreds of Belgian settlers established it, but many moved to the capital of the state and other towns around the area, where the [[Walloon language|Walloon]] and French could be heard.\n\nThe [[Occitan language]] can be heard in the state of [[Guanajuato]], it is also known as ''Langue d'oc'' is a language originally spoken in [[Occitania|Southern France]]. Also to note is the city [[Guanajuato City|Guanajuato]] has a sizable French expatriate community.\n\n==== German ====\n{{main|German Mexicans}}\n[[File:Colegio Alem\u00e1n Alexander von Humboldt.jpg|thumbnail|Students of the [[Colegio Alem\u00e1n Alexander von Humboldt (Mexico City)|Colegio Alem\u00e1n Alexander von Humboldt]], which was founded by German immigrants in 1894.]]\nThe [[Plautdietsch language]], is spoken by descendants of German and Dutch [[Mennonites in Mexico|Mennonite immigrants]] in the states of [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] and [[Durango]]. Other German communities are in [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], [[Puebla]], [[Mexico City]], [[Sinaloa]] and [[Chiapas]], and the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]]. The largest German school outside of Germany is in Mexico City (Alexander von Humboldt school). These represent the large German populations where they still try to preserve the German culture (evident in its popular regional polka-like music types, ''[[conjunto]]'' and ''[[norte\u00f1o (music)|norte\u00f1o]]'') and language. Other strong German communities lie in [[Coahuila]] and [[Zacatecas]] (notably the [[Mennonites]]), Chiapas ([[Tapachula]]) and other parts of Nuevo Le\u00f3n (esp. the [[Monterrey]] area has a large German minority), [[Tamaulipas]] (the Rio Grande Valley in connections to [[German American]] culture and [[Mexican American]] or ''[[Tejano]]'' influences), Puebla ([[Nuevo Necaxa]]) where the German culture and language have been preserved to different extents. According to the 2010 census, there were 6,214 Germans living in Mexico.<ref name=inegi.gob.mx /> As of 2012, about 20,000 Germans reside in Mexico.<ref name=\"stats.oecd.org\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.oecd.org/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=MIG|title=International Migration Database|first=|last=OECD|website=stats.oecd.org}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Vicente_Fox_2.jpg|thumb|left|200px|[[Vicente Fox]], 55th [[President of Mexico]]. His great-grandfaher emigrated to [[Mexico]] from the [[United States]]\u00ad to a [[German people|German]] family]]\n\nOf special interest is the settlement [[Villa Carlota, Mexico|Villa Carlota]]: that was the name under which two German farming settlements, in the villages of [[Santa Elena, Yucat\u00e1n|Santa Elena]] and Pustunich in Yucat\u00e1n, were founded during the [[Second Mexican Empire]] (1864\u20131867).<ref>Alma Dur\u00e1n-Merk (2007). Identifying Villa Carlota: German Settlements in Yucat\u00e1n, M\u00e9xico, During the Second Empire. Augsburg: Universit\u00e4t Augsburg.</ref> Villa Carlota attracted a total of 443 German-speaking immigrants, most of them were farmers and artisans who emigrated with their families: the majority came from [[Prussia]] and many among them were Protestants.<ref>Alma Dur\u00e1n-Merk (2008a). Nur deutsche Elite f\u00fcr Yukatan? Neue Ergebnisse zur Migrationsforschung w\u00e4hrend des Zweiten mexikanischen Kaiserreiches. Only \"Selected\" German Immigrants in Yucat\u00e1n? Recent Findings about the Colonization Policy of the Second Mexican Empire. In: OPUS Augsburg, <http://opus.bibliothek.uni-augsburg.de/volltexte/2008/1320/pdf/Duran_Merk_Selected_German_Migration.pdf.</ref> Although in general these immigrants were well received by the hosting society,  and the Imperial government honored to the extent of its capabilities the contract it offered to these farmers, the colonies collapsed in 1867.<ref>Alma Dur\u00e1n-Merk (2008b): Los colonos alemanes en Yucat\u00e1n durante el Segundo Imperio Mexicano. In: OPUS Augsburg, http://opus.bibliothek.uni-augsburg.de/volltexte/2008/1329/pdf/Duran_Merk_Colonos_alemanes_Yucat\u00e1n.pdf.</ref> After the disintegration of Villa Carlota as such, some families migrated to other parts of the peninsular, into the United States and back to Germany.  Many stayed in Yucat\u00e1n, where there are descendants of these pioneers with last names such as Worbis, Dietrich and Sols, among others.<ref>A full list with the more than 120 names of the families who colonized \"Villa Carlota\" as well as the names of the officers and organizers of these colonization program, can be found in: Alma Dur\u00e1n-Merk (2009). Villa Carlota. Colonias alemanas en Yucat\u00e1n. M\u00e9rida: CEPSA/Instituto de Cultura de Yucat\u00e1n/ CONACULTA, {{ISBN|978-607-7824-02-2}}.</ref>\n\nIncluded in the [[Germans|ethnic German]] immigration to Mexico are from [[Austria]], [[Switzerland]] and the French region of [[Alsace]] which was part of France since the end of WWI, as well those from [[Bavaria]] and [[High German languages|High German]] regions of Germany. {{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}. There are about 2,000,000 Mexicans with some partial German ancestry, without counting the ones with total German ancestry, making Mexico 3rd country with the largest German community in Latin America, behind [[Brazil]] and [[Argentina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-OoZ0O-rgUU|title=Los que llegaron - Alemanes (11/04/2012)|first=|last=Canal Once|date=12 April 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==== Irish ====\n{{main|Irish Mexican}}\nThere is also an Irish-Mexican population in Hidalgo and the northern states. According to INM, in 2009 there were 289 Irish expatriates living in Mexico.<ref name=\"Chavez 2012\">Chavez, Ernesto y Cobo, Salvador, 2012.  \"Extranjeros Residentes en M\u00e9xico: Una aproximaci\u00f3n cuantitativa con base en los registros administrativos del INM\" INM, Mexico DF, 2012</ref>\n\nMany Mexican Irish communities existed in Mexican Texas until the revolution. Many Irish then sided with Catholic Mexico against Protestant pro-US elements. The Batall\u00f3n de San Patricio, a battalion of U.S. troops who deserted and fought alongside the Mexican Army against the United States in the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] (1846\u201348). In some cases, Irish immigrants or Americans left from California (the Irish Confederate army of Fort Yuma, Arizona during the [[U.S. Civil War]] (1861\u201365). \u00c1lvaro Obreg\u00f3n (O'Brien) was president of Mexico during 1920-24 and Ciudad Obreg\u00f3n and its airport are named in his honor. Actor Anthony Quinn is another famous Mexican of Irish descent. There are also monuments in Mexico City paying tribute to those Irish who fought for Mexico in the 19th century.\n\n==== Italian ====\n{{main|Italian Mexican}}\n[[File:Inmigrantesitalianosamexico.jpg|thumbnail|Italian community in [[Monterrey]] (1905).]]\nThere has not been a huge influx of Italians to Mexico, as there has been to other countries in America such as Argentina, Brazil, and the United States. However, there was an important number of arrivals from [[northern Italy]] and [[Veneto]] in the late 19th century who are today well assimilated in Mexican society. The exact number of Italian descendants is not known, but it is estimated that there around 85,000 Italian Mexicans in the eight original communities. As of 2012, 20,000 Italians reside in Mexico<ref name=\"stats.oecd.org\"/>\n\n====Russian====\n{{main|Russian Mexican}} \nAccording to INM in 2009 1,396  Russians are living documented in Mexico.<ref name=\"Ch\u00e1vez 2012\"/> According to the Russian embassy, 25,000 reside in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.publimetro.com.mx/mx/noticias/2011/06/30/turistas-rusos-se-enamoran-mexico.html?page=1&word=noticias&blog=mx&kind=category|title=Russians in Mexico|website=publimetro.com.mx}}</ref>\n\nMost left [[Russia]] during its [[communist]] regime ([[Soviet Union]]), taking advantage of the Mexican law allowing migrants from communist countries refuge if they touch Mexican soil, and the ability to become legal residents of Mexico. {{Citation needed|date=November 2007}} The [[Spiritual Christian]] ''[http://www.molokane.org/places/Mexico/ Pryguny]'' were a small early 20th century immigrant group to [[Guadalupe, Baja California|Valle de Guadalupe]], Baja California.\n\n==== Spanish ====\n{{main|Spanish Mexican}}\n[[File:StatueSpanishexMalecon.JPG|thumbnail|150px|Statue in [[Veracruz, Veracruz]] commemorating the Spanish immigrants that arrived as a result of the [[Spanish Civil War]].]]\n\n[[Spaniards]] make up the largest group of Europeans in Mexico. Most of them arrived during the [[New Spain|colonial period]] but others have since then immigrated, especially during the [[Spanish Civil War]] (1936\u201339) and the [[Francisco Franco]] regime (1939\u201375).\n\nThe first Spaniards who arrived in Mexico, were soldiers and sailors of [[Extremadura]], [[Andalusia]] and [[La Mancha]] who discovered the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]], the shores of the [[Gulf of Mexico]] and then made the conquest of what they call the [[New Spain]]. Among the soldiers sent by the Spanish crown to the colonial territory were Muslims converts from [[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain|C\u00f3rdoba]] and [[Granada]]. At the end of the 16th century, both common and aristocrat people migrated to Mexico and disseminated by its territory.\n\nMost recent immigrants came during the Spanish Civil War. Some of the migrants returned to Spain after the civil war, but some of them remained in Mexico. According to the 2010 census, there were 18,873 Spaniards living in Mexico.<ref name=\"inegi.gob.mx\"/>\n\nDue to the 2008 Financial Crisis and the resulting economic decline and high unemployment in Spain, many Spaniards have been emigrating to Mexico to seek new opportunities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newamericamedia.org/2013/02/as-spains-economy-worsens-young-adults-flock-to-mexico-for-jobs.php|title=As Spain's Economy Worsens, Young Adults Flock to Mexico for Jobs - New America Media|website=newamericamedia.org|access-date=2013-11-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203052506/http://newamericamedia.org/2013/02/as-spains-economy-worsens-young-adults-flock-to-mexico-for-jobs.php|archive-date=2013-12-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> For example, during the last quarter of 2012, a number of 7,630 work permits were granted to Spaniards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanielparishflannery/2013/04/30/as-spain-falters-spaniards-look-to-latin-america/|title=As Spain Falters, Spaniards Look to Latin America|first=Nathaniel Parish|last=Flannery|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe article on [[Basque Mexicans]] covers the large segment of Spaniards and some French immigrants of the [[Basque people|Basque]] ethnic group.\n\n==== Other European ====\nSmall waves of immigrants from [[Poland]], [[Ukraine]] and other Eastern European countries ([[Bulgaria]], [[Hungary]], [[Romania]] etc.), arrived during the Cold War.\n\nFewer immigrants came from [[Belgium]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Switzerland]], [[Cyprus]], [[Greece]] (See [[Greek Mexicans|Greek Mexican]]), [[Albania]], [[Croatia]], [[Serbia]], [[Czech Republic]], [[Montenegro]], [[Denmark]], [[Norway]], [[Sweden]], [[Finland]], [[Slovakia]], [[Slovenia]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Malta]], [[Portugal]] and [[Cape Verde]].\n\n=== Asian ===\n{{main|Asian Mexican}}\n[[File:Monumento a la inmigrac\u00edon coreana en Yucat\u00e1n (02).JPG|thumbnail|Monument in [[Merida, Yucatan]] commemorating 100 years of Korean immigration.]]\nMexico has seen immigration from different parts of Asia throughout its history. The first known Asians arrived during the Colonial era as slaves, labourers and adventurers from the [[Philippines]], southern [[China]] and [[India]]. Smaller numbers of immigrants came from Korea, Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), Indonesia, Cambodia, Japan and the Malay peninsula. This group of immigrants were collectively described as \"Chino\" meaning Chinese despite coming from many diverse origins.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1984|location=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hhNfVshMw64C&pg=PA21&dq=slaves+Acapulco+Chinese+Filipinos+Japanese+Malays#v=onepage&q=slaves%20acapulco%20chinese%20filipinos%20japanese%20malays&f=false|quote= |volume=Volume 2 of The Cambridge History of Latin America: Colonial Latin America. I-II|page=21|title=The Cambridge History of Latin America|isbn=0521245168|edition=illustrated, reprint|author=Leslie Bethell|editor=Leslie Bethell}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|publisher=University of Arizona Press|year=2013|location=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mMY4-ffumwUC&pg=PA134&dq=slaves+acapulco+chinese+japanese#v=onepage&q=slaves%20acapulco%20chinese%20japanese&f=false|quote= |volume=|page=134|title=The Affinity of the Eye: Writing Nikkei in Peru|isbn=0816599874|edition=|author=Ignacio L\u00f3pez-Calvo|others=Fernando Iwasaki}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|publisher=Duke University Press|year=2002|location=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1PDVdU4YZWgC&pg=PA200&dq=slaves+manila+chinese+japanese+acapulco#v=onepage&q=slaves%20manila%20chinese%20japanese%20acapulco&f=false|quote= |volume=|page=200|title=Cultures in Contact: World Migrations in the Second Millennium|isbn=0822384078|edition=|author=Dirk Hoerder|others=Andrew Gordon, Alexander Keyssar, Daniel James}}</ref> During the early 20th century, a significant number of Asians, primarily Chinese and Korean, were imported as labourers. These immigrants were known as ''Henequen'' and ''Chinetescos'' and were heavily concentrated in agricultural plantations in the Pacific states (e.g. [[Sinaloa]]) and the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]].\n\n====Korean====\n{{main|Korean Mexican}}\nA more recent wave (late 20th and early 21st century) of Korean immigrants have arrived as merchants and skilled labourers.<ref>{{Cite news|periodical=The Chosun Ilbo|url=http://english.chosun.com/cgi-bin/printNews?id=200708160018|date=2007-08-16|accessdate=2009-07-30|title=Five Generations On, Mexico's Koreans Long for Home|postscript=.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110621224921/http://english.chosun.com/cgi-bin/printNews?id=200708160018|archivedate=2011-06-21}}</ref> Modern immigrants can be found in large cities (especially Mexico City and Monterrey), while Korean descendants are most numerous in the coastal regions like [[Baja California]], [[Sonora]], [[Guerrero]], [[Veracruz]], [[Campeche]], [[Yucat\u00e1n (state)|Yucat\u00e1n]] and [[Quintana Roo]]. According to INM, in 2009 there were 5,518 South Koreans and 481 North Koreans living in M\u00e9xico<ref name=\"Chavez 2012\"/> There are an estimated 40,000 descendants of Korean henequen workers.\n\n====Chinese====\n{{Main|Chinese Mexican}}\n[[File:ChinaAssociationofMexicali.jpg|thumb|right|thumb|250px|Chines Association of Mexicali \u4e2d\u83ef\u6703\u9928]]\nThe story of [[Chinese immigration to Mexico]] extends from the late 19th century to the 1930s. By the 1920s, there was a significant population of Chinese nationals, with Mexican wives and Chinese-Mexican children. Most of these were deported in the 1930s to the United States and China with a number being repatriated in the late 1930s and in 1960. Smaller groups returned from the 1930s to the 1980s. The two main Chinese-Mexican communities are in Mexicali and Mexico City but few are of pure Chinese blood.<ref name=\"camacho547565\">{{cite journal |last1= Schiavone Camacho |first1= Julia Maria |date=November 2009 |title=Crossing Boundaries, Claiming a Homeland: The Mexican Chinese Transpacific Journey to Becoming Mexican, 1930s-1960s |journal= Pacific Historical Review |location=Berkeley |volume=78 |issue=4 |pages=547\u2013565 |doi=10.1525/phr.2009.78.4.545}}</ref>\n\nThe city of [[Mexicali]] in [[Baja California]] has the largest [[Overseas Chinese|Chinese]] population in Mexico and the largest [[Chinatown]] called [[Chinatowns in Latin America|''La Chinesca'']]. The culture and language from the mainly [[Yue Chinese|Cantonese]] and [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]]-speaking peoples are evident in the food, architecture, and everyday life in Mexico City. The Chinese entered the nation in the 19th century to build railroads, and many [[xenophobic]] acts were taken against them because Mexico preferred European immigrants. \nAccording to the 2010 Census there are 6,655 Chinese immigrants living in Mexico.<ref name=\"inegi.gob.mx\"/>\n\n====Japanese====\n{{Main|Japanese Mexican}}\n[[File:LMJJapaneseSectionJHS.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Liceo Mexicano Japon\u00e9s]] Japanese Section Junior High School]]\nThe Japanese community is also important in Mexico, and they reside mainly in Mexico City, [[Morelia]], [[San Luis Potos\u00ed]], [[Puebla]], [[Guadalajara, Jalisco|Guadalajara]], and [[Aguascalientes]], and the immigrant colony in the state of [[Chiapas]] known as [[Colonia Enomoto]]. The [[Japanese language]] is important in their cultural life in Mexico and many institutions for [[Japanese diaspora|nikkei]] exist and those wishing to learn the language and their ways of life can attend these lyceums. According to INM, in 2009 there were 4,485 Japanese immigrants residing in Mexico.<ref name=\"Ch\u00e1vez 2012\"/>\n\n====Southeast & South Asian====\nOther Asian communities in Mexico are Indians and Pakistanis followed by Filipinos from the [[Philippines]] when the country was under Spanish colonial (1540's-1898) and U.S. American territorial rule (1899\u20131946). These ethnic groups arrived in the northern states of Mexico as contract farm laborers in the 20th century. And a small [[Vietnam]]ese community that has close connections with the [[Vietnamese Americans|Vietnamese American]] community in the United States. The majority of Asian Mexicans live in urban areas or along the US-Mexican border.\n\nThere are approximately 200,000 (0.2%) Mexican people who can partly claim [[Overseas Filipinos|Filipino]] ancestry stemming from colonial times. The Philippines had a connection to Mexico through Spain, as it was administrated from [[New Spain]] for over 300 years. According to INM, in 2009 there were 823 immigrants from the Philippines residing in Mexico.<ref name=\"Ch\u00e1vez 2012\"/>\n\n====Middle Eastern====\n===== Arab =====\n{{main|Arab Mexican}}\nEthnologue reports that 400,000 Mexicans speak Arabic.<ref name=\"ethnologue\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=MX|title=Mexico|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Arab Mexican population consists of [[Lebanon|Lebanese]], [[Syrians]] and [[Palestinians]], whose families arrived in Mexico after the fall of the [[Ottoman Empire]] in World War I. The majority of them are Christian but some are Muslims.\n\nBusiness tycoon and billionaire [[Carlos Slim|Carlos Slim Hel\u00fa]] is the best-known Mexican of this immigrant group, as he is currently ranked by Forbes as the richest man in the world. His parents, [[Lebanese Maronite Christians|Maronite Christians]], immigrated to Mexico from [[Lebanon]].\n\n===== Other Middle Eastern =====\nOther members of the [[Middle Eastern]] community in Mexico include [[Armenians]].\n\n== Foreign-born population by country of birth ==\n[[File:Sinagoga_Nidjei_Israel,_Justo_Sierra_71_(2).JPG|thumb|right|250px|Sinagoga Nidjei Israel, Justo Sierra 71. Inner religious Jews services \nthe Nidjei Israel synagogue, in Mexico city.]]\n[[File:Marcela_ortiz_aznar.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Marcela Ortiz Aznar the singer of the group Poetic Missing [[Fado]] of [[Bethlehem]]. A Fado group from Mexico.]]\n\nMost foreigners in Mexico counted in the Census come from the United States or other [[Hispanophone]] countries, with smaller numbers from [[Europe]], [[East Asia]], and the non-Hispanophone [[Americas]]. Their numbers have been rising as the country's economy develops, but still comprise less than 1% of the population.\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Place || Country || 2017 || 2010 || 2000 || 1990\n|- bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"\n| 1 || {{USA}} || align=right| 899,311 || align=right| 738,103 || align=right| 343,591|| align=right| 194,619\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n| 2 || {{GTM}} || align=right| 54,508 || align=right| 35,322  || align=right| 23,597 || align=right| 46,005\n|- bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"\n| 3 || {{ESP}} || align=right| 27,608 || align=right| 18,873 || align=right| 21,024|| align=right| 24,783\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n| 4 || {{COL}} || align=right| 20,658 || alig