exhibit.htm |archivedate=14 October 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> publisher\n\n===Military===\n*Sir [[Edward Brampton]], godson of King Edward IV, a knight and commander during the [[War of the Roses]]<ref>''The first of the Tudors: a study of Henry VII and his reign'' (Taylor & Francis, 1981) by Michael Van Cleave Alexander, page 97</ref>\n* [[Frank Alexander de Pass]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sephardim.com/html/lore.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-12-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051224211804/http://www.sephardim.com/html/lore.html |archivedate=24 December 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> World War I [[British Indian Army]] Victoria Cross recipient\n* [[Albert Goldsmid]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=322&letter=G#1091|title=GOLDSMID - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=www.jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref> colonel\n* [[Frederick John Goldsmid]],<ref name=\"jewishencyclopedia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=322&letter=G#1107|title=GOLDSMID - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=www.jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref> general\n* [[Thomas William Gould]],<ref>[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:fqT0Pvw_wVUJ:www.dictionaryofeverything.com/explore/947/Thomas_William_Gould.html+%22Thomas+William+Gould%22+Jewish&hl=en ]{{dead link|date=July 2018}}</ref> World War II [[Royal Navy]] Victoria Cross recipient\n* [[John Patrick Kenneally]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mishalov.com/Kenneally.html|title=John Kenneally|website=www.mishalov.com}}</ref> World War II British Army Victoria Cross recipient (Jewish father)\n* [[Issy Smith]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.geocities.com/digger_history_youngest_vc/pages/smith-vc.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021105212333/http://au.geocities.com/digger_history_youngest_vc/pages/smith-vc.htm|archivedate=2002-11-05|title=Smith VC|date=5 November 2002|publisher=}}</ref> World War I [[British Army]] Victoria Cros