2007 }}</ref>\n* Sir [[Sidney Abrahams]], Britain, Olympic [[long jumper]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewsinsports.org/olympics.asp?sport=olympics&ID=318 |title=Solomon Abrahams |publisher=Jewsinsports.org |date= |accessdate=12 May 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Jo Ankier]], Britain, record holder (1,500m & 3,000m [[steeplechase (athletics)|steeplechase]])<ref>[http://www.thejc.com/home.aspx?ParentId=m14s44&SecId=44&AId=54735&ATypeId=1 The Jewish Chronicle] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013112702/http://www.thejc.com/home.aspx?ParentId=m14s44&SecId=44&AId=54735&ATypeId=1 |date=13 October 2007 }}</ref>\n*[[Harry Kane (hurdler)|Harry Kane]], Britain, Olympic [[hurdler]]<ref name=\"google1804\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=883&dat=19540730&id=6vFOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=e0wDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1804,1911973 |title=Eight Jewish Athletes at BEG |publisher=The Canadian Jewish Chronicle |date= 30 July 1954|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Weightlifting===\n* [[Ben Helfgott]], Polish-born British, three-time British champion (lightweight), three-time Maccabiah champion; survived [[Buchenwald]] and [[Theresienstadt concentration camp]]s, as all but one other of his family were killed by the Nazis\n* [[Edward Lawrence Levy]], Great Britain, world weightlifting champion; 14 world records\n\n===Wrestling===\n* [[Noam Dar]], Israeli-born Scottish wrestler\n* [[Fred Oberlander]], Austrian, British, and Canadian wrestler; world champion (freestyle heavyweight); Maccabiah champion\n* [[Samuel Rabin (artist)|Samuel Rabin]], Great Britain, Olympic bronze (freestyle middleweight)\n\n===Other sports===\n* [[Ludwig Guttmann]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishsports.net/historical_view.htm|title=A historical view of Jewish men and women in sports and their participation|website=www.jewishsports.net}}</ref> founder of the [[Paralympics]]\n* [[David Pleat]], former football manager<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewsinsports.org/profile.asp?sport=soccer&ID=128 |title=Pleat, David : Jews In Sports @ Virtual Museum |publisher=Jewsinsports.org |date=1945-01-15 |accessdate=2018-07-23}}</ref>\n* [[Barry Silkman]], footballer and agent\n* [[David Triesman]],<ref>[https://archive.today/20080205132101/http://www.fco.gov.uk/servlet/Front%3Fpagename=OpenMarket/Xcelerate/ShowPage&c=Page&cid=1115141149593 David Triesman, Lord Triesman of Tottenham ], Foreign and Commonwealth Office</ref> former Chairman of [[the Football Association]]\n\n== Philanthropists ==\n* [[Bernhard Baron]], cigarette maker and philanthropist<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishgen.org/jcr-uk/Community/Brightonh.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-01-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302041522/http://www.jewishgen.org/jcr-uk/Community/Brightonh.htm |archivedate=2 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Sir [[Clive Bourne]],<ref>''[[Jewish Chronicle]]'', obituary, 19 January 2007 p.45</ref> philanthropist\n* Dame [[Vivien Duffield]], philanthropist, daughter of Sir [[Charles Clore]]<ref>JYB 2005 p214</ref>\n* [[Joseph Duveen, 1st Baron Duveen of Millbank]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishbookweek.com/2007/250207i.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223190412/http://www.jewishbookweek.com/2007/250207i.php |archivedate=23 February 2007 |df=dmy-all }}: \"Lord Duveen and many other Jewish intellectuals\"</ref>\n* [[Anna Maria Goldsmid]],<ref>Oxf, ord [[Dictionary of National Biography]]: \"Born an Orthodox Jew, in her religious practices Anna Maria remained throughout her life very observant\"</ref> philanthropist\n* Sir [[Basil Henriques]],<ref>Concise [[Dictionary of National Biography]]: \"born into old, established Jewish family\"</ref> philanthropist\n* [[Maurice de Hirsch]],<ref>Oxford [[Dictionary of National Biography]]: \"His grandfather Jacob had established the family as one of the first Jewish families to acquire great wealth and social acceptability in Bavaria ... His mother came from an Orthodox Frankfurt family and ensured that the children were properly instructed in Jewish matters ... he thereafter lived more in London than in Paris.\"</ref> banker and philanthropist\n* [[Samuel Lewis (financier)|Samuel Lewis]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tymsder.co.uk/lender.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-05-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612043108/http://www.tymsder.co.uk/lender.htm |archivedate=12 June 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> financier and philanthropist\n* Sir [[Robert Mayer (philanthropist)|Robert Mayer]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ajcarchives.org/AJC_DATA/Files/1987_7_WestEurope.pdf |title=Data |website=ajcarchives.org |format=PDF}}</ref> philanthropist\n* [[Frederic David Mocatta]],<ref>Concise [[Dictionary of National Biography]]: \"Jewish philanthropist\"</ref> philanthropist\n\n==Miscellaneous==\n* [[Barney Barnato]],<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> diamond miner\n* [[Jack Beddington]],<ref>Oxford [[Dictionary of National Biography]]: \"His family were Jewish\"</ref> advertising executive\n* [[Neil Blair]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theblairpartnership.com/2017/09/29/literary-agent-neil-blair-opens-the-neil-blair-special-collections-reading-room-at-oxford-university/|title=NEIL BLAIR OPENS THE NEIL BLAIR SPECIAL COLLECTIONS READING ROOM AT OXFORD UNIVERSITY|accessdate=14 July 2019|work=The Blair Partnership}}</ref> literary agent\n* [[William Buzaglo]],<ref>{{Jewish Encyclopedia|article=William Buzaglo|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?letter=B&artid=1632}}</ref> self-proclaimed inventor\n* [[Antonio Fernandez Carvajal]],<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> merchant, first Jew to be naturalised as a British citizen\n* [[Jeremiah Duggan]],<ref name=\"The Press 2006, p.4\">'''The Press''', Hendon and Finchley Edition, 16 November 2006, p.4: \"Student Jeremiah, who was Jewish\"</ref> possible murder victim\n* [[Brian Epstein]] (1934-1967), music entrepreneur who discovered and managed [[the Beatles]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forward.com/culture/188384/meet-the-fifth-jewish-beatle-manager-brian-epste/|title=Meet the Fifth (Jewish) Beatle \u2014 Manager Brian Epstein|website=www.forward.com}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Foster (agent)|Michael Foster]], talent agent<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jewishpress.com/news/breaking-news/jewish-labour-donor-not-one-pound-to-central-party/2016/04/10/|title=Jewish Labour Donor: \u2018Not One Pound to Central Party'|work=[[The Jewish Press]]|first=Hana Levi|last=Julian|date=10 April 2016|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> \n* [[Alexander Goldberg]],<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/biographies.shtml]; ''[[The Irish Times]]'', Wednesday, 7 January 1998: \"Ireland's Young Bloomers\"</ref> human rights activist, chaplain and barrister\n* [[Henry Edward Goldsmid]],<ref name=\"jewishencyclopedia.com\"/> East India Company servant\n* [[Kurt Hahn]],<ref>Concise [[Dictionary of National Biography]]: \"born in Berlin of Jewish parents\"</ref> educationalist\n* [[Nathaniel Isaacs]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=256&letter=I&search=ISAACS,+NATHANIEL|title=ISAACS, NATHANIEL - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=www.jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref> explorer\n* [[Aaron Kosminski]], suspect in the Jack the Ripper case\n* [[Gottlieb Wilhelm Leitner]] (1840\u20131899), educationist and orientalist<ref>Oxford [[Dictionary of National Biography]]: \"registered with the Jewish community of Pest\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=169&letter=L&search=Leitner|title=LEITNER, GOTTLIEB WILLIAM - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=www.jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n* Sir [[Solomon de Medina]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=328&letter=M|title=MEDINA, SIR SOLOMON DE - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=www.jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref> army contractor, first English Jew to be knighted\n* [[Nigella Lawson]], celebrity chef\n* [[Chava Mond]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.co.il/content.asp?id%3D14439%26sid%3D7 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626005402/http://www.eonline.co.il/content.asp?id=14439&sid=7 |archivedate=26 June 2010 }}</ref> model\n* [[Dorrit Moussaieff]], Israeli-British businesswoman, entrepreneur, philanthropist and the [[First Lady of Iceland]] \n* [[Yotam Ottolenghi]], celebrity chef, food writer \n* [[Don Pacifico]],<ref>Concise [[Dictionary of National Biography]]: \"a Portuguese Jew, but born a British subject\"</ref> cause of the [[Pacifico incident]]\n* [[Krystyna Skarbek]],<ref>[http://www.lire.fr/critique.asp/idC=39075/idR=217/idG=4 Lire: le magazine litt\u00e9raire]: \"la comtesse Krystyna Skarbek, une aristocrate juive\"</ref> spy\n* Sir [[Bernard Waley-Cohen]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.commentarymagazine.com/Summaries/V38I4P62-1.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-04-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050423142301/http://www.commentarymagazine.com/Summaries/V38I4P62-1.htm |archivedate=23 April 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lord Mayor of London\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of the Jews in England]]\n*[[History of the Jews in Scotland]]\n*[[History of the Jews in Ireland]]\n*[[List of British Jewish entertainers]]\n*[[List of British Jewish nobility and gentry]]\n*[[List of British Jewish politicians]]\n*[[List of British Jewish scientists]]\n*[[List of British Jewish writers]]\n*[[Lists of Jews]]\n*[[List of Britons]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Celmins, Martin. ''Peter Green: The Authorized Biography''. London: Sanctuary Publishing, Ltd.; 3rd edition, 2003. pp.&nbsp;23\u201332.\n* JYB = [[Jewish Year Book]] (annual)\n* \"Obituary: Sir Edward Sassoon\". ''The Times'', Saturday, 25 May 1912; pg. 11; Issue 39908; col C.\n*  TimesAd: ''[[The Times]]'', 6/7/06 p34: \"A Call by Jews in Britain\" (advert signed by 300 British Jews)\n* David S. Katz, ''The Jews in the History of England, 1485\u20131850'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1994). xvi, 447 pp.\n\n{{Lists of Jews by country|noredlinks=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:British Jews}}\n[[Category:Lists of British Jews| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of British people|Jews]]\n[[Category:Lists of Jews]]\n[[Category:Lists of people by ethnicity|Jews]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMiscellaneous", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_British_Jews"}
{"title_page": "Khawarij", "text_new": "{{short description|Muslim sect}}\n{{redirect|Khariji|the village in Iran|Kharaji, Chaharmahal and Bakhtiari}}\n{{Expand Arabic|\u062e\u0648\u0627\u0631\u062c|date=April 2016}}\n{{expert needed|Islam|ex2=Middle Ages|date=September 2008}}\n{{Islam}}\n{{Islamism sidebar|Movements}}\nThe '''Khawarij''' {{Needs IPA|date=September 2017}} ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0648\u0627\u0631\u062c}}, ''al-Khaw\u0101rij'', singular {{lang|ar|\u062e\u0627\u0631\u062c\u064a}}, ''kh\u0101riji''), '''Kharijites''', or the '''ash-Shurah''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0631\u0627\u0629|ash-Shur\u0101h}} \"the Exchangers\") were a sect that appeared in the first century of Islam during the [[First Fitna]], the crisis of leadership after the death of [[Muhammad]]. It broke into revolt against the authority of the Caliph [[Ali]] after he agreed to arbitration with his rival, [[Muawiyah I]], to decide the succession to the [[Caliphate]] following the [[Battle of Siffin]] (657). A Kharijite later assassinated Ali, and for hundreds of years, the Khawarij were a source of insurrection against the Caliphate.\n\nThe Khawarij opposed arbitration as a means to choose a new ruler on the grounds that \"judgement belongs to God alone\". They considered arbitration a means for people to make decisions while the victor in a battle was determined by God. They believed that any Muslim\u2014even one who was not a [[Quraysh]] or even an [[Arabs|Arab]]\u2014could be the [[Imam]], the leader of the community, if he was morally irreproachable. If the leader sinned, it was the duty of Muslims to oppose and depose him. The only surviving sect of Khawarij are the [[Ibadis]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term ''al-Khariji'' was used as an [[Exonym and endonym|exonym]] by their opponents from the fact that they left Ali's army. The name comes from the [[Semitic root|Arabic root]] {{lang|ar|[[:wikt:|\u062e \u0631 \u062c]]}}, which has the primary meaning \"to leave\" or \"to get out\",{{sfn|Francesca|2006|p=84}} as in the basic word {{lang|ar|[[:wikt:\u062e\u0631\u062c|\u062e\u0631\u062c]]}} \"to go out\".{{sfn|Watt|1973|p=15}}\n\nHowever, the group called themselves ''ash-Shurat'' \"the Exchangers\", which they understood within the context of Islamic scripture ({{cite quran|2|207|s=ns}}) and philosophy to mean \"those who have traded the mortal life ([[al-Dunya]]) for the other life [with God] ([[al-Akhirah]])\".<ref name=Glasse-255>{{cite book|last1=Glasse|first1=Cyril|title=The New Encyclopedia of Islam|date=2001|publisher=Altamira Press|location=California|isbn=978-0759101890|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newencyclopediao0000glas/page/255 255\u201356]|url=https://archive.org/details/newencyclopediao0000glas/page/255}}</ref>{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|p=1075}}{{sfn|Francesca|2006|p=84}}<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Islam and the Muslim World|last=Martin|first=Richard C.|publisher=Macmillan Reference USA|year=2004|isbn=978-0028656038|location=|pages=390}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\n{{Further|First Fitna|Muhakkima}}\nThe Kharijites originated during the [[First Fitna]], the struggle for political leadership over the Muslim community, following the assassination in 656 of the third caliph [[Uthman]].{{sfn|Watt|1973|p=9}} [[Ali]], a cousin and son-in-law of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]], was elected caliph but soon had to face with opposition, first from [[Talhah|Talha ibn Ubayd Allah]], [[Zubayr ibn al-Awam]] and Muhammad's widow [[A'isha]], whom he was able to defeat (November 656),{{sfn|Donner|2010|pp=157\u2013159}} and later from [[Muawiyah I|Mu'awiya]], the governor of [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] and cousin of Uthman. Ali and Muwaiya faced each other at the [[Battle of Siffin]] in July 657. On the verge of defeat, Mu'awiya ordered his soldiers to hoist Qur'an on their lances; a signal to stop the fight and negotiate peace. The pious group of Qur'an readers (Qura) in Ali's army were moved by the gesture,{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=3}} which they interpreted as an appeal to the Book of God,{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=7}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=238}} and demanded that Ali stop the fight immediately. Although unwilling, he had to yield under pressure and threats of violence against him.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=3}}{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|p=1074}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=238}} An arbitration committee was setup with representatives from both Ali and Mu'awiya's side with a mandate to settle the dispute in the light of the Qur'an.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=3}} While most of Ali's army accepted the agreement, one group, mostly from the tribe of Tamim, vehemently objected to the arbitration and raised the slogan \"judgment belongs to God alone\".{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|p=1074}}\n\n===Harura===\nAs Ali marched back to [[Kufa]], his capital, resentment against the arbitration became widespread in his army. Some 12,000 dissenters seceded from the army and went to a place called Harura. They thus became known as the Harurites.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=3}} They held that the third caliph Uthman had deserved his death because of his faults, and that Ali was the legitimate caliph, while Mu'awiya was a rebel.{{sfn|Francesca|2006|pp=84\u201385}} They believed that the Qur'an clearly stated that as a rebel Mu'awiya was not entitled to arbitration, but rather should be fought until he repented, pointing to the verse:{{sfn|Francesca|2006|pp=84\u201385}}<ref name=OEIW>{{cite encyclopedia |author=John Alden Williams |author2=Justin Corfield |title=Khaw\u0101rij |encyclopedia=The Oxford Encyclopedia of the Islamic World |editor=John L. Esposito |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |year=2009 |url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195305135.001.0001/acref-9780195305135-e-0450 |url-access=subscription |ref=harv |isbn=9780195305135 |date= |accessdate=2017-08-22 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821044836/http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195305135.001.0001/acref-9780195305135-e-0450 |archivedate=2017-08-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|If two parties of the faithful fight each other, then conciliate them. Yet if one is rebellious to the other, then fight the insolent one until it returns to God\u200a's command. (Quran 49:9)}}\n\nThey held that in agreeing to arbitration Ali committed the grave sin of rejecting God's judgment (''[[hukm]]'') and attempted to substitute human judgment for God's clear injunction, which prompted their motto \"judgement belongs to God alone\" (''la hukma illa li-llah'').<ref name=OEIW/>{{sfn|Hawting|1978|p=460}} From this expression, which they were the first to use as a motto, they became known as ''[[Muhakkima]]''.{{sfn|Djebli|2000|p=107}} They also believed that Muslims owe allegiance only to the Quran and the sunna of Muhammad, Abu Bakr, and Umar, and denied that the right to the imamate should be based on close kinship with Muhammad.{{sfn|Francesca|2006|pp=84\u201385}}\n\nAli, after some time, visited the Harura camp and in order to win back their support argued that it was them who forced him to accept arbitration proposal despite his warnings against it. They acknowledged that they had sinned but argued that they had repented and asked Ali to do the same, which he did in very general and ambiguous terms. They subsequently offered back their allegiance to him and returned to Kufa on the condition that war against Mu'awiya be resumed within six months.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|pp=248\u2013249}}\n\n===Nahrawan===\nThe arbitration proceedings continued however and after a few months (March 658),{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|p=1074}} when Ali refused to denounce the arbitration and sent his arbitration delegation headed by [[Abu Musa Ash'ari]] to carry out the talks, Kharijites denounced Ali's caliphate and elected [[Abd Allah ibn Wahb al-Rasibi]] their caliph. In order to avoid being detected, they moved out of Kufa in small groups and went to a place called Nahrawan on the east bank of [[Tigris]]. Some five hundred of their [[Basra|Basran]] comrades were informed and they too joined them in Nahrawan, amounting to a total of 4,000 men.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=17\u201318}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|pp=251\u2013252}} Following this exodus, they were called as Khawarij.{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|pp=1074\u20131075}} They declared Ali and his followers apostates and killed several people who did not share their views.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=17\u201318}}\n\nIn the meantime, arbitrators declared that Uthman had been killed unjustly by the rebels. Other than that, however, they could not agree on anything substantial and the process collapsed. Ali now denounced the arbitrators and called on his supporters for renewed war against Mu'awiya.{{sfn|Donner|2010|p=163}} He invited Kharijites to join him in war against Mu'awiya as before. They refused to do so unless he would acknowledge that he had gone astray and repent. Ali consequently decided to depart for Syria without them.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=258}} On the way, however, he received news of the Kharijites' murdering various people, and was urged by his followers, who feared for their families and property in Kufa, to deal with the Kharijites first.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=259}} Kharijites refused to surrender the murderers and consequently Ali's attacked them in their camp, inflicting a heavy defeat on them at the [[Battle of Nahrawan]] (July 658), killing Ibn Wahb and most of his supporters.{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|pp=1074\u20131075}} Some 1200 of them, however, surrendered and were spared.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=18}} This bloodshed sealed the split of Kharijites from Ali's followers, and Kharijite calls for revenge ultimately led to Ali's assassination in 661 by a Kharijite.{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|pp=1074\u20131075}}{{sfn|Francesca|2006|pp=84\u201385}}\n\n== Later history ==\n\nFor hundreds of years the Khawarij continued to be a source of insurrection against the Caliphate.<ref name=Glasse-255/> Five small Kharijite revolts, involving about 200 men each, following Nahrawan were defeated during the caliphate of Ali.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=18}}{{sfn|Watt|1973|p=19}} Under Mu'awiya, Basra replaced Kufa as the center of Kharijite disturbance. His governors of Iraq [[Ziyad ibn Abihi]] and [[Ubayd Allah ibn Ziyad]] dealt with Kharijites with a heavy-hand and sixteen Kharijite revolts, with rebel numbers in individual revolts varying between 30 to 500, were suppressed.{{sfn|Watt|1973|p=19}} From now on, they started the practice of raiding undefended towns in the neighborhoods of Basra in rapid cavalry attacks whereby they would seem to appear from nowhere, pillage the towns and disappear quickly before the government forces could respond. If pursued, they would flee into mountainous regions of Iran.{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|p=1075}} In Basra, Ibn Ziyad is reported to have been particularly hard on them. He jailed any Kharijite whom he suspected of being dangerous and executed several Kharijite sympathizers who had publicly spoken against him.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|pp=25\u201326}} To avoid suppression, Basran Kharijites fled to Arabia around 680 CE.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=27}}\n\n===Second Fitna===\nAfter the death of Mua'wiya in 680, the empire fell to civil war over the question of leadership. The people of Hejaz (where Mecca and Medina are located) rebelled against the new caliph [[Yazid I|Yazid]].{{sfn|Donner|2010|pp=177, 181}} When Yazid sent an army to end the Hijazi rebellion in 683 and [[Siege of Mecca (683)|Mecca was besieged]], Kharijites assisted [[Abd Allah ibn al-Zubayr]], who was based on Mecca and opposed Yazid, in defending the city.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=27}} However, Yazid died soon afterwards and Ibn al-Zubayr proclaimed himself caliph. Kharijites, after discovering that Ibn al-Zubayr had proclaimed caliphate and did not share their view of Uthman and condemned his murder, abandoned him{{sfn|Rotter|1982|p=80}} and went to Basra. Basran tribal chiefs expelled Ibn Ziyad and the city fell to civil war. Karijites took over the city, killed the deputy appointed by Ibn Ziyad and broke 140 of their comrades free from Ibn Ziyad's prison.{{sfn|Morony|1984|p=473}}\n\nThey aroused condemnation by mainstream scholars such as  14th-century Muslim Ismail [[ibn Kathir]] who wrote, \"If they ever gained strength, they would surely corrupt the whole of the Earth, Iraq and [[Syria (region)|Shaam]] \u2013 they would not leave a baby, male or female, neither a man or a woman, because as far as they are concerned the people have caused corruption, a corruption that cannot be rectified except by mass killing.\"<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\"/>\nIn a similar vein, the 10th century Islamic scholar [[Abu Bakr al-Ajurri]] said, \"None of the scholars, in either past or recent times, ever disagreed that the Khawarij are an evil group, disobedient to Allah Almighty and to His Messenger - Peace Be Upon Him. Even if they pray, fast, or strive in worship, it does not benefit them, and even if they openly enjoin good and forbid evil it does not benefit them, as they are a people who interpret the Quran according to their desire.\"<ref name=\"al-Yaqoubi3\">{{Cite book | last = Al-Yaqoubi | first = Muhammad |authorlink=Muhammad al-Yaqoubi| year = 2015 | title = Refuting ISIS: A Rebuttal Of Its Religious And Ideological Foundations | page = 20| publisher = Sacred Knowledge |isbn=978-1908224125| title-link = Refuting ISIS: A Rebuttal Of Its Religious And Ideological Foundations }}</ref> One modern historian describes Khawarij as \"[[bedouin]] nomads who resented the centralization of power in the new Islamic state that curtailed the freedom of their tribal society.\"<ref name=Schultz-1981-175>{{cite book|last1=Schultz|first1=Joseph P.|title=Judaism and the Gentile Faiths: Comparative Studies in Religion|date=1981|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|page=175|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dchpiP-9YQAC&pg=PA175|quote=bedouin nomads who resented the centralization of power in the new Islamic state that curtailed the freedom of their tribal society.|isbn=9780838617076|access-date=2015-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214171402/https://books.google.com/books?id=dchpiP-9YQAC&pg=PA175|archive-date=2017-02-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==In hadith==\nAmong the hadith that refer to the Khawarij (according to some sources) include:\n\nAfter the [[Battle of Hunayn]], a man named Dhu aI-Khuwaisira is reported to have accused Muhammad of unjustly distributing the spoils. Umar reportedly asked for Muhammad's permission to kill the man, but the latter declined, saying:{{quote|text=Let him go, there will be people from him who will pray and fast so eagerly that your prayer and fasting will seem comparatively small to you; they plunge so deeply into the religion that they come out on the other side, like a sharp arrow through a target on which no trace of blood and flesh remains.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|pp=15\u201316}}}} According to German historian [[Julius Wellhausen]], the report is a fabrication and was invented retrospectively.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|pp=15\u201316}}\n\n{{QuoteHadith|Abu Dharr|matn=Allah's Messenger (saws) said: Verily there would arise from my Ummah after me a group (of people) who would recite the Quran, but it would not go beyond their throats, and they would pass clean through their religion just as the arrow passes through the prey, and they would never come back to it. They would be the worst among the creation and the creatures.|<ref>[[Sahih Muslim]] Hadith 2335</ref>}}\n\n==Beliefs and practices==\n{{Aqidah|Other}}\n===Early Muslim governance===\nThe Khawarij considered the caliphate of [[Abu Bakr]] and [[Umar]] to be rightly guided but believed that Uthman had deviated from the path of justice and truth in the last days of his caliphate and hence was liable to be killed or displaced. They also believed that Ali committed a grave sin when he agreed on the arbitration with Muawiyah. The Kharijites thus deemed the arbitrators (Abu Musa Ashaari and 'Amr ibn al-'As), the leaders who appointed these arbitrators (Ali and Muawiyah I) and all those who agreed on the arbitration (all companions of Ali and Muawiyah]) as [[Kafir|kuffar]] \"disbelievers\", as they had breached the rules of the Qur'an. They also believed that all participants in the [[Battle of the Camel]], including [[Talhah]], [[Zubayr ibn al-Awam]] and [[Aisha]] had committed a major sin.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[Abul A'la Maududi]], ''Khilafat-o-Malookeyat'' (Caliphate and kingship), ([[Urdu]]), p 214.</ref>\n\n===Doctrinal differences with other sects===\nKharijites differ with both Sunni and/or Shi\u02bfa on some points of doctrine:\n* Sunnis accept Ali as the fourth [[Rashidun|rightly-guided Caliph]] and also accept the three Caliphs before him, who were elected by their community. Shi'a believe that the [[Imamah (Shia doctrine)|imamate]] was the right of Ali, and the rule of the first three Rashidun caliphs was unlawful. Kharijites insist that the caliph need not be from the [[Quraysh (tribe)|Quraysh tribe]], but any pious Muslim nominated by other Muslims was eligible to be the caliph.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=goldhizer/> \n*Unlike Sunni and Shia, Kharijites believed that Muslims had the right and duty to revolt against any ruler who deviated from their interpretation of Islam,<ref name=goldhizer>Goldhizer, Ignaz. \"Muslim Studies\"(Transaction Publishers, 1971) Vol.1 p.130 (Downloadable from https://www.scribd.com/doc/94082191/Goldziher-Muslim-Studies-1 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003011846/https://www.scribd.com/doc/94082191/Goldziher-Muslim-Studies-1 |date=2015-10-03 }})</ref> or, according to other interpretations, failed to manage Muslim's affairs with justice and consultation<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> or committed a major sin.<ref name=Glasse-255/>\n* Kharijites reject the doctrine of [[Ismah|infallibility]] for the leader of the Muslim community in contrast to Shi'a but in agreement with Sunnis.<ref>Baydawi, Abdullah. \"Tawali' al- Anwar min Matali' al-Anzar\", circa 1300. Translated alongside other texts in the 2001 \"Nature, Man and God in Medieval Islam\" by Edwin Elliott Calverley and James Wilson Pollock. pp. 1001-1009</ref>\n* Unlike the more extreme Kharijites, the Ibadis reject the murder of Uthman as well as the Kharijite belief that all Muslims holding differing viewpoints were infidels.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n===Other doctrines===\nMany Khawarij groups believed that the act of sinning is analogous to [[kufr]] \"disbelief\" and that every grave sinner was regarded as a kafir unless they repent. They invoked the doctrine of [[free will]], in opposition to that of [[predestination in Islam|predestination]] in their opposition to the [[Ummayad Caliphate]], which held that Umayyad rule was ordained by God.<ref name=Campo-417>{{cite book|last1=Campo|first1=Juan Eduardo|title=Encyclopedia of Islam|date=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing.|location=New York|page=417|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OZbyz_Hr-eIC&pg=PA417&dq=Khawarij,+doctrine+quran#v=onepage&q=Khawarij%2C%20doctrine%20quran&f=false|accessdate=1 October 2015|isbn=9781438126968}}</ref>\n\nBased on Kharijite poetry writings, scholar [[Ihsan Abbas]] finds three categories of focus among them:<ref name=Timani/> \n*the strong desire of Kharijites for martyrdom and dying for the sake of God<ref name=Timani/> \n*detailed descriptions of how Kharijites defined a just and pious ruler<ref name=Timani/>\n*their universal tendency to blame the self for failing to establish the previous two categories.<ref name=Timani>Hussam S. Timani, ''Modern Intellectual Readings of the Kharijites'', pgs. 84-85. Volume 262 of American University Studies, Series VII: Theology and Religion. [[Bern]]: [[Peter Lang (publisher)|Peter Lang]], 2008.{{ISBN|9780820497013}}</ref>\n\nOn the basis of women fighting alongside Muhammad, Kh\u0101rij\u012bs have viewed fighting jihad as a requirement for women. One famous example is the warrior and poet [[Layl\u0101 bint \u1e6car\u012bf]].<ref>Lori A. Allen, 'Jihad: Arab States', in ''Encyclopedia of Women and Islamic Cultures: Family, Law and Politics'', ed. by Suad Joseph and Afs\u0101na Na\u01e7m\u0101b\u0101d\u012b  319-21 (p. 319).</ref>\n\n===Modern times===\n\nIn the modern era, some of Muslim theologians and observers have compared the beliefs and actions of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] (IS), [[al-Qaeda]], and like-minded groups to the Khawarij.<ref name=\"thinkprogress.org\">{{cite web|url=http://thinkprogress.org/world/2015/03/05/3630340/prominent-islamic-scholar-refutes-claims-isiss-links-islam/|title=Prominent Islamic Scholar Refutes Claims of ISIS's Links to Islam|work=Think Progress|date=March 2015|access-date=2015-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906162241/http://thinkprogress.org/world/2015/03/05/3630340/prominent-islamic-scholar-refutes-claims-isiss-links-islam/|archive-date=2015-09-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"expose\">{{cite web|url=http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/leuiyij-shaykh-saalih-al-suhaymee-it-is-obligatory-to-name-expose-and-refute-the-instigators-of-extremist-ideologies.cfm |title=Shaykh Saalih Al-Suhaymee: It Is Obligatory to Name, Expose and Refute the Instigators of Extremist Ideologies and Activities |website=Islam Against Extremism |year=2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110042110/http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/leuiyij-shaykh-saalih-al-suhaymee-it-is-obligatory-to-name-expose-and-refute-the-instigators-of-extremist-ideologies.cfm |archivedate=2015-01-10 }}</ref><ref name=\"Unjust to ascribe actions of kharijite renegades to islam and muslims\">{{cite web|url=http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/nbleuwe-it-is-criminal-and-unjust-to-ascribe-the-actions-of-the-kharijite-renegades-to-islam-and-the-muslim.cfm |title=It Is Criminal and Unjust to Ascribe the Actions of the Kharijite Renegades (Al-Qaidah, ISIS) to Islam and the Muslims |website=Islam Against Extremism |year=2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227053930/http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/nbleuwe-it-is-criminal-and-unjust-to-ascribe-the-actions-of-the-kharijite-renegades-to-islam-and-the-muslim.cfm |archivedate=2015-02-27 }}</ref><ref name=\"contemporary Kharijites\">{{cite web|url=http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/hnjsd-imam-al-albani-contemporary-takfiri-kharijites-are-dogs-of-hellfire-upon-the-prophetic-description-of-them.cfm |title=Imam Al-Albani: The Prophetic Description of 'Dogs of Hellfire' and Contemporary Takfiri Kharijites |website=Islam Against Extremism |year=2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227053926/http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/hnjsd-imam-al-albani-contemporary-takfiri-kharijites-are-dogs-of-hellfire-upon-the-prophetic-description-of-them.cfm |archivedate=2015-02-27 }}</ref> In particular, the groups are alleged to share the Kharijites' radical approach whereby self-described Muslims are declared unbelievers and therefore deemed them worthy of death and their disinterest in Quranic calls for moderation.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/another-battle-with-islams-true-believers/article20802390/ |title=Another battle with Islam's 'true believers' |work=The Globe and Mail |date=29 September 2014 |first1=SHEEMA |last1=KHAN |accessdate=13 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119055307/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/another-battle-with-islams-true-believers/article20802390/ |archive-date=19 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=jebara>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/fruits-of-the-tree-of-extremism|title=Imam Mohamad Jebara: Fruits of the tree of extremism|author=Mohamad Jebara More Mohamad Jebara|work=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=2019-01-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510165202/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/fruits-of-the-tree-of-extremism|archive-date=2019-05-10|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=hasan-balance-2012>[http://www.quilliamfoundation.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/publications/free/the-balance-of-islam-in-challenging-extremism.pdf The Balance of Islam in Challenging Extremism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802045255/http://www.quilliamfoundation.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/publications/free/the-balance-of-islam-in-challenging-extremism.pdf |date=2014-08-02 }}| Dr. Usama Hasan| 2012| quilliam foundation</ref> However, IS preachers strongly reject being compared to the Khawarij.<ref>{{cite news|title=Counter-radicalisation (3): A disarming approach: Can the beliefs that feed terrorism be changed?|url=https://www.economist.com/news/international/21695876-can-beliefs-feed-terrorism-be-changed-disarming-approach|accessdate=4 April 2016|work=[[The Economist]]|date=2 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404032828/http://www.economist.com/news/international/21695876-can-beliefs-feed-terrorism-be-changed-disarming-approach|archive-date=4 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ibadi]]s, a fellow early sect with similar beliefs, form the majority of the population of [[Oman]] (where they first settled in 686),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/mu.html#People |title=CIA - The World Factbook |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] |date=June 5, 2013 |accessdate=June 10, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516023047/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook//geos/mu.html#People |archive-date=May 16, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and there are smaller concentrations of them in the [[M'zab]] of [[Algeria]], [[Djerba]] in [[Tunisia]], the [[Nafusa Mountains]] in [[Libya]], and [[Zanzibar]].\n\nIn the 18th century, Hanafi scholar [[Ibn Abidin]] declared the [[Wahhabi movement]] of [[Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab]] as modern Khawarij although he does not consider them non-Muslims.<ref name=Ahmad-IMVEL-164>{{cite book|last1=Ahmad|first1=Ahmad Atif|title=Islam, Modernity, Violence, and Everyday Life|date=2009|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan.|page=164|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ccbIAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA164&dq=Khawarij+wahhab++Ibn+Abidin#v=onepage&q=Khawarij%20wahhab%20%20Ibn%20Abidin&f=false|accessdate=9 January 2016|isbn=9780230619562}}</ref>\n<ref>Khaled Abou El Fadl, \"9/11 and the Muslim Transformation.\" Taken from [https://books.google.com/books?id=m-ZLkRpYQWMC&pg=PA87&dq=khawarij+wahabi&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ncoRUtnsD6HF2QX2o4GgAw&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=khawarij%20wahabi&f=false September 11 in History: A Watershed Moment?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125212133/https://books.google.com/books?id=m-ZLkRpYQWMC&pg=PA87&dq=khawarij+wahabi&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ncoRUtnsD6HF2QX2o4GgAw&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=khawarij%20wahabi&f=false |date=2018-11-25 }}, pg. 87. Ed. [[Mary L. Dudziak]]. [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]]: [[Duke University Press]] 2003. {{ISBN|9780822332428}}</ref>\n\n== Principal groups ==\n* [[Azariqa]], the followers of Nafi ibn al-Azraq al-Hanaf\u012b al-Handhal\u012b\n* [[Najdat]], the followers of [[Najdah ibn 'Amir]]\n* [[Ibadi]]s, the followers of [[Abd-Allah ibn Ibadh|Abd Allah ibn Ibad]] are not the same ideology as the khawarij but share similar beliefs.\n* [[Sufri]]s, the followers of [[Ziyad ibn al-Asfar]] and [[Umran ibn Hattan]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kharijite Rebellion (866\u2013896)]]\n*[[Murji'ah]]\n*[[Salafism]]\n*[[Succession to Muhammad]]\n*[[Wahhabism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{EI2|last=Djebli|first=Moktar|authorlink=|title=Ta\u1e25k\u012bm|pages=107\u2013108|volume=10}}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Donner |first = Fred M. |author-link = Fred Donner |title = Muhammad and the Believers, at the Origins of Islam |year = 2010 |publisher = [[Harvard University Press]] |location = Cambridge, MA |isbn = 9780674050976 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=YM8RBAAAQBAJ }}\n* {{EI2|last=Levi Della Vida|first=G.|authorlink=Giorgio Levi Della Vida|title=Kh\u0101ridjites|pages=1074\u20131077|volume=4}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|ref=harv|last=Francesca|first= Ersilia | year= 2006 | title=Kh\u0101rij\u012bs |encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02be\u0101n|volume=3: J\u2013O|editor-last=McAuliffe|editor-first=Jane Dammen|publisher=E. J. Brill|pp=84\u201389|doi= 10.1163/1875-3922_q3_EQCOM_00103}}\n* {{cite journal |ref = harv |last = Hawting |first = Gerald R. |title = The Significance of the Slogan \"l\u0101 hukma ill\u0101 lill\u0101h\" and the References to the \"Hud\u016bd\" in the Traditions about the Fitna and the Murder of 'Uthm\u0101n |journal = Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies |year = 1978 |volume = 41 |number = 3 |pages = 453\u2013463 |jstor = 615490}}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Madelung |first = Wilferd |author-link=Wilferd Madelung |title = The Succession to Muhammad: A Study of the Early Caliphate |url = https://books.google.de/books?id=2QKBUwBUWWkC |year = 1997 |publisher = Cambridge University Press |location = Cambridge, England |isbn = 0521646960 }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Morony|first=Michael|author-link=Michael G. Morony|year=1984|title=Iraq After the Muslim Conquest|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|location=Princeton|isbn=0-691-05395-2}}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Rotter |first = Gernot |year = 1982 |title = Die Umayyaden und der zweite B\u00fcrgerkrieg (680-692) |language = de |publisher = Deutsche Morgenl\u00e4ndische Gesellschaft |location = Wiesbaden |url = https://books.google.de/books?id=NuANAAAAYAAJ |isbn = 9783515029131 }}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Watt |first = W. Montgomery |year = 1973 |author-link = W. Montgomery Watt |title = The Formative Period of Islamic Thought |publisher = [[Edinburgh University Press]] |location = Edinburgh, Scotland |url = https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.137377/page/n3 |isbn = 9780852242452 }}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Wellhausen |first = Julius |year = 1901 |author-link = Julius Wellhausen |title = Die religi\u00f6s-politischen Oppositionsparteien im alten Islam |language = de |url = https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.358135 |publisher = Weidmannsche buchhandlung |location = Berlin|oclc = 453206240 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite encyclopedia | title = Kharijites in Persia | last = Bosworth | first = C. Edmund | authorlink = Clifford Edmund Bosworth | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/kharijites-in-persia | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica | pages = | location = | publisher = | year = 2009 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Al-Yaqoubi | first = Muhammad |authorlink=Muhammad al-Yaqoubi| year = 2015 | title = Refuting ISIS: A Rebuttal Of Its Religious And Ideological Foundations | publisher = Sacred Knowledge |isbn=978-1908224125| title-link = Refuting ISIS: A Rebuttal Of Its Religious And Ideological Foundations }}\n* J. J. Saunders, A History of Medieval Islam, Routledge (UK), 1 October 1972 {{ISBN|0-415-05914-3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.islamfact.com/ Ibadhi Islam site]\n*[http://www.islamfrominside.com/Pages/Articles/Hermeneutics%20of%20takfir.html Hermeneutics of Takfir]\n\n{{Islamic Theology|state=uncollapsed|schools}}\n{{Theology}}\n{{Islam topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Kharijism| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Muslim sect}}\n{{redirect|Khariji|the village in Iran|Kharaji, Chaharmahal and Bakhtiari}}\n{{Expand Arabic|\u062e\u0648\u0627\u0631\u062c|date=April 2016}}\n{{expert needed|Islam|ex2=Middle Ages|date=September 2008}}\n{{Islam}}\n{{Islamism sidebar|Movements}}\nThe '''Khawarij''' {{Needs IPA|date=September 2017}} ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0648\u0627\u0631\u062c}}, ''al-Khaw\u0101rij'', singular {{lang|ar|\u062e\u0627\u0631\u062c\u064a}}, ''kh\u0101riji''), '''Kharijites''', or the '''ash-Shurah''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0631\u0627\u0629|ash-Shur\u0101h}} \"the Exchangers\") were a sect that appeared in the first century of Islam during the [[First Fitna]], the crisis of leadership after the death of [[Muhammad]]. It broke into revolt against the authority of the Caliph [[Ali]] after he agreed to arbitration with his rival, [[Muawiyah I]], to decide the succession to the [[Caliphate]] following the [[Battle of Siffin]] (657). A Kharijite later assassinated Ali, and for hundreds of years, the Khawarij were a source of insurrection against the Caliphate.\n\nThe Khawarij opposed arbitration as a means to choose a new ruler on the grounds that \"judgement belongs to God alone\". They considered arbitration a means for people to make decisions while the victor in a battle was determined by God. They believed that any Muslim\u2014even one who was not a [[Quraysh]] or even an [[Arabs|Arab]]\u2014could be the [[Imam]], the leader of the community, if he was morally irreproachable. If the leader sinned, it was the duty of Muslims to oppose and depose him. The only surviving sect of Khawarij are the [[Ibadis]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term ''al-Khariji'' was used as an [[Exonym and endonym|exonym]] by their opponents from the fact that they left Ali's army. The name comes from the [[Semitic root|Arabic root]] {{lang|ar|[[:wikt:|\u062e \u0631 \u062c]]}}, which has the primary meaning \"to leave\" or \"to get out\",{{sfn|Francesca|2006|p=84}} as in the basic word {{lang|ar|[[:wikt:\u062e\u0631\u062c|\u062e\u0631\u062c]]}} \"to go out\".{{sfn|Watt|1973|p=15}}\n\nHowever, the group called themselves ''ash-Shurat'' \"the Exchangers\", which they understood within the context of Islamic scripture ({{cite quran|2|207|s=ns}}) and philosophy to mean \"those who have traded the mortal life ([[al-Dunya]]) for the other life [with God] ([[al-Akhirah]])\".<ref name=Glasse-255>{{cite book|last1=Glasse|first1=Cyril|title=The New Encyclopedia of Islam|date=2001|publisher=Altamira Press|location=California|isbn=978-0759101890|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newencyclopediao0000glas/page/255 255\u201356]|url=https://archive.org/details/newencyclopediao0000glas/page/255}}</ref>{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|p=1075}}{{sfn|Francesca|2006|p=84}}<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Islam and the Muslim World|last=Martin|first=Richard C.|publisher=Macmillan Reference USA|year=2004|isbn=978-0028656038|location=|pages=390}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\n{{Further|First Fitna|Muhakkima}}\nThe Kharijites originated during the [[First Fitna]], the struggle for political leadership over the Muslim community, following the assassination in 656 of the third caliph [[Uthman]].{{sfn|Watt|1973|p=9}} [[Ali]], a cousin and son-in-law of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]], was elected caliph but soon had to face with opposition, first from [[Talhah|Talha ibn Ubayd Allah]], [[Zubayr ibn al-Awam]] and Muhammad's widow [[A'isha]], whom he was able to defeat (November 656),{{sfn|Donner|2010|pp=157\u2013159}} and later from [[Muawiyah I|Mu'awiya]], the governor of [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] and cousin of Uthman. Ali and Muwaiya faced each other at the [[Battle of Siffin]] in July 657. On the verge of defeat, Mu'awiya ordered his soldiers to hoist Qur'an on their lances; a signal to stop the fight and negotiate peace. The pious group of Qur'an readers (Qura) in Ali's army were moved by the gesture,{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=3}} which they interpreted as an appeal to the Book of God,{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=7}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=238}} and demanded that Ali stop the fight immediately. Although unwilling, he had to yield under pressure and threats of violence against him.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=3}}{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|p=1074}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=238}} An arbitration committee was setup with representatives from both Ali and Mu'awiya's side with a mandate to settle the dispute in the light of the Qur'an.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=3}} While most of Ali's army accepted the agreement, one group, mostly from the tribe of Tamim, vehemently objected to the arbitration and raised the slogan \"judgment belongs to God alone\".{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|p=1074}}\n\n===Harura===\nAs Ali marched back to [[Kufa]], his capital, resentment against the arbitration became widespread in his army. Some 12,000 dissenters seceded from the army and went to a place called Harura. They thus became known as the Harurites.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=3}} They held that the third caliph Uthman had deserved his death because of his faults, and that Ali was the legitimate caliph, while Mu'awiya was a rebel.{{sfn|Francesca|2006|pp=84\u201385}} They believed that the Qur'an clearly stated that as a rebel Mu'awiya was not entitled to arbitration, but rather should be fought until he repented, pointing to the verse:{{sfn|Francesca|2006|pp=84\u201385}}<ref name=OEIW>{{cite encyclopedia |author=John Alden Williams |author2=Justin Corfield |title=Khaw\u0101rij |encyclopedia=The Oxford Encyclopedia of the Islamic World |editor=John L. Esposito |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |year=2009 |url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195305135.001.0001/acref-9780195305135-e-0450 |url-access=subscription |ref=harv |isbn=9780195305135 |date= |accessdate=2017-08-22 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821044836/http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195305135.001.0001/acref-9780195305135-e-0450 |archivedate=2017-08-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|If two parties of the faithful fight each other, then conciliate them. Yet if one is rebellious to the other, then fight the insolent one until it returns to God\u200a's command. (Quran 49:9)}}\n\nThey held that in agreeing to arbitration Ali committed the grave sin of rejecting God's judgment (''[[hukm]]'') and attempted to substitute human judgment for God's clear injunction, which prompted their motto \"judgement belongs to God alone\" (''la hukma illa li-llah'').<ref name=OEIW/>{{sfn|Hawting|1978|p=460}} From this expression, which they were the first to use as a motto, they became known as ''[[Muhakkima]]''.{{sfn|Djebli|2000|p=107}} They also believed that Muslims owe allegiance only to the Quran and the sunna of Muhammad, Abu Bakr, and Umar, and denied that the right to the imamate should be based on close kinship with Muhammad.{{sfn|Francesca|2006|pp=84\u201385}}\n\nAli, after some time, visited the Harura camp and in order to win back their support argued that it was them who forced him to accept arbitration proposal despite his warnings against it. They acknowledged that they had sinned but argued that they had repented and asked Ali to do the same, which he did in very general and ambiguous terms. They subsequently offered back their allegiance to him and returned to Kufa on the condition that war against Mu'awiya be resumed within six months.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|pp=248\u2013249}}\n\n===Nahrawan===\nThe arbitration proceedings continued however and after a few months (March 658),{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|p=1074}} when Ali refused to denounce the arbitration and sent his arbitration delegation headed by [[Abu Musa Ash'ari]] to carry out the talks, Kharijites denounced Ali's caliphate and elected [[Abd Allah ibn Wahb al-Rasibi]] their caliph. In order to avoid being detected, they moved out of Kufa in small groups and went to a place called Nahrawan on the east bank of [[Tigris]]. Some five hundred of their [[Basra|Basran]] comrades were informed and they too joined them in Nahrawan, amounting to a total of 4,000 men.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=17\u201318}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|pp=251\u2013252}} Following this exodus, they were called as Khawarij.{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|pp=1074\u20131075}} They declared Ali and his followers apostates and killed several people who did not share their views.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=17\u201318}}\n\nIn the meantime, arbitrators declared that Uthman had been killed unjustly by the rebels. Other than that, however, they could not agree on anything substantial and the process collapsed. Ali now denounced the arbitrators and called on his supporters for renewed war against Mu'awiya.{{sfn|Donner|2010|p=163}} He invited Kharijites to join him in war against Mu'awiya as before. They refused to do so unless he would acknowledge that he had gone astray and repent. Ali consequently decided to depart for Syria without them.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=258}} On the way, however, he received news of the Kharijites' murdering various people, and was urged by his followers, who feared for their families and property in Kufa, to deal with the Kharijites first.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=259}} Kharijites refused to surrender the murderers and consequently Ali's attacked them in their camp, inflicting a heavy defeat on them at the [[Battle of Nahrawan]] (July 658), killing Ibn Wahb and most of his supporters.{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|pp=1074\u20131075}} Some 1200 of them, however, surrendered and were spared.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=18}} This bloodshed sealed the split of Kharijites from Ali's followers, and Kharijite calls for revenge ultimately led to Ali's assassination in 661 by a Kharijite.{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|pp=1074\u20131075}}{{sfn|Francesca|2006|pp=84\u201385}}\n\n== Later history ==\n\nFor hundreds of years the Khawarij continued to be a source of insurrection against the Caliphate.<ref name=Glasse-255/> Five small Kharijite revolts, involving about 200 men each, following Nahrawan were defeated during the caliphate of Ali.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=18}}{{sfn|Watt|1973|p=19}} Under Mu'awiya, Basra replaced Kufa as the center of Kharijite disturbance. His governors of Iraq [[Ziyad ibn Abihi]] and [[Ubayd Allah ibn Ziyad]] dealt with Kharijites with a heavy-hand and sixteen Kharijite revolts, with rebel numbers in individual revolts varying between 30 to 500, were suppressed.{{sfn|Watt|1973|p=19}} From now on, they started the practice of raiding undefended towns in the neighborhoods of Basra in rapid cavalry attacks whereby they would seem to appear from nowhere, pillage the towns and disappear quickly before the government forces could respond. If pursued, they would flee into mountainous regions of Iran.{{sfn|Levi Della Vida|1978|p=1075}} In Basra, Ibn Ziyad is reported to have been particularly hard on them. He jailed any Kharijite whom he suspected of being dangerous and executed several Kharijite sympathizers who had publicly spoken against him.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|pp=25\u201326}} To avoid suppression, Basran Kharijites fled to Arabia around 680 CE.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=27}}\n\n===Second Fitna===\nAfter the death of Mua'wiya in 680, the empire fell to civil war over the question of leadership. The people of Hejaz (where Mecca and Medina are located) rebelled against the new caliph [[Yazid I|Yazid]].{{sfn|Donner|2010|pp=177, 181}} When Yazid sent an army to end the Hijazi rebellion in 683 and [[Siege of Mecca (683)|Mecca was besieged]], Kharijites assisted [[Abd Allah ibn al-Zubayr]], who was based on Mecca and opposed Yazid, in defending the city.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|p=27}} However, Yazid died soon afterwards and Ibn al-Zubayr proclaimed himself caliph. Kharijites, after discovering that Ibn al-Zubayr had proclaimed caliphate and did not share their view of Uthman and condemned his murder, abandoned him{{sfn|Rotter|1982|p=80}} and went to Basra. Basran tribal chiefs expelled Ibn Ziyad and the city fell to civil war. Karijites took over the city, killed the deputy appointed by Ibn Ziyad and broke 140 of their comrades free from Ibn Ziyad's prison.{{sfn|Morony|1984|473}}\n\nThey aroused condemnation by mainstream scholars such as  14th-century Muslim Ismail [[ibn Kathir]] who wrote, \"If they ever gained strength, they would surely corrupt the whole of the Earth, Iraq and [[Syria (region)|Shaam]] \u2013 they would not leave a baby, male or female, neither a man or a woman, because as far as they are concerned the people have caused corruption, a corruption that cannot be rectified except by mass killing.\"<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\"/>\nIn a similar vein, the 10th century Islamic scholar [[Abu Bakr al-Ajurri]] said, \"None of the scholars, in either past or recent times, ever disagreed that the Khawarij are an evil group, disobedient to Allah Almighty and to His Messenger - Peace Be Upon Him. Even if they pray, fast, or strive in worship, it does not benefit them, and even if they openly enjoin good and forbid evil it does not benefit them, as they are a people who interpret the Quran according to their desire.\"<ref name=\"al-Yaqoubi3\">{{Cite book | last = Al-Yaqoubi | first = Muhammad |authorlink=Muhammad al-Yaqoubi| year = 2015 | title = Refuting ISIS: A Rebuttal Of Its Religious And Ideological Foundations | page = 20| publisher = Sacred Knowledge |isbn=978-1908224125| title-link = Refuting ISIS: A Rebuttal Of Its Religious And Ideological Foundations }}</ref> One modern historian describes Khawarij as \"[[bedouin]] nomads who resented the centralization of power in the new Islamic state that curtailed the freedom of their tribal society.\"<ref name=Schultz-1981-175>{{cite book|last1=Schultz|first1=Joseph P.|title=Judaism and the Gentile Faiths: Comparative Studies in Religion|date=1981|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|page=175|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dchpiP-9YQAC&pg=PA175|quote=bedouin nomads who resented the centralization of power in the new Islamic state that curtailed the freedom of their tribal society.|isbn=9780838617076|access-date=2015-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214171402/https://books.google.com/books?id=dchpiP-9YQAC&pg=PA175|archive-date=2017-02-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==In hadith==\nAmong the hadith that refer to the Khawarij (according to some sources) include:\n\nAfter the [[Battle of Hunayn]], a man named Dhu aI-Khuwaisira is reported to have accused Muhammad of unjustly distributing the spoils. Umar reportedly asked for Muhammad's permission to kill the man, but the latter declined, saying:{{quote|text=Let him go, there will be people from him who will pray and fast so eagerly that your prayer and fasting will seem comparatively small to you; they plunge so deeply into the religion that they come out on the other side, like a sharp arrow through a target on which no trace of blood and flesh remains.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|pp=15\u201316}}}} According to German historian [[Julius Wellhausen]], the report is a fabrication and was invented retrospectively.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1901|pp=15\u201316}}\n\n{{QuoteHadith|Abu Dharr|matn=Allah's Messenger (saws) said: Verily there would arise from my Ummah after me a group (of people) who would recite the Quran, but it would not go beyond their throats, and they would pass clean through their religion just as the arrow passes through the prey, and they would never come back to it. They would be the worst among the creation and the creatures.|<ref>[[Sahih Muslim]] Hadith 2335</ref>}}\n\n==Beliefs and practices==\n{{Aqidah|Other}}\n===Early Muslim governance===\nThe Khawarij considered the caliphate of [[Abu Bakr]] and [[Umar]] to be rightly guided but believed that Uthman had deviated from the path of justice and truth in the last days of his caliphate and hence was liable to be killed or displaced. They also believed that Ali committed a grave sin when he agreed on the arbitration with Muawiyah. The Kharijites thus deemed the arbitrators (Abu Musa Ashaari and 'Amr ibn al-'As), the leaders who appointed these arbitrators (Ali and Muawiyah I) and all those who agreed on the arbitration (all companions of Ali and Muawiyah]) as [[Kafir|kuffar]] \"disbelievers\", as they had breached the rules of the Qur'an. They also believed that all participants in the [[Battle of the Camel]], including [[Talhah]], [[Zubayr ibn al-Awam]] and [[Aisha]] had committed a major sin.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[Abul A'la Maududi]], ''Khilafat-o-Malookeyat'' (Caliphate and kingship), ([[Urdu]]), p 214.</ref>\n\n===Doctrinal differences with other sects===\nKharijites differ with both Sunni and/or Shi\u02bfa on some points of doctrine:\n* Sunnis accept Ali as the fourth [[Rashidun|rightly-guided Caliph]] and also accept the three Caliphs before him, who were elected by their community. Shi'a believe that the [[Imamah (Shia doctrine)|imamate]] was the right of Ali, and the rule of the first three Rashidun caliphs was unlawful. Kharijites insist that the caliph need not be from the [[Quraysh (tribe)|Quraysh tribe]], but any pious Muslim nominated by other Muslims was eligible to be the caliph.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=goldhizer/> \n*Unlike Sunni and Shia, Kharijites believed that Muslims had the right and duty to revolt against any ruler who deviated from their interpretation of Islam,<ref name=goldhizer>Goldhizer, Ignaz. \"Muslim Studies\"(Transaction Publishers, 1971) Vol.1 p.130 (Downloadable from https://www.scribd.com/doc/94082191/Goldziher-Muslim-Studies-1 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003011846/https://www.scribd.com/doc/94082191/Goldziher-Muslim-Studies-1 |date=2015-10-03 }})</ref> or, according to other interpretations, failed to manage Muslim's affairs with justice and consultation<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> or committed a major sin.<ref name=Glasse-255/>\n* Kharijites reject the doctrine of [[Ismah|infallibility]] for the leader of the Muslim community in contrast to Shi'a but in agreement with Sunnis.<ref>Baydawi, Abdullah. \"Tawali' al- Anwar min Matali' al-Anzar\", circa 1300. Translated alongside other texts in the 2001 \"Nature, Man and God in Medieval Islam\" by Edwin Elliott Calverley and James Wilson Pollock. pp. 1001-1009</ref>\n* Unlike the more extreme Kharijites, the Ibadis reject the murder of Uthman as well as the Kharijite belief that all Muslims holding differing viewpoints were infidels.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n===Other doctrines===\nMany Khawarij groups believed that the act of sinning is analogous to [[kufr]] \"disbelief\" and that every grave sinner was regarded as a kafir unless they repent. They invoked the doctrine of [[free will]], in opposition to that of [[predestination in Islam|predestination]] in their opposition to the [[Ummayad Caliphate]], which held that Umayyad rule was ordained by God.<ref name=Campo-417>{{cite book|last1=Campo|first1=Juan Eduardo|title=Encyclopedia of Islam|date=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing.|location=New York|page=417|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OZbyz_Hr-eIC&pg=PA417&dq=Khawarij,+doctrine+quran#v=onepage&q=Khawarij%2C%20doctrine%20quran&f=false|accessdate=1 October 2015|isbn=9781438126968}}</ref>\n\nBased on Kharijite poetry writings, scholar [[Ihsan Abbas]] finds three categories of focus among them:<ref name=Timani/> \n*the strong desire of Kharijites for martyrdom and dying for the sake of God<ref name=Timani/> \n*detailed descriptions of how Kharijites defined a just and pious ruler<ref name=Timani/>\n*their universal tendency to blame the self for failing to establish the previous two categories.<ref name=Timani>Hussam S. Timani, ''Modern Intellectual Readings of the Kharijites'', pgs. 84-85. Volume 262 of American University Studies, Series VII: Theology and Religion. [[Bern]]: [[Peter Lang (publisher)|Peter Lang]], 2008.{{ISBN|9780820497013}}</ref>\n\nOn the basis of women fighting alongside Muhammad, Kh\u0101rij\u012bs have viewed fighting jihad as a requirement for women. One famous example is the warrior and poet [[Layl\u0101 bint \u1e6car\u012bf]].<ref>Lori A. Allen, 'Jihad: Arab States', in ''Encyclopedia of Women and Islamic Cultures: Family, Law and Politics'', ed. by Suad Joseph and Afs\u0101na Na\u01e7m\u0101b\u0101d\u012b  319-21 (p. 319).</ref>\n\n===Modern times===\n\nIn the modern era, some of Muslim theologians and observers have compared the beliefs and actions of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] (IS), [[al-Qaeda]], and like-minded groups to the Khawarij.<ref name=\"thinkprogress.org\">{{cite web|url=http://thinkprogress.org/world/2015/03/05/3630340/prominent-islamic-scholar-refutes-claims-isiss-links-islam/|title=Prominent Islamic Scholar Refutes Claims of ISIS's Links to Islam|work=Think Progress|date=March 2015|access-date=2015-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906162241/http://thinkprogress.org/world/2015/03/05/3630340/prominent-islamic-scholar-refutes-claims-isiss-links-islam/|archive-date=2015-09-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"expose\">{{cite web|url=http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/leuiyij-shaykh-saalih-al-suhaymee-it-is-obligatory-to-name-expose-and-refute-the-instigators-of-extremist-ideologies.cfm |title=Shaykh Saalih Al-Suhaymee: It Is Obligatory to Name, Expose and Refute the Instigators of Extremist Ideologies and Activities |website=Islam Against Extremism |year=2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110042110/http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/leuiyij-shaykh-saalih-al-suhaymee-it-is-obligatory-to-name-expose-and-refute-the-instigators-of-extremist-ideologies.cfm |archivedate=2015-01-10 }}</ref><ref name=\"Unjust to ascribe actions of kharijite renegades to islam and muslims\">{{cite web|url=http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/nbleuwe-it-is-criminal-and-unjust-to-ascribe-the-actions-of-the-kharijite-renegades-to-islam-and-the-muslim.cfm |title=It Is Criminal and Unjust to Ascribe the Actions of the Kharijite Renegades (Al-Qaidah, ISIS) to Islam and the Muslims |website=Islam Against Extremism |year=2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227053930/http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/nbleuwe-it-is-criminal-and-unjust-to-ascribe-the-actions-of-the-kharijite-renegades-to-islam-and-the-muslim.cfm |archivedate=2015-02-27 }}</ref><ref name=\"contemporary Kharijites\">{{cite web|url=http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/hnjsd-imam-al-albani-contemporary-takfiri-kharijites-are-dogs-of-hellfire-upon-the-prophetic-description-of-them.cfm |title=Imam Al-Albani: The Prophetic Description of 'Dogs of Hellfire' and Contemporary Takfiri Kharijites |website=Islam Against Extremism |year=2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227053926/http://www.islamagainstextremism.com/articles/hnjsd-imam-al-albani-contemporary-takfiri-kharijites-are-dogs-of-hellfire-upon-the-prophetic-description-of-them.cfm |archivedate=2015-02-27 }}</ref> In particular, the groups are alleged to share the Kharijites' radical approach whereby self-described Muslims are declared unbelievers and therefore deemed them worthy of death and their disinterest in Quranic calls for moderation.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/another-battle-with-islams-true-believers/article20802390/ |title=Another battle with Islam's 'true believers' |work=The Globe and Mail |date=29 September 2014 |first1=SHEEMA |last1=KHAN |accessdate=13 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119055307/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/another-battle-with-islams-true-believers/article20802390/ |archive-date=19 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=jebara>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/fruits-of-the-tree-of-extremism|title=Imam Mohamad Jebara: Fruits of the tree of extremism|author=Mohamad Jebara More Mohamad Jebara|work=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=2019-01-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510165202/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/fruits-of-the-tree-of-extremism|archive-date=2019-05-10|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=hasan-balance-2012>[http://www.quilliamfoundation.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/publications/free/the-balance-of-islam-in-challenging-extremism.pdf The Balance of Islam in Challenging Extremism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802045255/http://www.quilliamfoundation.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/publications/free/the-balance-of-islam-in-challenging-extremism.pdf |date=2014-08-02 }}| Dr. Usama Hasan| 2012| quilliam foundation</ref> However, IS preachers strongly reject being compared to the Khawarij.<ref>{{cite news|title=Counter-radicalisation (3): A disarming approach: Can the beliefs that feed terrorism be changed?|url=https://www.economist.com/news/international/21695876-can-beliefs-feed-terrorism-be-changed-disarming-approach|accessdate=4 April 2016|work=[[The Economist]]|date=2 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404032828/http://www.economist.com/news/international/21695876-can-beliefs-feed-terrorism-be-changed-disarming-approach|archive-date=4 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ibadi]]s, a fellow early sect with similar beliefs, form the majority of the population of [[Oman]] (where they first settled in 686),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/mu.html#People |title=CIA - The World Factbook |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] |date=June 5, 2013 |accessdate=June 10, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516023047/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook//geos/mu.html#People |archive-date=May 16, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and there are smaller concentrations of them in the [[M'zab]] of [[Algeria]], [[Djerba]] in [[Tunisia]], the [[Nafusa Mountains]] in [[Libya]], and [[Zanzibar]].\n\nIn the 18th century, Hanafi scholar [[Ibn Abidin]] declared the [[Wahhabi movement]] of [[Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab]] as modern Khawarij although he does not consider them non-Muslims.<ref name=Ahmad-IMVEL-164>{{cite book|last1=Ahmad|first1=Ahmad Atif|title=Islam, Modernity, Violence, and Everyday Life|date=2009|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan.|page=164|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ccbIAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA164&dq=Khawarij+wahhab++Ibn+Abidin#v=onepage&q=Khawarij%20wahhab%20%20Ibn%20Abidin&f=false|accessdate=9 January 2016|isbn=9780230619562}}</ref>\n<ref>Khaled Abou El Fadl, \"9/11 and the Muslim Transformation.\" Taken from [https://books.google.com/books?id=m-ZLkRpYQWMC&pg=PA87&dq=khawarij+wahabi&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ncoRUtnsD6HF2QX2o4GgAw&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=khawarij%20wahabi&f=false September 11 in History: A Watershed Moment?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125212133/https://books.google.com/books?id=m-ZLkRpYQWMC&pg=PA87&dq=khawarij+wahabi&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ncoRUtnsD6HF2QX2o4GgAw&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=khawarij%20wahabi&f=false |date=2018-11-25 }}, pg. 87. Ed. [[Mary L. Dudziak]]. [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]]: [[Duke University Press]] 2003. {{ISBN|9780822332428}}</ref>\n\n== Principal groups ==\n* [[Azariqa]], the followers of Nafi ibn al-Azraq al-Hanaf\u012b al-Handhal\u012b\n* [[Najdat]], the followers of [[Najdah ibn 'Amir]]\n* [[Ibadi]]s, the followers of [[Abd-Allah ibn Ibadh|Abd Allah ibn Ibad]] are not the same ideology as the khawarij but share similar beliefs.\n* [[Sufri]]s, the followers of [[Ziyad ibn al-Asfar]] and [[Umran ibn Hattan]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kharijite Rebellion (866\u2013896)]]\n*[[Murji'ah]]\n*[[Salafism]]\n*[[Succession to Muhammad]]\n*[[Wahhabism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{EI2|last=Djebli|first=Moktar|authorlink=|title=Ta\u1e25k\u012bm|pages=107\u2013108|volume=10}}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Donner |first = Fred M. |author-link = Fred Donner |title = Muhammad and the Believers, at the Origins of Islam |year = 2010 |publisher = [[Harvard University Press]] |location = Cambridge, MA |isbn = 9780674050976 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=YM8RBAAAQBAJ }}\n* {{EI2|last=Levi Della Vida|first=G.|authorlink=Giorgio Levi Della Vida|title=Kh\u0101ridjites|pages=1074\u20131077|volume=4}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|ref=harv|last=Francesca|first= Ersilia | year= 2006 | title=Kh\u0101rij\u012bs |encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02be\u0101n|volume=3: J\u2013O|editor-last=McAuliffe|editor-first=Jane Dammen|publisher=E. J. Brill|pp=84\u201389|doi= 10.1163/1875-3922_q3_EQCOM_00103}}\n* {{cite journal |ref = harv |last = Hawting |first = Gerald R. |title = The Significance of the Slogan \"l\u0101 hukma ill\u0101 lill\u0101h\" and the References to the \"Hud\u016bd\" in the Traditions about the Fitna and the Murder of 'Uthm\u0101n |journal = Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies |year = 1978 |volume = 41 |number = 3 |pages = 453\u2013463 |jstor = 615490}}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Madelung |first = Wilferd |author-link=Wilferd Madelung |title = The Succession to Muhammad: A Study of the Early Caliphate |url = https://books.google.de/books?id=2QKBUwBUWWkC |year = 1997 |publisher = Cambridge University Press |location = Cambridge, England |isbn = 0521646960 }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Morony|first=Michael|author-link=Michael G. Morony|year=1984|title=Iraq After the Muslim Conquest|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|location=Princeton|isbn=0-691-05395-2}}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Rotter |first = Gernot |year = 1982 |title = Die Umayyaden und der zweite B\u00fcrgerkrieg (680-692) |language = de |publisher = Deutsche Morgenl\u00e4ndische Gesellschaft |location = Wiesbaden |url = https://books.google.de/books?id=NuANAAAAYAAJ |isbn = 9783515029131 }}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Watt |first = W. Montgomery |year = 1973 |author-link = W. Montgomery Watt |title = The Formative Period of Islamic Thought |publisher = [[Edinburgh University Press]] |location = Edinburgh, Scotland |url = https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.137377/page/n3 |isbn = 9780852242452 }}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Wellhausen |first = Julius |year = 1901 |author-link = Julius Wellhausen |title = Die religi\u00f6s-politischen Oppositionsparteien im alten Islam |language = de |url = https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.358135 |publisher = Weidmannsche buchhandlung |location = Berlin|oclc = 453206240 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite encyclopedia | title = Kharijites in Persia | last = Bosworth | first = C. Edmund | authorlink = Clifford Edmund Bosworth | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/kharijites-in-persia | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica | pages = | location = | publisher = | year = 2009 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Al-Yaqoubi | first = Muhammad |authorlink=Muhammad al-Yaqoubi| year = 2015 | title = Refuting ISIS: A Rebuttal Of Its Religious And Ideological Foundations | publisher = Sacred Knowledge |isbn=978-1908224125| title-link = Refuting ISIS: A Rebuttal Of Its Religious And Ideological Foundations }}\n* J. J. Saunders, A History of Medieval Islam, Routledge (UK), 1 October 1972 {{ISBN|0-415-05914-3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.islamfact.com/ Ibadhi Islam site]\n*[http://www.islamfrominside.com/Pages/Articles/Hermeneutics%20of%20takfir.html Hermeneutics of Takfir]\n\n{{Islamic Theology|state=uncollapsed|schools}}\n{{Theology}}\n{{Islam topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Kharijism| ]]\n", "name_user": "AhmadLX", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSecond Fitna:harv fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khawarij"}
{"title_page": "Andean condor", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Vultur|the birds known as vultures|Vulture}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|A large South American bird in the New World vulture family }}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Andean condor\n| fossil_range = {{Fossil range|2.6|0}}<small>Late [[Pliocene]]\u2013[[Holocene]]</small>\n| image = Andean Condor in flight.jpg\n| image_caption = Soaring over [[Arequipa]] in southern [[Peru]].\n| status = NT\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|title= ''Vultur gryphus'' |author= [[BirdLife International]] |year= 2017 |page= e.T22697641A117360971 |access-date= 18 January 2020|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Vultur\n| parent_authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| species = gryphus\n| authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| synonyms =\n* ''Vultur fossilis'' <small>[[Francisco Moreno|Moreno]] & Mercerat, 1891</small>\n* ''Vultur patruus'' <small>[[Einar L\u00f6nnberg|L\u00f6nnberg]], 1902</small>\n* ''Vultur pratruus'' <small>Emslie, 1988 (''lapsus'')</small>\n| range_map = AndeanMap.png\n| range_map_caption = Yellow \u2013 approximate range/distribution\n}}\n\nThe '''Andean condor''' (''Vultur gryphus'') is a South American bird in the [[New World vulture]] family [[Cathartidae]] and is the only member of the [[genus]] '''''Vultur'''''. Found in the [[Andes]] mountains and adjacent Pacific coasts of western South America, the Andean condor is the largest flying bird in the world by combined measurement of weight and wingspan. It has a maximum wingspan of {{convert|3.3|m|ftin|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Richard P. Reading|Brian Miller|2000}} exceeded only by the wingspans of four [[seabirds]] and [[water birds]]\u2014the roughly {{convert|3.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}} maximum of the [[wandering albatross]], [[southern royal albatross]], [[great white pelican]] and [[Dalmatian pelican]].<ref name=\"Ferguson-Lees\">{{cite book\n | last = Ferguson-Lees\n | first = James\n | author2 = Christie, David A.\n | title = Raptors of the World\n | publisher = Houghton Mifflin\n | year = 2001\n | location = Boston\n | isbn = 0-618-12762-3}}</ref>\n\nIt is a large black vulture with a ruff of white feathers surrounding the base of the neck and, especially in the male, large white patches on the wings. The head and neck are nearly featherless, and are a dull red color, which may flush and therefore change color in response to the bird's emotional state. In the male, there is a wattle on the neck and a large, dark red [[Comb (anatomy)|comb]] or caruncle on the crown of the head. Unlike most [[bird of prey|birds of prey]], the male is larger than the female.\n\nThe condor is primarily a [[scavenger]], feeding on [[carrion]]. It prefers large carcasses, such as those of [[deer]] or [[cattle]]. It reaches sexual maturity at five or six years of age and [[Bird nest|nests]] at elevations of up to {{convert|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}}, generally on inaccessible rock ledges. One or two eggs are usually laid. It is one of the world's longest-living birds, with a lifespan of over 70 years in some cases.\n\nThe Andean condor is a national symbol of [[Argentina]], [[Bolivia]], [[Chile]], [[Colombia]], [[Ecuador]], and [[Peru]] and plays an important role in the [[folklore]] and [[mythology]] of the Andean regions. The Andean condor is considered [[Near Threatened|near threatened]] by the [[IUCN]].<ref name=IUCN/> It is threatened by habitat loss and by [[secondary poisoning]] from carcasses killed by hunters. [[Captive breeding]] programs have been instituted in several countries.\n\n==Taxonomy and systematics==\nThe Andean condor was described by [[Sweden|Swedish]] scientist [[Carl Linnaeus]] in 1758 in the [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|tenth edition]] of his ''[[Systema Naturae]]'' and retains its original [[binomial nomenclature|binomial]] name of ''Vultur gryphus''.<ref>{{cite book | last=Linnaeus | first=C | authorlink=Carl Linnaeus | title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. Tomus I. Editio decima, reformata. | volume=v.1 | quote = V. maximus, car\u00fancula verticali longitudine capitis. | publisher=Laurentii Salvii | place=Holmiae (Stockholm) | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/726991 | year=1758| page=86 | language=Latin }}</ref> The Andean condor is sometimes called the Argentinean condor, Bolivian condor, Chilean condor, Colombian condor, Ecuadorian condor, or Peruvian condor after one of the nations to which it is native. The generic term ''Vultur'' is directly taken from the [[Latin]] ''vultur'' or ''voltur'', which means \"vulture\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Simpson | first = D.P. | title = Cassell's Latin Dictionary | publisher = Cassell Ltd. | year = 1979 | edition = 5th | location = London | page = 883 | isbn = 0-304-52257-0}}</ref> Its specific epithet is derived from a variant of the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] word \u03b3\u03c1\u03c5\u03c0\u03cc\u03c2 (''grup\u00f3s'', \"hook-nosed\").<ref>{{cite book|last=Liddell|first=Henry George|author2=Robert Scott|year=1980|title=Greek-English Lexicon, Abridged Edition|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=0-19-910207-4|url=https://archive.org/details/lexicon00lidd}}</ref> The word condor itself is derived from the [[Quechua language|Quechua]] ''kuntur''.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia| title=Raven|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary|editor1=J. Simpson |editor2=E. Weiner | year=1989 |edition= 2nd| location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn= 0-19-861186-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quechua.org.uk/Eng/Main/AnalysisMainFrame.htm |title=A Quechua metaphor for a plane: Kuntur-man = \"looking like a Condor\" |publisher=Quechua.org.uk |accessdate=2010-03-20}}</ref>\n\nThe exact [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] placement of the Andean condor and the remaining six species of [[New World vulture]]s remains unclear.<ref name=\"SACC\"/> Although both are similar in appearance and have similar [[ecological niche|ecological roles]], the New World and [[Old World vultures]] evolved from different ancestors in different parts of the world and are not closely related. Just how different the two families are is currently under debate, with some earlier authorities suggesting that the New World vultures are more closely related to [[storks]].<ref name=\"SibleyMonroe\">[[Charles Sibley|Sibley, Charles G.]] and Monroe, Burt L. (1990). ''[https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN0300049692 Distribution and Taxonomy of the Birds of the World]''. Yale University Press. {{ISBN|0-300-04969-2}}. Retrieved 2007-04-11.</ref> More recent authorities maintain their overall position in the order [[Falconiformes]] along with the Old World vultures<ref name=Sibley1991/> or place them in their own order, Cathartiformes.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1098/rsbl.2006.0523|title=Diversification of Neoaves: Integration of molecular sequence data and fossils|year=2006|last1=Ericson|first1=P. G.P|last2=Anderson|first2=C. L|last3=Britton|first3=T.|last4=Elzanowski|first4=A.|last5=Johansson|first5=U. S|last6=Kallersjo|first6=M.|last7=Ohlson|first7=J. I|last8=Parsons|first8=T. J|last9=Zuccon|first9=D.|displayauthors=8|journal=Biology Letters|volume=2|issue=4|pages=543\u20137|pmid=17148284|pmc=1834003}}</ref> The [[South American Classification Committee]] has removed the New World vultures from [[Ciconiiformes]] and instead described them as ''[[incertae sedis]]'', but notes that a move to Falconiformes or Cathartiformes is possible.<ref name=\"SACC\">Remsen, J. V., Jr.; Cadena, C. D.; Jaramillo, A.; Nores, M.; Pacheco, J. F.; Robbins, M. B.; Schulenberg, T. S.; Stiles, F. G.; Stotz, D. F. and Zimmer, K. J. (2007). [http://www.museum.lsu.edu/~Remsen/SACCBaseline.html ''A classification of the bird species of South America.''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302073659/http://www.museum.lsu.edu/~Remsen/SACCBaseline.html |date=2009-03-02 }} South American Classification Committee. Retrieved on 2007-10-15</ref>\n\nThe Andean condor is the only accepted living species of its genus, ''Vultur''.<ref>{{cite web\n | title = ''Vultur gryphus''\n | publisher = Integrated Taxonomic Information System\n | url = http://itis.gov/servlet/SingleRpt/SingleRpt?search_topic=TSN&search_value=175279\n | accessdate = 2008-01-13}}</ref> Unlike the [[California condor]] (''Gymnogyps californianus''), which is known from extensive [[fossil]] remains and some additional ones of [[:wiktionary:congener|congeners]], the fossil record of the Andean condor recovered to date is scant. Presumed [[Plio-Pleistocene]] species of South American condors were later recognized to be not different from the present species, although one known only from a few rather small bones found in a Pliocene deposit of [[Tarija Department]], Bolivia, may have been a smaller [[chronospecies|palaeosubspecies]], ''V. gryphus patruus''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Fisher, Harvey L. |year=1944|title= The skulls of the Cathartid vultures|journal=[[Condor (journal)|Condor]]|volume=46|issue=6|pages= 272\u2013296|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v046n06/p0272-p0296.pdf| doi = 10.2307/1364013| jstor = 1364013}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Vultur gryphus head (Linnaeus, 1758).jpg|right|thumb|There is a dark red caruncle (or comb) on the top of the head of the adult male.]]\n\n[[File:Vultur gryphus -Franklin Park Zoo, Massachusetts, USA -female-8a (1).jpg|right|thumb|Adult female at [[Franklin Park Zoo]], USA]]\n[[File:Vultur gryphus talon.jpg|thumb|right|Detail of talon showing elongated middle toe]]\nAlthough the California condor is, from beak to tail, about 7 to 8&nbsp;cm longer, the Andean condor has a wider wingspan, which ranges from {{convert|270|-|320|cm|ftin|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Ferguson-Lees\"/> It is also typically heavier, reaching a weight of {{convert|11|to|15|kg|lb|abbr=on}} for males and {{convert|8|to|11|kg|lb|abbr=on}} for females.<ref name=\"Handbookof\">{{cite book |title=Handbook of the Birds of the World |last1=del Hoyo |first1=J | last2=Elliot | first2 = A | last3=Sargatal | first3 = J | year=1996 |publisher=[[Lynx Edicions]] |location=[[Barcelona]] |isbn=84-87334-20-2|volume=3|title-link=Handbook of the Birds of the World }}</ref> Overall length can range from {{convert|100|to|130|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Handbookof\" /> Among standard measurements, the [[Wing chord (biology)|wing chord]] is {{convert|75.7|-|85.2|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the [[tail]] is {{convert|33|-|38|cm|in|abbr=on}} and the [[Tarsus (skeleton)|tarsus]] is {{convert|11.5|-|12.5|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Ferguson-Lees\"/> Measurements are usually taken from specimens reared in captivity.<ref name=\"Ferguson-Lees\"/> The mean weight is {{convert|11.3|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, with the males averaging about a kilogram more at {{convert|12.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, the females a kilogram less at {{convert|10.1|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Condors possess the heaviest average weight for any living flying bird or animal, ahead of [[trumpeter swan]]s (''Cygnus buccinator'') and [[Dalmatian pelican]]s (''Pelecanus crispus'').<ref name = \"CRC\">''CRC Handbook of Avian Body Masses, 2nd Edition'' by John B. Dunning Jr. (Editor). CRC Press (2008), {{ISBN|978-1-4200-6444-5}}.</ref><ref>Wallace, M. P., & Temple, S. A. (1987). ''Competitive interactions within and between species in a guild of avian scavengers''. The Auk, 290-295.</ref> However, other sources claim a mean species body mass of {{convert|10.3|kg|lb|abbr=on}} for the Andean condor.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Atanasov | first1 = A. T. | year = 2007 | title = The near to linear allometric relationship between total metabolic energy per life span and body mass of nonpasserine birds | url = | journal = Bulgarian Journal of Veterinary Medicine | volume = 10 | issue = 4| pages = 235\u2013245 }}</ref> The Andean condor is the largest living land bird capable of flight if measured in terms of average weight and wingspan, although male [[bustard]]s of the largest species (far more sexually dimorphic in size) can weigh more.<ref name=\"Handbookof\" /><ref>[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=3822 Andean Condor ''Vultur gryphus'']. Birdlife International.</ref><ref name=\"Wood\">{{cite book| author = Wood, Gerald| title = The Guinness Book of Animal Facts and Feats| year = 1983| isbn = 978-0-85112-235-9| url = https://archive.org/details/guinnessbookofan00wood| publisher = Enfield, Middlesex : Guinness Superlatives}}</ref> The mean wingspan is around {{convert|283|cm|ftin|0|abbr=on}} and the wings have the largest surface area of any extant bird.<ref name=\"Wood\"/> Among living bird species, only the [[great albatross]]es and the two largest species of [[pelican]] exceed the Andean condor in average and maximal wingspan.<ref name=\"Wood\"/><ref name=\"Harrison\">Harrison, Peter, ''Seabirds: An Identification Guide''. Houghton Mifflin Harcourt (1991), {{ISBN|978-0-395-60291-1}}</ref>\n[[File:Vultur gryphus -Dou\u00e9-la-Fontaine Zoo, France-8a.jpg|left|thumb|Female at Dou\u00e9-la-Fontaine Zoo, France.]]\n[[File:AndeanCondorMale.jpg|right|thumb|Male at the [[Cincinnati Zoo]].]]\nThe adult [[plumage]] is a uniform black, except for a frill of white feathers at the base of the neck and, especially in the male, large bands of white on the wings, which only appear after the bird's first [[moult]].<ref name=\"Hilty\">{{cite book\n | last =Hilty\n | first =Stephen L.\n | title =A Guide to the Birds of Colombia\n | publisher =Princeton University Press\n | year =1977\n | page =88\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=1k5fV_hQqE8C&pg=PA88\n | isbn =0-691-08372-X }}</ref> The head and neck are red to blackish-red and have few feathers. The head and neck are meticulously kept clean by the bird,<ref name=CleMet3>{{cite web\n |title=Behavior of the Andean Condor \n |publisher=Cleveland Metroparks Zoo \n |url=http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/behavior.htm \n |accessdate=2007-01-10 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219194934/http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/behavior.htm \n |archivedate=19 December 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> and their baldness is an adaptation for hygiene, allowing the skin to be exposed to the [[Sterilization (microbiology)|sterilizing]] effects of [[dehydration]] and [[ultraviolet light]] at high altitudes.<ref name=\"Patagonia\">{{cite book | last = Lutz | first = Dick|author2=Lutz, Richard L.| title = Patagonia: At the Bottom of the World | publisher = DIMI Press | year = 2002| pages = [https://archive.org/details/patagonia00rich/page/71 71]\u201374|url=https://archive.org/details/patagonia00rich | url-access = registration | isbn = 0-931625-38-6}}</ref> The crown of the head is flattened. In the male, the head is crowned with a dark red caruncle or comb, while the skin of his neck lies in folds, forming a wattle.<ref name=\"Hilty\"/> When condors are agitated (for example, during courtship), their head and neck flush, a clear signal to animals nearby. Juveniles have a grayish-brown general coloration, blackish head and neck skin, and a brown ruff.\n<ref name=\"Blake\">{{cite book\n | author = Blake, Emmet Reid\n | title =Birds of Mexico: A Guide for Field Identification\n | publisher =University of Chicago Press\n | year =1953\n | pages =[https://archive.org/details/birdsofmexicogui00blak/page/262 262]\u2013263\n | url =https://archive.org/details/birdsofmexicogui00blak\n | url-access = registration\n | isbn= 0-226-05641-4}}</ref>\n\nThe middle toe is greatly elongated, and the hind one is only slightly developed, while the talons of all the toes are comparatively straight and blunt. The feet are thus more adapted to walking, and are of little use as weapons or organs of [[prehension]] as in birds of prey and [[Old World vulture]]s.<ref name=\"Feduccia\"/> The beak is hooked, and adapted to tear rotting meat.<ref name=\"SanDiego\"/> The [[iris (anatomy)|irises]] of the male are brown, while those of the female are deep red.<ref name=\"Smithsonian\"/> They have no eyelashes.<ref name=\" Pterylosis \">{{Cite journal| last = Fisher| first = Harvey L.| title = The Pterylosis of the Andean Condor|url=http://sora.unm.edu/node/99237 | journal = [[Condor (journal)|Condor]]| volume = 44 | issue = 1| pages = 30\u201332| year = 1942| doi = 10.2307/1364195| jstor =1364195 }}</ref> Unlike the case with most other [[bird of prey|birds of prey]],<ref>{{cite book\n  |last = Andersson\n  |first = Malte B.\n  |title = Sexual selection\n  |publisher = Princeton University Press\n  |year = 1994\n  |page = 269\n  |accessdate = 19 July 2010\n  |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lNnHdvzBlTYC\n  |isbn = 978-0-691-00057-2}}</ref> the female is smaller.<ref>{{cite book\n  |last1 = Arnold\n  |first1 = Caroline\n  |last2 = Wallace\n  |first2 = Michael Phillip\n  |last3 = Wallace\n  |first3 = Michael\n  |title = On the brink of extinction: the California condor\n  |publisher = Houghton Mifflin Harcourt\n  |year = 1993\n  |page = 11\n  |accessdate = 19 July 2010\n  |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dQYHp0csAvcC\n  |isbn = 978-0-15-257990-6}}</ref>\n\nObservation of wing color patterns, and the size and shape of the male\u2019s crest, are the best ways of identifying individual Andean condors. Sighting-resighting methods assess the size and structure of populations.<ref>{{cite journal |author1= M\u00e9ndez, D. |author2= Marsden, S. | author3= Lloyd, H. | year=2019| title= Assessing population size and structure for Andean Condor Vultur gryphus in Bolivia using a photographic 'capture\u2010recapture' method| journal=Ibis| volume=161| pages=  867\u2013877| doi= 10.1111/ibi.12681| issue=4| doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n[[File:Condor des Andes m\u00e2le adulte.jpg|thumb|right| Andean condor, in Chilean national park [[Torres del Paine]]]]\nThe Andean condor is found in [[South America]] in the [[Andes]] including the [[Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta|Santa Marta Mountains]]. In the north, its range begins in [[Venezuela]] and Colombia, where it is extremely rare,<ref name=\"BirdLife\"/> then continues south along the Andes in Ecuador, Peru, and Chile, through Bolivia and western Argentina to the [[Tierra del Fuego]].<ref name=\"Blake\"/> In the early 19th century, the Andean condor bred from western Venezuela to Tierra del Fuego, along the entire chain of the Andes, but its range has been greatly reduced due to human activity.<ref name=\"Haemig \"/> Its habitat is mainly composed of open grasslands and alpine areas up to {{convert|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}} in elevation. It prefers relatively open, non-forested areas which allow it to spot carrion from the air, such as the [[p\u00e1ramo]] or rocky, mountainous areas in general.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Habitat of the Andean Condor \n |publisher=Cleveland Metroparks Zoo \n |url=http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/habitat.htm \n |accessdate=2007-01-10 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061220141630/http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/habitat.htm \n |archivedate=20 December 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> It occasionally ranges to lowlands in eastern Bolivia, northern Peru, and southwestern Brazil,<ref name=\"SibleyMonroe\"/> descends to lowland desert areas in Chile and Peru, and is found over [[Nothofagus|southern-beech]] forests in [[Patagonia]].<ref name=\"BirdLife\"/> In southern Patagonia, meadows are important for Andean condors as this habitat is likely to have herbivores present. In this region, Andean condor distributions are therefore influenced by the locations of meadows as well as cliffs for nesting and roosting.<ref>{{cite journal |author1= P\u00e9rez\u2010Garc\u00eda, J.M. |author2= S\u00e1nchez\u2010Zapata, J.A. | author3= Lambertucci, S.A. | author4= Hiraldo, F. | author5= Don\u00e1zar, J.A | year=2018| title= Low\u2010frequency, threatened habitats drive the large\u2010scale distribution of Andean Condors in southern Patagonia| journal=Ibis| volume=160| pages= 647\u2013658 | doi=10.1111/ibi.12563| issue=3}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology and behavior==\n[[File:Andean Condor in full flight.JPG|thumb|left|Andean condors often spend much of their time soaring on montane updraughts.]]\nThe condor soars with its wings held horizontally and its [[primary feather]]s bent upwards at the tips.<ref name=\"Hilty\"/> The lack of a large [[sternum]] to anchor its correspondingly large flight muscles physiologically identifies it as primarily being a soarer. It flaps its wings on rising from the ground, but after attaining a moderate elevation it flaps its wings very rarely, relying on thermals to stay aloft.<ref name=\"Wehner\"/> [[Charles Darwin]] commented on having watched them for half an hour without once observing a flap of their wings.<ref>{{cite book\n | last =Darwin\n | first= Charles\n | title =The Voyage of the Beagle\n | publisher =P.F. Collier\n | year =1909\n | page=[https://archive.org/details/voyagebeagle00darwgoog/page/n209 201]\n | url= https://archive.org/details/voyagebeagle00darwgoog}}</ref> It prefers to roost on high places from which it can launch without major wing-flapping effort. Andean condors are often seen soaring near rock cliffs, using the heat [[thermals]] to aid them in rising in the air.<ref name=\"Benson\">{{cite book\n |author1=Benson, Sara  |author2=Paul Hellander\n | title =Peru\n | publisher =Lonely Planet Publications\n | year =2007\n | page=[https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetperu00sara_0/page/53 53]\n | url= https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetperu00sara_0\n |url-access=registration  | isbn = 978-1-74059-749-4}}</ref>\n\nLike other [[New World vulture]]s, the Andean condor has the unusual habit of [[urohidrosis]]: it often empties its [[cloaca]] onto its legs and feet. A cooling effect through [[evaporative cooling|evaporation]] has been proposed as a reason for this behavior, but it does not make any sense in the cold Andean habitat of the bird.<ref name=Sibley1991>{{cite book\n |author1=Sibley, Charles G.  |author2=Jon E. Ahlquist\n | title =Phylogeny and Classification of Birds: A Study in Molecular Evolution\n | publisher =Yale University Press\n | year =1991\n | url= https://books.google.com/books?visbn=0300040857\n | isbn = 0-300-04085-7}}</ref> Because of this habit, their legs are often streaked with a white buildup of [[uric acid]].<ref name=\"Feduccia\">{{cite book\n | last =Feduccia\n | first =J. Alan\n | title =The Origin and Evolution of Birds\n | publisher =Yale University Press\n | year =1999\n | page =300\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=8QRKV7eSqmIC&pg=PA300\n | isbn =0-226-05641-4 }}</ref>\n\nThere is a well-developed social structure within large groups of condors, with competition to determine a 'pecking order' by body language, competitive play behavior, and [[Bird vocalization|vocalizations]].<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Donazard\n | first = Jos\u00e9 A\n | author2 = Feijoo, Juan E.\n | title = Social structure of Andean Condor roosts: Influence of sex, age, and season\n | journal =[[Condor (journal)|Condor]]\n | volume = 104\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 832\u2013837\n | publisher =Cooper Ornithological Society\n | url = http://cat.inist.fr/?aModele=afficheN&cpsidt=14022914\n | accessdate =2008-01-10\n | doi = 10.1650/0010-5422(2002)104[0832:SSOACR]2.0.CO;2\n | year = 2002\n | issn = 0010-5422 | hdl = 10261/65935\n | hdl-access = free\n }}</ref> Generally, mature males tend to be at the top of the pecking order, with post-dispersal immature males tending to be near the bottom.<ref name=\"Ferguson-Lees\"/>\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Vultur gryphus MWNH 0718.JPG|left|thumb|Egg, Collection [[Museum Wiesbaden]]]]\n[[File:Condor02 ST 98.jpg|thumb|right|A juvenile condor in [[Colca Canyon]], [[Peru]].]]\n[[File:Condor des andes immature.jpg|thumb|right|A young female Andean condor, in [[Nahuel Huapi National Park]], [[Argentina]].]]\n\nSexual maturity and breeding behavior do not appear in the Andean condor until the bird is five or six years of age.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Andean Condor (''Vultur Gryphus'') \n |publisher=[[The Peregrine Fund]] \n |url=http://www.peregrinefund.org/explore_raptors/vultures/andcondr.html \n |accessdate=2007-01-10 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205055624/http://www.peregrinefund.org/Explore_Raptors/vultures/andcondr.html \n |archivedate=5 February 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> It may live to 50 years or more, and it mates for life.<ref name=\"Tait\"/> During courtship displays, the skin of the male's neck flushes, changing from dull red to bright yellow, and inflates.<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Whitson\n | first = Martha A\n | author2 = Whitson, Paul D.\n | title = Breeding Behavior of the Andean Condor (''Vultur Gryphus'')\n | journal =[[Condor (journal)|Condor]]\n | volume = 71\n | pages = 73\u201375\n | publisher =Cooper Ornithological Society\n | year =1968\n | url =http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v071n01/p0073-p0075.pdf\n | accessdate = 2007-01-10\n | doi = 10.2307/1366056 | jstor = 1366056\n | issue = 1}}</ref> He approaches the female with neck outstretched, revealing the inflated neck and the chest patch, while hissing,<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Gailey\n | first = Janet\n | author2 = Bolwig, Neils\n | title =Observations on the Breeding Behavior of the Andean Condor (''Vultur Gryphus'')\n | journal =[[Condor (journal)|Condor]]\n | publisher =Cooper Ornithological Society\n | volume = 75\n | pages = 60\u201368\n | year =1973\n | url =http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v075n01/p0060-p0068.pdf\n | accessdate = 2007-01-10\n | doi =10.2307/1366535 | jstor = 1366535\n | issue = 1}}</ref> then extends his wings and stands erect while clicking his tongue.<ref name=\"Smithsonian\"/> Other courtship rituals include hissing and clucking while hopping with wings partially spread, and dancing.<ref name=\"Patagonia\"/> The Andean condor prefers to roost and breed at elevations of {{convert|3000|to|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Fjelds\u00e5\">{{cite book\n | last = Fjelds\u00e5\n | first =Jon\n | author2= Krabbe, Niels\n | title =Birds of the High Andes\n | publisher =Apollo Books\n | year =1990\n | page =90\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=NmXSeVrmlgIC\n | isbn =87-88757-16-1 }}</ref> Its nest, which consists of a few sticks placed around the eggs, is created on inaccessible ledges of rock. However, in coastal areas of Peru, where there are few cliffs, some nests are simply partially shaded crannies scraped out against boulders on slopes.<ref name=\"Haemig \"/> It deposits one or two bluish-white [[egg (biology)|eggs]], weighing about {{convert|280|g|oz|abbr=on}} and ranging from {{convert|75|to|100|mm|in|abbr=on}} in length, during the months of February and March every second year. The egg hatches after 54 to 58&nbsp;days of [[Avian incubation|incubation]] by both parents.<ref name=\"Smithsonian\">{{cite web\n |author=Friends of the Zoo \n |title=Andean Condor \n |publisher=Smithsonian National Zoological Park \n |url=http://nationalzoo.si.edu/Animals/Birds/Facts/FactSheets/fact-andeancondor.cfm \n |accessdate=2008-01-08 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009075845/http://nationalzoo.si.edu/Animals/Birds/Facts/FactSheets/fact-andeancondor.cfm \n |archivedate=2007-10-09 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> If the chick or egg is lost or removed, another egg is laid to take its place. Researchers and breeders take advantage of this behavior to double the reproductive rate by taking the first egg away for hand-rearing, causing the parents to lay a second egg, which they are generally allowed to raise.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| author=National Research Council\n | title = Scientific Bases for the Preservation of the Hawaiian Crow\n | publisher =National Academies Press\n | year = 1992\n | page =74\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=8cDX2mb07mcC&pg=PA74\n | isbn =0-309-04775-7 }}</ref>\n\nThe young are covered with a grayish down until they are almost as large as their parents. They are able to fly after six months,<ref name=\"Hilty\"/> but continue to roost and hunt with their parents until age two, when they are displaced by a new clutch.<ref>Cisneros-Heredia, Diego F. (2006). [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.177.5617&rep=rep1&type=pdf \"Notes on breeding, behaviour and distribution of some birds in Ecuador\"]. ''Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club'' '''126''' (2): 153\u2013164 contains a record of a juvenile accompanying an adult male in July, too early to have been of that year's cohort.</ref> Healthy adults have no natural predators, but large [[birds of prey]] and [[mammal]]ian predators, like [[South American fox|fox]]es and [[cougar]]s, may take eggs and  hatchlings, with large predators a possible but not confirmed threat to fledglings or infirm adults. Predation is relatively uncommon, since the vigilant parents often aggressively displace birds of prey who come near and the rocky, precipitous location of most nests are difficult for mammals to access.\n\n===Feeding===\nThe Andean condor is a [[scavenger]], feeding mainly on [[carrion]].<ref name=\"Wehner\">{{cite book\n | last =Wehner\n | first =Ross\n | author2= del Gaudio, Renee |author3=Jankowski, Kazia\n | title =Moon Peru\n | publisher =Avalon Travel\n | year =2007\n | page =180\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=2tVNa8P0inYC&pg=PA180\n | isbn =978-1-56691-983-8 }}</ref> Wild condors inhabit large territories, often traveling more than {{convert|200|km|mi|abbr=on}} a day in search of carrion.<ref name=\"Patagonia\"/> In inland areas, they prefer large carcasses. Naturally, they feed on the largest carcasses available, which can include [[llama]]s (''Lama glama''), [[alpaca]]s (''Vicugna pacos''), [[rhea (bird)|rhea]]s (''Rhea ssp.''), [[guanaco]]s (''Lama guanicoe''), [[deer]] and [[armadillo]]s. Wild individuals could acquire extra carotenoids from vegetal matter contained in carcass viscera and fresh vegetation.<ref name=\"Blanco2013\">{{cite journal  | last1=Blanco |first1=G. |last2=Hornero-M\u00e9ndez |first2=D. |last3=Lambertucci |first3=S.A. |last4=Don\u00e1zar |first4=J.A. |last5=Bautista |first5=L.M. |last6= Wiemeyer |first6=G. |last7=Sanchez-Zapata |first7=J.A. |last8=Garrido-Fern\u00e1ndez |first8=J. |last9=Hiraldo |first9=F.  |year=2013 |title=Need and seek for dietary micronutrients: endogenous regulation, external signaling and food sources of carotenoids in New World vultures |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=8 |issue=6 |page=e65562 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0065562 |pmid=23785435 |url=https://digital.csic.es/handle/10261/78234?locale=en |pmc=3681859|bibcode=2013PLoSO...865562B }}</ref> However, most inland condors now live largely off of domestic animals, which are now more widespread in South America, such as [[cattle]] (''Bos primigenius taurus''), [[horse]]s (''Equus ferus caballus''), [[donkey]]s (''Equus africanus asinus''), [[mule]]s, [[sheep]] (''Ovis aries''), [[pig]]s (''Sus scrofa domesticus''), [[goat]]s (''Capra aegagrus hircus'') and [[dog]]s (''Canis lupus familiaris''). They also feed on the carcasses of introduced game species such as [[wild boar]]s (''Sus scrofa''), [[rabbit]]s (''Oryctolagus cuniculus''), [[fox]]es (''Vulpes vulpes'') and [[red deer]] (''Cervus elaphus''). For condors who live around the coast, the diet consists mainly of beached carcasses of marine mammals, largely [[cetacean]]s.<ref name=\"Smithsonian\"/><ref name=\"ADW\"/> They will also raid the nests of smaller birds to feed on the eggs.<ref>{{cite web\n | title =Andean Condor (''Vultur Gryphus'')\n | publisher = [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]\n | url = http://animals.nationalgeographic.com/animals/birds/andean-condor.html\n | accessdate = 2007-01-10}}</ref> Andean condors have been observed to do some hunting of small, live animals, such as [[rodent]]s, [[bird]]s and [[rabbit]]s, which (given their lack of powerful, grasping feet or developed hunting technique) they usually kill by jabbing repeatedly with their bill.<ref name= ADW>[http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Vultur_gryphus.html ADW: Vultur gryphus: INFORMATION]. Animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu. Retrieved on 2012-12-19.</ref>\n[[File:Andean Condor skeleton.jpg|thumb|Andean condor skeleton ([[Museum of Osteology]])]]\nCoastal areas provide a constant food supply, and in particularly plentiful areas, some Andean condors limit their foraging area to several kilometers of beach-front land.<ref name=\"Haemig \">{{cite web\n |last=Haemig \n |first=PD \n |title=Ecology of Condors \n |publisher=Ecology Online Sweden \n |year=2007 \n |url=http://www.ecology.info/condors.htm \n |accessdate=March 30, 2009 \n}}</ref> They locate carrion by spotting it or by following other scavengers, such as [[corvid]]s or other vultures.<ref name=\"snyder\">{{cite book\n |author1=Snyder, Noel F. R.  |author2=Helen Snyder\n | title =Raptors of North America: Natural History and Conservation\n | publisher =Voyageur Press\n | page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780760325827/page/45 45]\n | year =2006\n | url= https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780760325827\n |url-access=registration  | isbn = 0-7603-2582-0}}</ref> It may follow New World vultures of the genus ''[[Cathartes]]''\u2014the [[turkey vulture]] (''C. aura''), the [[lesser yellow-headed vulture]] (''C. burrovianus''), and the [[greater yellow-headed vulture]] (''C. melambrotus'')\u2014to carcasses. The ''Cathartes'' vultures forage by smell, detecting the scent of [[Ethanethiol|ethyl mercaptan]], a gas produced by the beginnings of decay in dead animals. These smaller vultures cannot rip through the tougher hides of these larger animals with the efficiency of the larger condor, and their interactions are often an example of [[mutual dependence]] between species.<ref name=\"Dietland\">{{cite book\n | last =Muller-Schwarze\n | first =Dietland\n | title =Chemical Ecology of Vertebrates\n | publisher =Cambridge University Press\n | page=350\n | year =2006\n | url= https://books.google.com/?id=HaaFlUw4goIC&pg=PA1\n | isbn = 0-521-36377-2}}</ref> [[Black vulture]]s (''Coragyps atratus''), [[king vulture]]s (''Sarcoramphus papa'') and even mammalian scavengers may sometimes track ''Cathartes'' vultures for carcasses but the condor is invariably dominant among the scavengers in its range.<ref>[http://www.ecology.info/condors.htm Ecology of Condors: the California Condor and Andean Condor]. Ecology.info. Retrieved on 2012-12-19.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecology.info/condors.htm |title=Ecology of Condors |accessdate=2006-10-05 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001235133/http://www.ecology.info/condors.htm |archivedate=2006-10-01 }}. ecology.info.</ref> Andean condors are intermittent eaters in the wild, often going for a few days without eating, then gorging themselves on several pounds at once, sometimes to the point of being unable to lift off the ground. Because its feet and talons are not adapted to grasping, it must feed while on the ground.<ref name=\"Patagonia\"/> Like other carrion-feeders, it plays an important role in its [[ecosystem]] by disposing of carrion which would otherwise be a breeding ground for disease.<ref name=\"cotton\">{{cite journal\n |last=Gomez \n |title=The role of greater yellow-headed vultures Cathartes melambrotus as scavengers in neotropical forest \n |journal=Ibis \n |volume=136 \n |issue=2 \n |pages=193\u2013196 \n |year=1994 \n |url=http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=3646491&q=Cathartes+melambrotus&uid=791396595&setcookie=yes \n |accessdate=2008-01-06 \n |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1994.tb01084.x \n |first1=Luis G. \n |last2=Houston \n |first2=David C. \n |last3=Cotton \n |first3=Peter \n |last4=Tye \n |first4=Alan \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080129233040/http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=3646491&q=Cathartes+melambrotus&uid=791396595&setcookie=yes \n |archivedate=29 January 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\n===Longevity===\nBeing a slowly-maturing bird with no known natural predators in adulthood, an Andean condor is a long-lived bird. Longevity and mortality rates are not known to have been extensively studied in the wild. Some estimations of lifespans of wild birds has exceeded 50 years. In 1983, the [[Guinness Book of World Records]] considered the longest-lived bird of any species with a confirmed lifespan was an Andean condor that died after surviving 72 years in captivity, having been captured from the wild as a juvenile of undetermined age.<ref name=\"Wood\"/> Several species of [[parrot]] have been reported to live for perhaps over 100 years in captivity, but these (at least in 1983) were not considered authenticated.<ref name=\"Wood\"/> Another early captive-held specimen of condor reportedly lived for 71 years.<ref name=\"Wood\"/> However, these lifespans have been exceeded by a male, nicknamed \"Thaao\", that was kept at [[Beardsley Zoo]] in [[Connecticut]]. Thaao was born in captivity in 1930 and died on January 26, 2010, making him 79 years of age.<ref>[http://beardsleyzoo.org/node/150 Zoo Family Mourns Death of Oldest Living Andean Condor in Captivity | Connecticut's Beardsley Zoo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520105325/http://www.beardsleyzoo.org/node/150 |date=2012-05-20 }}. Beardsleyzoo.org (2010-01-26). Retrieved on 2012-12-19.</ref> This would be the greatest verified age ever known for a bird.<ref name=\"Wood\"/>\n\n==Relationship with humans==\n\n===Conservation status===\n[[File:Vultur gryphus -Taronga Zoo, Australia-8a.jpg|thumb|left|Adult male at [[Taronga Zoo]], Australia]]\nThe Andean condor is considered [[Near Threatened|near threatened]] by the [[IUCN]] and the Peruvian [[Conservation organizations|Conservation Organization]].<ref name=IUCN/> It was first placed on the United States [[Endangered Species]] list in 1970,<ref>{{cite web|title=Species Profile: Andean Condor |publisher=United States Department of Fish and Wildlife |url=http://ecos.fws.gov/speciesProfile/SpeciesReport.do?spcode=B03Y |accessdate=2007-10-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303165337/http://ecos.fws.gov/speciesProfile/SpeciesReport.do?spcode=B03Y |archivedate=March 3, 2009 }}</ref> a status which is assigned to an animal that is in danger of extinction throughout all or a significant portion of its range.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Endangered Species Program \n |publisher=United States Department of Fish and Wildlife \n |url=http://www.fws.gov/Endangered/wildlife.html \n |accessdate=2007-10-16 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070921072436/http://www.fws.gov/Endangered/wildlife.html \n |archivedate=2007-09-21 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> Threats to its population include loss of habitat needed for foraging, secondary poisoning from animals killed by hunters and persecution.<ref name=\"Reading\">{{cite book\n | last =Reading\n | first =Richard P.\n | author2 =Miller, Brian\n | title =Endangered Animals: A Reference Guide to Conflicting Issues\n | publisher =Greenwood Press\n | year =2000\n | page =16\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=f_AWCtX29-kC&pg=PA16\n | isbn = 0-313-30816-0}}</ref> It is threatened mainly in the northern area of its range, and is extremely rare in Venezuela and Colombia, where it has undergone considerable declines in recent years.<ref>{{cite book\n | last =Beletsky\n | first =Les\n | title =Birds of the World\n | publisher =JHU Press\n | year =2006\n | page =70\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=50_95BRVIjkC\n | isbn =0-8018-8429-2 }}</ref> Because it is adapted to very low mortality and has correspondingly low reproductive rates, it is extremely vulnerable to human persecution,<ref name=\"BirdLife\">{{cite web|title=Species factsheet: Vultur Gryphus |year=2004 |publisher=BirdLife International |url=http://www.redlist.org/search/details.php?species=40258 |accessdate=2008-01-04 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060305172904/http://www.redlist.org/search/details.php?species=40258 |archivedate=2006-03-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> most of which stems from the fact that it is perceived as a threat by farmers due to alleged attacks on livestock.<ref name=\"Tait\">{{cite book\n | last =Tait\n | first =Malcolm\n | title =Going, Going, Gone: Animals and Plants on the Brink of Extinction\n | publisher =Sterling Publishing\n | year =2006\n | page =[https://archive.org/details/goinggoinggone00thin/page/22 22]\n | url =https://archive.org/details/goinggoinggone00thin\n | url-access =registration\n | isbn = 1-84525-027-3}}</ref> Education programs have been implemented by conservationists to dispel this misconception.<ref name=\"Roach\"/> Reintroduction programs using captive-bred Andean condors, which release birds hatched in North American zoos into the wild to bolster populations,<ref name=\"Roach\">{{cite web\n | last =Roach\n | first =John\n | title =Peru's Andean Condors Are Rising Tourist Attraction\n | work = National Geographic News\n | publisher = [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]\n | date = 2004-07-22\n | url = http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2004/07/0722_040722_andeancondor.html\n | accessdate = 2007-01-10}}</ref> have been introduced in Argentina, Venezuela, and Colombia. The first captive-bred Andean condors were released into the wild in 1989.<ref>{{cite web\n |author=Conservation and Research for Endangered Species \n |title=Andean Condor Reintroduction Program \n |publisher=Zoological Society of San Diego \n |url=http://cres.sandiegozoo.org/projects/rb_condor_andean.html \n |accessdate=2007-01-10 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010112901/http://cres.sandiegozoo.org/projects/rb_condor_andean.html \n |archivedate=2006-10-10 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> When raising condors, human contact is minimal; chicks are fed with glove puppets which resemble adult Andean condors in order to prevent the chicks from [[imprinting (psychology)|imprinting]] on humans, which would endanger them upon release as they would not be wary of humans.<ref name=\"Pullin\"/> The condors are kept in aviaries for three months prior to release, where they acclimatize to an environment similar to that which they will be released in.<ref name=\"Pullin\">{{cite book\n | last = Pullin\n | first = Andrew S.\n | title = Conservation Biology\n | publisher = Cambridge University Press\n | year = 2002\n | page = 234\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=ED-8V8cE67UC&pg=PA234\n | isbn = 0-521-64482-8}}</ref> Released condors are tracked by satellite in order to observe their movements and to monitor whether they are still alive.<ref name=\"SanDiego\"/>\n\nIn response to the capture of all the wild individuals of the California condor, in 1988 the [[US Fish and Wildlife Service]] began a reintroduction experiment involving the release of captive Andean condors into the wild in [[California]]. Only females were released to prevent it becoming an [[invasive species]]. The experiment was a success, and all the Andean condors were recaptured and re-released in South America before the reintroduction of the California condors took place.<ref name=\"USFW\">{{cite web | title = California condor, (Gymnogyps californianus) | publisher= U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service| url = http://www.fws.gov/species/species_accounts/bio_cond.html| accessdate = 2007-08-14}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, local authorities of the [[Ancasmarca]] region rescued two Andean condors that were caged and displayed in a local market as an attraction for tourists.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.andina.com.pe/agencia/noticia-rescatan-dos-condores-andinos-eran-exhibidos-a-turistas-calca-cusco-509987.aspx Rescatan dos c\u00f3ndores andinos que eran exhibidos a turistas en Calca Cusco], ''Andina.com.pe'', 12 June 2014</ref>\n\n===Role in culture===\n[[File:Chancay Sleeved Tunic with Flying Condors.png|thumb|[[Chancay culture|Chancay]] textile with flying condors, 1200-1400 AD]]\nThe Andean condor is a national symbol of Argentina, Bolivia, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru and [[Andean Region, Venezuela|Venezuelan Andes]] states. It is the [[List of national birds|national bird]] of Bolivia, Chile, Colombia, and Ecuador.<ref>{{cite web\n | last =MacDonald\n | first =Tina\n | author2 = MacDonald, Duncan\n | title =National Birds\n | url =http://www.camacdonald.com/birding/CountryIndex.htm\n | accessdate = 2007-10-06 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071006063912/http://www.camacdonald.com/birding/CountryIndex.htm#A| archivedate= 6 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> It plays an important role in the [[folklore]] and [[mythology]] of the [[South American]] Andean regions,<ref name=\"Tait\"/> and has been represented in Andean art from c. 2500 BCE onward,<ref name=\"Werness\">{{cite book\n | last =Werness\n | first =Hope B.\n | title =The Continuum Encyclopedia of Animal Symbolism in Art\n | publisher =Continuum International Publishing Group\n | year =2004\n | page =103\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=fr2rANLrPmoC\n | isbn =0-8264-1525-3 }}</ref> and they are a part of indigenous Andean religions.<ref name=\"Howard-Malverde\">{{cite book\n | last =Howard-Malverde\n | first =Rosaleen\n | title =Creating Context in Andean Cultures\n | publisher =Oxford University Press\n | year =1997\n | page =16\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=t7ybxALxNfwC&pg=PA16\n | isbn =0-19-510914-7 }}</ref> In Andean mythology, the Andean condor was associated with the sun deity,<ref>{{cite book\n | last = Mundkur\n | first =Balaji\n | title =The Cult of the Serpent\n | publisher =SUNY Press\n | year =1983\n | page =129\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=PDkuiPhZJr0C\n | isbn =0-87395-631-1 }}</ref> and was believed to be the ruler of the upper world.<ref>{{cite book\n |author1=Mills, Alice |author2=Parker, Janet |author3=Stanton, Julie | title =Mythology: Myths, Legends and Fantasies\n | publisher =New Holland Publishers\n | year =2006\n | page =493\n | isbn =1-77007-453-8}}</ref> The Andean condor is considered a symbol of power and health by many Andean cultures, and it was believed that the bones and organs of the Andean condor possessed medicinal powers, sometimes leading to the hunting and killing of condors to obtain its bones and organs.<ref name=\"SanDiego\">{{cite web\n | title = Andean Condor\n | publisher = Zoological Society of San Diego\n | url = http://www.sandiegozoo.org/animalbytes/t-andean_condor.html\n | accessdate = 2007-01-10}}</ref><ref name=\"CleMet2\">{{cite web\n |title=History of the Andean Condor \n |publisher=Cleveland Metroparks Zoo \n |url=http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/history.htm \n |accessdate=2007-01-10 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219195345/http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/history.htm \n |archivedate=19 December 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> In some versions of Peruvian bullfighting, a condor is tied to the back of a bull, where it pecks at the animal as bullfighters fight it. The condor generally survives and is set free.<ref>{{cite book| last =Kokotovic| first =Misha| title = The Colonial Divide in Peruvian Narrative:Social Conflict and Transculturation | publisher = Sussex Academic Press| year = 2007| page =49| isbn =978-1-84519-184-9 }}</ref>\n\nIn Peru, they are occasionally shot, but more often revered and used for ceremonial purposes. The Yawar Fiesta is a celebration, the pinnacle of which is the tying of an Andean condor to the back of a bull, allowing the condor to kill the bull with its talons before being released. This ceremony is a symbolic representation of the power of the Andean peoples (the condor) over the Spanish (the bull).<ref>{{cite book| last =Arguedas| first =Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda| title = Yawar Fiesta| translator =  Frances Horning Barraclough| publisher = NorthWood, Inc.| year = 2002| isbn =1-55971-019-5 }}</ref> There is also a ceremony known as the ''arranque del condor'' in which a live Andean condor is suspended from a frame and is punched to death by horsemen as they ride by.<ref>{{cite book| last = Mackenzie| first = John P.S.| title = Birds of Prey| publisher = Waveland Pr Inc.| year = 2002| location = Toronto| page = [https://archive.org/details/yawarfiesta00jose/page/30 30]| isbn = 1-57766-245-8| url = https://archive.org/details/yawarfiesta00jose/page/30}}</ref>\n\n[[Condorito]] is a Chilean comic book and comic strip that features an anthropomorphic condor living in a fictitious town named Pelotillehue, a typical small Chilean provincial town. He is meant to be a representation of the Chilean people.\n\nThe Andean condor is a popular figure on [[postage stamp|stamps]] in many countries, appearing on one for Ecuador in 1958, Argentina in 1960, Peru in 1973, Bolivia in 1985, Colombia in 1992, Chile in 2001, and [[Venezuela]] in 2004.<ref name=\"Stamp \">{{cite web | title =Andean Condor | publisher =Bird Stamps | url = http://www.bird-stamps.org/cspecies/2800600.htm | accessdate = 2008-01-15}}</ref> It has also appeared on the coins and banknotes of Colombia and Chile.<ref>{{cite web | title =A Field Guide to the Birds on Banknotes | publisher =Krause Publications | url = http://members.tripod.com/~fieldguide/bobn.html | accessdate = 2008-01-16}}</ref> The condor is featured in several [[coat of arms|coats of arms]] of Andean countries as a symbol of [[Andes mountains]].\n\nThe Andean condor is depicted on the logo of [[Avianca]] and [[Aerolineas Argentinas]], which are two of the largest airlines in South America. \n{{gallery\n|title=National coat of arms\n|width=120 |height=100\n|align=center\n|File:Coat of arms of Bolivia.svg|[[Coat of arms of Bolivia|Coat of arms]] of [[Bolivia]].\n|File:Coat of arms of Chile.svg|[[Coat of arms of Chile|Coat of arms]] of [[Chile]].\n|File:Coat of arms of Colombia.svg|[[Coat of arms of Colombia|Coat of arms]] of [[Colombia]].\n|File:Coat of arms of Ecuador.svg|[[Coat of arms of Ecuador|Coat of arms]] of [[Ecuador]].\n|File:Escudo de la Rep\u00fablica Peruana (1821-1825).png|First [[Coat of arms of Peru|Coat of arms]] of [[Peru]].\n|File:Coat of arms of Venezuela (1812).svg|[[Coat of arms of Venezuela|Former coat of arms]] of [[Venezuela]].\n}}\n{{gallery\n|title=Others coat of arms\n|width=120 |height=100\n|align=center\n|File:Escudo de Pichincha.gif|Coat of arms of [[Pichincha Province]], [[Ecuador]].\n|File:Escudo de Chimborazo.svg|Coat of arms of [[Chimborazo Province]], [[Ecuador]].\n|File:Coat of arms of M\u00e9rida State.svg|Coat of arms of [[M\u00e9rida (state)|State of M\u00e9rida]], [[Venezuela]].\n|File:Imperial standard of the ethnocacerist movement.jpg|Imperial standard of the [[Movimiento Etnocacerista|Ethnocacerist Movement]], [[Peru]].\n|File:Escudo-UNAM-escalable.svg|[[National Autonomous University of Mexico]], depicting a condor and [[golden eagle]].\n|File:Uncuyo.jpg|[[National University of Cuyo]], [[Argentina]].\n}}\n{{gallery\n|title=Condor in popular culture\n|width=120 |height=100\n|align=center\n|File:Vultur gryphus Chili XIX.jpg|Hunting for condor. Chile, 1854.<ref>[http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.wdl/clsabn.3979 Atlas de la historia fisica y politica de Chile]. [Laminas, Volumen 1], 1854.</ref>\n|File:CondorLassoLyd.jpg|Argentinian [[gaucho]]s lassoing a condor, 1895.\n|File:60 cent Chile Condor.jpg|Stamp of Chile, 60 centavos, 1935.\n||[[Aero C\u00f3ndor]], an airline that flies over the Nazca lines in Peru.\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|33em}}\n* {{citation|author1=Richard P. Reading|author2=Brian Miller|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f_AWCtX29-kC&pg=PA16|title=Endangered Animals: A Reference Guide to Conflicting Issues|chapter=Andean Condor|p=[https://archive.org/details/endangeredanimal0000unse_m4q9/page/16 16]|date=2000|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-03-1330-816-1|ref={{sfnref|Richard P. Reading|Brian Miller|2000}}|url=https://archive.org/details/endangeredanimal0000unse_m4q9/page/16}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons+cat|Vultur gryphus|Vultur_gryphus}}\n{{Wikispecies|Vultur gryphus}}\n* [http://www.vulture-territory.com/andean.html Vulture Territory Facts and Characteristics: Andean condor]\n* ARKive \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20060720164351/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/birds/Vultur_gryphus/ images and movies of the Andean condor ''(Vultur gryphus)'']\n* [http://www.imagesandmusic.nl/dhtml/Condors.htm Video of Peruvian condors]\n* [http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=3822&m=0 BirdLife Species Factsheet]\n* [http://www.ecologia.info/condor-dos-andes.htm Andean condor]\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/andean-condor-vultur-gryphus Andean condor videos] on the Internet Bird Collection\n* [http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-colombia-condors30-2009aug30-pictures,0,377184.photogallery Scientists Work to Repopulate Colombia's Skies with Condors] \u2013 slideshow by ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]''\n* [http://www.bioandina.org.ar Proyecto Conservaci\u00f3n C\u00f3ndor Andino de Argentina], Organizado por la Fundaci\u00f3n Bioandina Argentina.\n*[http://www.ecology.info/condors.htm Ecology of condors]\n\n{{Vulture}}\n{{Symbols of Colombia}}\n{{Bolivia symbols}}\n{{Featured article}}\n{{Portalbar|Biology|Animals|Birds|Mythology|Latin America|Bolivia|Chile|Colombia}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q170598}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:condor, Andean}}\n[[Category:Cathartidae|Andean condor]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Andes|*]]\n[[Category:New World vultures]]\n[[Category:P\u00e1ramo fauna]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Argentina]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Colombia]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Chile]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Peru]]\n[[Category:Near threatened animals]]\n[[Category:Near threatened biota of South America]]\n[[Category:Extant Piacenzian first appearances|Andean condor]]\n[[Category:Pliocene birds of South America|Andean condor]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|Andean condor]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus|Andean condor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Vultur|the birds known as vultures|Vulture}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|A large South American bird in the New World vulture family }}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Andean condor\n| fossil_range = {{Fossil range|2.6|0}}<small>Late [[Pliocene]]\u2013[[Holocene]]</small>\n| image = Andean Condor in flight.jpg\n| image_caption = Soaring over [[Arequipa]] in southern [[Peru]].\n| status = NT\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|title= ''Vultur gryphus'' |author= [[BirdLife International]] |year= 2017 |page= e.T22697641A117360971 |access-date= 18 January 2020|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Vultur\n| parent_authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| species = gryphus\n| authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| synonyms =\n* ''Vultur fossilis'' <small>[[Francisco Moreno|Moreno]] & Mercerat, 1891</small>\n* ''Vultur patruus'' <small>[[Einar L\u00f6nnberg|L\u00f6nnberg]], 1902</small>\n* ''Vultur pratruus'' <small>Emslie, 1988 (''lapsus'')</small>\n| range_map = AndeanMap.png\n| range_map_caption = Yellow \u2013 approximate range/distribution\n}}\n\nThe '''Andean condor''' (''Vultur gryphus'') is a South American bird in the [[New World vulture]] family [[Cathartidae]] and is the only member of the [[genus]] '''''Vultur'''''. Found in the [[Andes]] mountains and adjacent Pacific coasts of western South America, the Andean condor is the largest flying bird in the world by combined measurement of weight and wingspan. It has a maximum wingspan of {{convert|3.3|m|ftin|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Richard P. Reading|Brian Miller|2000}} exceeded only by the wingspans of four [[seabirds]] and [[water birds]]\u2014the roughly {{convert|3.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}} maximum of the [[wandering albatross]], [[southern royal albatross]], [[great white pelican]] and [[Dalmatian pelican]].<ref name=\"Ferguson-Lees\">{{cite book\n | last = Ferguson-Lees\n | first = James\n | author2 = Christie, David A.\n | title = Raptors of the World\n | publisher = Houghton Mifflin\n | year = 2001\n | location = Boston\n | isbn = 0-618-12762-3}}</ref>\n\nIt is a large black vulture with a ruff of white feathers surrounding the base of the neck and, especially in the male, large white patches on the wings. The head and neck are nearly featherless, and are a dull red color, which may flush and therefore change color in response to the bird's emotional state. In the male, there is a wattle on the neck and a large, dark red [[Comb (anatomy)|comb]] or caruncle on the crown of the head. Unlike most [[bird of prey|birds of prey]], the male is larger than the female.\n\nThe condor is primarily a [[scavenger]], feeding on [[carrion]]. It prefers large carcasses, such as those of [[deer]] or [[cattle]]. It reaches sexual maturity at five or six years of age and [[Bird nest|nests]] at elevations of up to {{convert|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}}, generally on inaccessible rock ledges. One or two eggs are usually laid. It is one of the world's longest-living birds, with a lifespan of over 70 years in some cases.\n\nThe Andean condor is a national symbol of [[Argentina]], [[Bolivia]], [[Chile]], [[Colombia]], [[Ecuador]], and [[Peru]] and plays an important role in the [[folklore]] and [[mythology]] of the Andean regions. The Andean condor is considered [[Near Threatened|near threatened]] by the [[IUCN]].<ref name=IUCN/> It is threatened by habitat loss and by [[secondary poisoning]] from carcasses killed by hunters. [[Captive breeding]] programs have been instituted in several countries.\n\n==Taxonomy and systematics==\nThe Andean condor was described by [[Sweden|Swedish]] scientist [[Carl Linnaeus]] in 1758 in the [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|tenth edition]] of his ''[[Systema Naturae]]'' and retains its original [[binomial nomenclature|binomial]] name of ''Vultur gryphus''.<ref>{{cite book | last=Linnaeus | first=C | authorlink=Carl Linnaeus | title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. Tomus I. Editio decima, reformata. | volume=v.1 | quote = V. maximus, car\u00fancula verticali longitudine capitis. | publisher=Laurentii Salvii | place=Holmiae (Stockholm) | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/726991 | year=1758| page=86 | language=Latin }}</ref> The Andean condor is sometimes called the Argentinean condor, Bolivian condor, Chilean condor, Colombian condor, Ecuadorian condor, or Peruvian condor after one of the nations to which it is native. The generic term ''Vultur'' is directly taken from the [[Latin]] ''vultur'' or ''voltur'', which means \"vulture\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Simpson | first = D.P. | title = Cassell's Latin Dictionary | publisher = Cassell Ltd. | year = 1979 | edition = 5th | location = London | page = 883 | isbn = 0-304-52257-0}}</ref> Its specific epithet is derived from a variant of the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] word \u03b3\u03c1\u03c5\u03c0\u03cc\u03c2 (''grup\u00f3s'', \"hook-nosed\").<ref>{{cite book|last=Liddell|first=Henry George|author2=Robert Scott|year=1980|title=Greek-English Lexicon, Abridged Edition|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=0-19-910207-4|url=https://archive.org/details/lexicon00lidd}}</ref> The word condor itself is derived from the [[Quechua language|Quechua]] ''kuntur''.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia| title=Raven|encyclopedia=Oxford English Dictionary|editor1=J. Simpson |editor2=E. Weiner | year=1989 |edition= 2nd| location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn= 0-19-861186-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quechua.org.uk/Eng/Main/AnalysisMainFrame.htm |title=A Quechua metaphor for a plane: Kuntur-man = \"looking like a Condor\" |publisher=Quechua.org.uk |accessdate=2010-03-20}}</ref>\n\nThe exact [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] placement of the Andean condor and the remaining six species of [[New World vulture]]s remains unclear.<ref name=\"SACC\"/> Although both are similar in appearance and have similar [[ecological niche|ecological roles]], the New World and [[Old World vultures]] evolved from different ancestors in different parts of the world and are not closely related. Just how different the two families are is currently under debate, with some earlier authorities suggesting that the New World vultures are more closely related to [[storks]].<ref name=\"SibleyMonroe\">[[Charles Sibley|Sibley, Charles G.]] and Monroe, Burt L. (1990). ''[https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN0300049692 Distribution and Taxonomy of the Birds of the World]''. Yale University Press. {{ISBN|0-300-04969-2}}. Retrieved 2007-04-11.</ref> More recent authorities maintain their overall position in the order [[Falconiformes]] along with the Old World vultures<ref name=Sibley1991/> or place them in their own order, Cathartiformes.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1098/rsbl.2006.0523|title=Diversification of Neoaves: Integration of molecular sequence data and fossils|year=2006|last1=Ericson|first1=P. G.P|last2=Anderson|first2=C. L|last3=Britton|first3=T.|last4=Elzanowski|first4=A.|last5=Johansson|first5=U. S|last6=Kallersjo|first6=M.|last7=Ohlson|first7=J. I|last8=Parsons|first8=T. J|last9=Zuccon|first9=D.|displayauthors=8|journal=Biology Letters|volume=2|issue=4|pages=543\u20137|pmid=17148284|pmc=1834003}}</ref> The [[South American Classification Committee]] has removed the New World vultures from [[Ciconiiformes]] and instead described them as ''[[incertae sedis]]'', but notes that a move to Falconiformes or Cathartiformes is possible.<ref name=\"SACC\">Remsen, J. V., Jr.; Cadena, C. D.; Jaramillo, A.; Nores, M.; Pacheco, J. F.; Robbins, M. B.; Schulenberg, T. S.; Stiles, F. G.; Stotz, D. F. and Zimmer, K. J. (2007). [http://www.museum.lsu.edu/~Remsen/SACCBaseline.html ''A classification of the bird species of South America.''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302073659/http://www.museum.lsu.edu/~Remsen/SACCBaseline.html |date=2009-03-02 }} South American Classification Committee. Retrieved on 2007-10-15</ref>\n\nThe Andean condor is the only accepted living species of its genus, ''Vultur''.<ref>{{cite web\n | title = ''Vultur gryphus''\n | publisher = Integrated Taxonomic Information System\n | url = http://itis.gov/servlet/SingleRpt/SingleRpt?search_topic=TSN&search_value=175279\n | accessdate = 2008-01-13}}</ref> Unlike the [[California condor]] (''Gymnogyps californianus''), which is known from extensive [[fossil]] remains and some additional ones of [[:wiktionary:congener|congeners]], the fossil record of the Andean condor recovered to date is scant. Presumed [[Plio-Pleistocene]] species of South American condors were later recognized to be not different from the present species, although one known only from a few rather small bones found in a Pliocene deposit of [[Tarija Department]], Bolivia, may have been a smaller [[chronospecies|palaeosubspecies]], ''V. gryphus patruus''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Fisher, Harvey L. |year=1944|title= The skulls of the Cathartid vultures|journal=[[Condor (journal)|Condor]]|volume=46|issue=6|pages= 272\u2013296|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v046n06/p0272-p0296.pdf| doi = 10.2307/1364013| jstor = 1364013}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Vultur gryphus head (Linnaeus, 1758).jpg|right|thumb|There is a dark red caruncle (or comb) on the top of the head of the adult male.]]\n\n[[File:Vultur gryphus -Franklin Park Zoo, Massachusetts, USA -female-8a (1).jpg|right|thumb|Adult female at [[Franklin Park Zoo]], USA]]\n[[File:Vultur gryphus talon.jpg|thumb|right|Detail of talon showing elongated middle toe]]\nAlthough the California condor is, from beak to tail, about 7 to 8&nbsp;cm longer, the Andean condor has a wider wingspan, which ranges from {{convert|270|-|320|cm|ftin|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Ferguson-Lees\"/> It is also typically heavier, reaching a weight of {{convert|11|to|15|kg|lb|abbr=on}} for males and {{convert|8|to|11|kg|lb|abbr=on}} for females.<ref name=\"Handbookof\">{{cite book |title=Handbook of the Birds of the World |last1=del Hoyo |first1=J | last2=Elliot | first2 = A | last3=Sargatal | first3 = J | year=1996 |publisher=[[Lynx Edicions]] |location=[[Barcelona]] |isbn=84-87334-20-2|volume=3|title-link=Handbook of the Birds of the World }}</ref> Overall length can range from {{convert|100|to|130|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Handbookof\" /> Among standard measurements, the [[Wing chord (biology)|wing chord]] is {{convert|75.7|-|85.2|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the [[tail]] is {{convert|33|-|38|cm|in|abbr=on}} and the [[Tarsus (skeleton)|tarsus]] is {{convert|11.5|-|12.5|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Ferguson-Lees\"/> Measurements are usually taken from specimens reared in captivity.<ref name=\"Ferguson-Lees\"/> The mean weight is {{convert|11.3|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, with the males averaging about a kilogram more at {{convert|12.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, the females a kilogram less at {{convert|10.1|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Condors possess the heaviest average weight for any living flying bird or animal, ahead of [[trumpeter swan]]s (''Cygnus buccinator'') and [[Dalmatian pelican]]s (''Pelecanus crispus'').<ref name = \"CRC\">''CRC Handbook of Avian Body Masses, 2nd Edition'' by John B. Dunning Jr. (Editor). CRC Press (2008), {{ISBN|978-1-4200-6444-5}}.</ref><ref>Wallace, M. P., & Temple, S. A. (1987). ''Competitive interactions within and between species in a guild of avian scavengers''. The Auk, 290-295.</ref> However, other sources claim a mean species body mass of {{convert|10.3|kg|lb|abbr=on}} for the Andean condor.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Atanasov | first1 = A. T. | year = 2007 | title = The near to linear allometric relationship between total metabolic energy per life span and body mass of nonpasserine birds | url = | journal = Bulgarian Journal of Veterinary Medicine | volume = 10 | issue = 4| pages = 235\u2013245 }}</ref> The Andean condor is the largest living land bird capable of flight if measured in terms of average weight and wingspan, although male [[bustard]]s of the largest species (far more sexually dimorphic in size) can weigh more.<ref name=\"Handbookof\" /><ref>[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=3822 Andean Condor ''Vultur gryphus'']. Birdlife International.</ref><ref name=\"Wood\">{{cite book| author = Wood, Gerald| title = The Guinness Book of Animal Facts and Feats| year = 1983| isbn = 978-0-85112-235-9| url = https://archive.org/details/guinnessbookofan00wood| publisher = Enfield, Middlesex : Guinness Superlatives}}</ref> The mean wingspan is around {{convert|283|cm|ftin|0|abbr=on}} and the wings have the largest surface area of any extant bird.<ref name=\"Wood\"/> Among living bird species, only the [[great albatross]]es and the two largest species of [[pelican]] exceed the Andean condor in average and maximal wingspan.<ref name=\"Wood\"/><ref name=\"Harrison\">Harrison, Peter, ''Seabirds: An Identification Guide''. Houghton Mifflin Harcourt (1991), {{ISBN|978-0-395-60291-1}}</ref>\n[[File:Vultur gryphus -Dou\u00e9-la-Fontaine Zoo, France-8a.jpg|left|thumb|Female at Dou\u00e9-la-Fontaine Zoo, France.]]\n[[File:AndeanCondorMale.jpg|right|thumb|Male at the [[Cincinnati Zoo]].]]\nThe adult [[plumage]] is a uniform black, except for a frill of white feathers at the base of the neck and, especially in the male, large bands of white on the wings, which only appear after the bird's first [[moult]].<ref name=\"Hilty\">{{cite book\n | last =Hilty\n | first =Stephen L.\n | title =A Guide to the Birds of Colombia\n | publisher =Princeton University Press\n | year =1977\n | page =88\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=1k5fV_hQqE8C&pg=PA88\n | isbn =0-691-08372-X }}</ref> The head and neck are red to blackish-red and have few feathers. The head and neck are meticulously kept clean by the bird,<ref name=CleMet3>{{cite web\n |title=Behavior of the Andean Condor \n |publisher=Cleveland Metroparks Zoo \n |url=http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/behavior.htm \n |accessdate=2007-01-10 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219194934/http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/behavior.htm \n |archivedate=19 December 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> and their baldness is an adaptation for hygiene, allowing the skin to be exposed to the [[Sterilization (microbiology)|sterilizing]] effects of [[dehydration]] and [[ultraviolet light]] at high altitudes.<ref name=\"Patagonia\">{{cite book | last = Lutz | first = Dick|author2=Lutz, Richard L.| title = Patagonia: At the Bottom of the World | publisher = DIMI Press | year = 2002| pages = [https://archive.org/details/patagonia00rich/page/71 71]\u201374|url=https://archive.org/details/patagonia00rich | url-access = registration | isbn = 0-931625-38-6}}</ref> The crown of the head is flattened. In the male, the head is crowned with a dark red caruncle or comb, while the skin of his neck lies in folds, forming a wattle.<ref name=\"Hilty\"/> When condors are agitated, their head and neck flush, a clear signal to animals nearby. Juveniles have a grayish-brown general coloration, blackish head and neck skin, and a brown ruff.\n<ref name=\"Blake\">{{cite book\n | author = Blake, Emmet Reid\n | title =Birds of Mexico: A Guide for Field Identification\n | publisher =University of Chicago Press\n | year =1953\n | pages =[https://archive.org/details/birdsofmexicogui00blak/page/262 262]\u2013263\n | url =https://archive.org/details/birdsofmexicogui00blak\n | url-access = registration\n | isbn= 0-226-05641-4}}</ref>\n\nThe middle toe is greatly elongated, and the hind one is only slightly developed, while the talons of all the toes are comparatively straight and blunt. The feet are thus more adapted to walking, and are of little use as weapons or organs of [[prehension]] as in birds of prey and [[Old World vulture]]s.<ref name=\"Feduccia\"/> The beak is hooked, and adapted to tear rotting meat.<ref name=\"SanDiego\"/> The [[iris (anatomy)|irises]] of the male are brown, while those of the female are deep red.<ref name=\"Smithsonian\"/> They have no eyelashes.<ref name=\" Pterylosis \">{{Cite journal| last = Fisher| first = Harvey L.| title = The Pterylosis of the Andean Condor|url=http://sora.unm.edu/node/99237 | journal = [[Condor (journal)|Condor]]| volume = 44 | issue = 1| pages = 30\u201332| year = 1942| doi = 10.2307/1364195| jstor =1364195 }}</ref> Unlike the case with most other [[bird of prey|birds of prey]],<ref>{{cite book\n  |last = Andersson\n  |first = Malte B.\n  |title = Sexual selection\n  |publisher = Princeton University Press\n  |year = 1994\n  |page = 269\n  |accessdate = 19 July 2010\n  |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lNnHdvzBlTYC\n  |isbn = 978-0-691-00057-2}}</ref> the female is smaller.<ref>{{cite book\n  |last1 = Arnold\n  |first1 = Caroline\n  |last2 = Wallace\n  |first2 = Michael Phillip\n  |last3 = Wallace\n  |first3 = Michael\n  |title = On the brink of extinction: the California condor\n  |publisher = Houghton Mifflin Harcourt\n  |year = 1993\n  |page = 11\n  |accessdate = 19 July 2010\n  |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dQYHp0csAvcC\n  |isbn = 978-0-15-257990-6}}</ref>\n\nObservation of wing color patterns, and the size and shape of the male\u2019s crest, are the best ways of identifying individual Andean condors. Sighting-resighting methods assess the size and structure of populations.<ref>{{cite journal |author1= M\u00e9ndez, D. |author2= Marsden, S. | author3= Lloyd, H. | year=2019| title= Assessing population size and structure for Andean Condor Vultur gryphus in Bolivia using a photographic 'capture\u2010recapture' method| journal=Ibis| volume=161| pages=  867\u2013877| doi= 10.1111/ibi.12681| issue=4| doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n[[File:Condor des Andes m\u00e2le adulte.jpg|thumb|right| Andean condor, in Chilean national park [[Torres del Paine]]]]\nThe Andean condor is found in [[South America]] in the [[Andes]] including the [[Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta|Santa Marta Mountains]]. In the north, its range begins in [[Venezuela]] and Colombia, where it is extremely rare,<ref name=\"BirdLife\"/> then continues south along the Andes in Ecuador, Peru, and Chile, through Bolivia and western Argentina to the [[Tierra del Fuego]].<ref name=\"Blake\"/> In the early 19th century, the Andean condor bred from western Venezuela to Tierra del Fuego, along the entire chain of the Andes, but its range has been greatly reduced due to human activity.<ref name=\"Haemig \"/> Its habitat is mainly composed of open grasslands and alpine areas up to {{convert|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}} in elevation. It prefers relatively open, non-forested areas which allow it to spot carrion from the air, such as the [[p\u00e1ramo]] or rocky, mountainous areas in general.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Habitat of the Andean Condor \n |publisher=Cleveland Metroparks Zoo \n |url=http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/habitat.htm \n |accessdate=2007-01-10 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061220141630/http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/habitat.htm \n |archivedate=20 December 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> It occasionally ranges to lowlands in eastern Bolivia, northern Peru, and southwestern Brazil,<ref name=\"SibleyMonroe\"/> descends to lowland desert areas in Chile and Peru, and is found over [[Nothofagus|southern-beech]] forests in [[Patagonia]].<ref name=\"BirdLife\"/> In southern Patagonia, meadows are important for Andean condors as this habitat is likely to have herbivores present. In this region, Andean condor distributions are therefore influenced by the locations of meadows as well as cliffs for nesting and roosting.<ref>{{cite journal |author1= P\u00e9rez\u2010Garc\u00eda, J.M. |author2= S\u00e1nchez\u2010Zapata, J.A. | author3= Lambertucci, S.A. | author4= Hiraldo, F. | author5= Don\u00e1zar, J.A | year=2018| title= Low\u2010frequency, threatened habitats drive the large\u2010scale distribution of Andean Condors in southern Patagonia| journal=Ibis| volume=160| pages= 647\u2013658 | doi=10.1111/ibi.12563| issue=3}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology and behavior==\n[[File:Andean Condor in full flight.JPG|thumb|left|Andean condors often spend much of their time soaring on montane updraughts.]]\nThe condor soars with its wings held horizontally and its [[primary feather]]s bent upwards at the tips.<ref name=\"Hilty\"/> The lack of a large [[sternum]] to anchor its correspondingly large flight muscles physiologically identifies it as primarily being a soarer. It flaps its wings on rising from the ground, but after attaining a moderate elevation it flaps its wings very rarely, relying on thermals to stay aloft.<ref name=\"Wehner\"/> [[Charles Darwin]] commented on having watched them for half an hour without once observing a flap of their wings.<ref>{{cite book\n | last =Darwin\n | first= Charles\n | title =The Voyage of the Beagle\n | publisher =P.F. Collier\n | year =1909\n | page=[https://archive.org/details/voyagebeagle00darwgoog/page/n209 201]\n | url= https://archive.org/details/voyagebeagle00darwgoog}}</ref> It prefers to roost on high places from which it can launch without major wing-flapping effort. Andean condors are often seen soaring near rock cliffs, using the heat [[thermals]] to aid them in rising in the air.<ref name=\"Benson\">{{cite book\n |author1=Benson, Sara  |author2=Paul Hellander\n | title =Peru\n | publisher =Lonely Planet Publications\n | year =2007\n | page=[https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetperu00sara_0/page/53 53]\n | url= https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetperu00sara_0\n |url-access=registration  | isbn = 978-1-74059-749-4}}</ref>\n\nLike other [[New World vulture]]s, the Andean condor has the unusual habit of [[urohidrosis]]: it often empties its [[cloaca]] onto its legs and feet. A cooling effect through [[evaporative cooling|evaporation]] has been proposed as a reason for this behavior, but it does not make any sense in the cold Andean habitat of the bird.<ref name=Sibley1991>{{cite book\n |author1=Sibley, Charles G.  |author2=Jon E. Ahlquist\n | title =Phylogeny and Classification of Birds: A Study in Molecular Evolution\n | publisher =Yale University Press\n | year =1991\n | url= https://books.google.com/books?visbn=0300040857\n | isbn = 0-300-04085-7}}</ref> Because of this habit, their legs are often streaked with a white buildup of [[uric acid]].<ref name=\"Feduccia\">{{cite book\n | last =Feduccia\n | first =J. Alan\n | title =The Origin and Evolution of Birds\n | publisher =Yale University Press\n | year =1999\n | page =300\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=8QRKV7eSqmIC&pg=PA300\n | isbn =0-226-05641-4 }}</ref>\n\nThere is a well-developed social structure within large groups of condors, with competition to determine a 'pecking order' by body language, competitive play behavior, and [[Bird vocalization|vocalizations]].<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Donazard\n | first = Jos\u00e9 A\n | author2 = Feijoo, Juan E.\n | title = Social structure of Andean Condor roosts: Influence of sex, age, and season\n | journal =[[Condor (journal)|Condor]]\n | volume = 104\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 832\u2013837\n | publisher =Cooper Ornithological Society\n | url = http://cat.inist.fr/?aModele=afficheN&cpsidt=14022914\n | accessdate =2008-01-10\n | doi = 10.1650/0010-5422(2002)104[0832:SSOACR]2.0.CO;2\n | year = 2002\n | issn = 0010-5422 | hdl = 10261/65935\n | hdl-access = free\n }}</ref> Generally, mature males tend to be at the top of the pecking order, with post-dispersal immature males tending to be near the bottom.<ref name=\"Ferguson-Lees\"/>\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Vultur gryphus MWNH 0718.JPG|left|thumb|Egg, Collection [[Museum Wiesbaden]]]]\n[[File:Condor02 ST 98.jpg|thumb|right|A juvenile condor in [[Colca Canyon]], [[Peru]].]]\n[[File:Condor des andes immature.jpg|thumb|right|A young female Andean condor, in [[Nahuel Huapi National Park]], [[Argentina]].]]\n\nSexual maturity and breeding behavior do not appear in the Andean condor until the bird is five or six years of age.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Andean Condor (''Vultur Gryphus'') \n |publisher=[[The Peregrine Fund]] \n |url=http://www.peregrinefund.org/explore_raptors/vultures/andcondr.html \n |accessdate=2007-01-10 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205055624/http://www.peregrinefund.org/Explore_Raptors/vultures/andcondr.html \n |archivedate=5 February 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> It may live to 50 years or more, and it mates for life.<ref name=\"Tait\"/> During courtship displays, the skin of the male's neck flushes, changing from dull red to bright yellow, and inflates.<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Whitson\n | first = Martha A\n | author2 = Whitson, Paul D.\n | title = Breeding Behavior of the Andean Condor (''Vultur Gryphus'')\n | journal =[[Condor (journal)|Condor]]\n | volume = 71\n | pages = 73\u201375\n | publisher =Cooper Ornithological Society\n | year =1968\n | url =http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v071n01/p0073-p0075.pdf\n | accessdate = 2007-01-10\n | doi = 10.2307/1366056 | jstor = 1366056\n | issue = 1}}</ref> He approaches the female with neck outstretched, revealing the inflated neck and the chest patch, while hissing,<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Gailey\n | first = Janet\n | author2 = Bolwig, Neils\n | title =Observations on the Breeding Behavior of the Andean Condor (''Vultur Gryphus'')\n | journal =[[Condor (journal)|Condor]]\n | publisher =Cooper Ornithological Society\n | volume = 75\n | pages = 60\u201368\n | year =1973\n | url =http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v075n01/p0060-p0068.pdf\n | accessdate = 2007-01-10\n | doi =10.2307/1366535 | jstor = 1366535\n | issue = 1}}</ref> then extends his wings and stands erect while clicking his tongue.<ref name=\"Smithsonian\"/> Other courtship rituals include hissing and clucking while hopping with wings partially spread, and dancing.<ref name=\"Patagonia\"/> The Andean condor prefers to roost and breed at elevations of {{convert|3000|to|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Fjelds\u00e5\">{{cite book\n | last = Fjelds\u00e5\n | first =Jon\n | author2= Krabbe, Niels\n | title =Birds of the High Andes\n | publisher =Apollo Books\n | year =1990\n | page =90\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=NmXSeVrmlgIC\n | isbn =87-88757-16-1 }}</ref> Its nest, which consists of a few sticks placed around the eggs, is created on inaccessible ledges of rock. However, in coastal areas of Peru, where there are few cliffs, some nests are simply partially shaded crannies scraped out against boulders on slopes.<ref name=\"Haemig \"/> It deposits one or two bluish-white [[egg (biology)|eggs]], weighing about {{convert|280|g|oz|abbr=on}} and ranging from {{convert|75|to|100|mm|in|abbr=on}} in length, during the months of February and March every second year. The egg hatches after 54 to 58&nbsp;days of [[Avian incubation|incubation]] by both parents.<ref name=\"Smithsonian\">{{cite web\n |author=Friends of the Zoo \n |title=Andean Condor \n |publisher=Smithsonian National Zoological Park \n |url=http://nationalzoo.si.edu/Animals/Birds/Facts/FactSheets/fact-andeancondor.cfm \n |accessdate=2008-01-08 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009075845/http://nationalzoo.si.edu/Animals/Birds/Facts/FactSheets/fact-andeancondor.cfm \n |archivedate=2007-10-09 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> If the chick or egg is lost or removed, another egg is laid to take its place. Researchers and breeders take advantage of this behavior to double the reproductive rate by taking the first egg away for hand-rearing, causing the parents to lay a second egg, which they are generally allowed to raise.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| author=National Research Council\n | title = Scientific Bases for the Preservation of the Hawaiian Crow\n | publisher =National Academies Press\n | year = 1992\n | page =74\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=8cDX2mb07mcC&pg=PA74\n | isbn =0-309-04775-7 }}</ref>\n\nThe young are covered with a grayish down until they are almost as large as their parents. They are able to fly after six months,<ref name=\"Hilty\"/> but continue to roost and hunt with their parents until age two, when they are displaced by a new clutch.<ref>Cisneros-Heredia, Diego F. (2006). [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.177.5617&rep=rep1&type=pdf \"Notes on breeding, behaviour and distribution of some birds in Ecuador\"]. ''Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club'' '''126''' (2): 153\u2013164 contains a record of a juvenile accompanying an adult male in July, too early to have been of that year's cohort.</ref> Healthy adults have no natural predators, but large [[birds of prey]] and [[mammal]]ian predators, like [[South American fox|fox]]es and [[cougar]]s, may take eggs and  hatchlings, with large predators a possible but not confirmed threat to fledglings or infirm adults. Predation is relatively uncommon, since the vigilant parents often aggressively displace birds of prey who come near and the rocky, precipitous location of most nests are difficult for mammals to access.\n\n===Feeding===\nThe Andean condor is a [[scavenger]], feeding mainly on [[carrion]].<ref name=\"Wehner\">{{cite book\n | last =Wehner\n | first =Ross\n | author2= del Gaudio, Renee |author3=Jankowski, Kazia\n | title =Moon Peru\n | publisher =Avalon Travel\n | year =2007\n | page =180\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=2tVNa8P0inYC&pg=PA180\n | isbn =978-1-56691-983-8 }}</ref> Wild condors inhabit large territories, often traveling more than {{convert|200|km|mi|abbr=on}} a day in search of carrion.<ref name=\"Patagonia\"/> In inland areas, they prefer large carcasses. Naturally, they feed on the largest carcasses available, which can include [[llama]]s (''Lama glama''), [[alpaca]]s (''Vicugna pacos''), [[rhea (bird)|rhea]]s (''Rhea ssp.''), [[guanaco]]s (''Lama guanicoe''), [[deer]] and [[armadillo]]s. Wild individuals could acquire extra carotenoids from vegetal matter contained in carcass viscera and fresh vegetation.<ref name=\"Blanco2013\">{{cite journal  | last1=Blanco |first1=G. |last2=Hornero-M\u00e9ndez |first2=D. |last3=Lambertucci |first3=S.A. |last4=Don\u00e1zar |first4=J.A. |last5=Bautista |first5=L.M. |last6= Wiemeyer |first6=G. |last7=Sanchez-Zapata |first7=J.A. |last8=Garrido-Fern\u00e1ndez |first8=J. |last9=Hiraldo |first9=F.  |year=2013 |title=Need and seek for dietary micronutrients: endogenous regulation, external signaling and food sources of carotenoids in New World vultures |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=8 |issue=6 |page=e65562 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0065562 |pmid=23785435 |url=https://digital.csic.es/handle/10261/78234?locale=en |pmc=3681859|bibcode=2013PLoSO...865562B }}</ref> However, most inland condors now live largely off of domestic animals, which are now more widespread in South America, such as [[cattle]] (''Bos primigenius taurus''), [[horse]]s (''Equus ferus caballus''), [[donkey]]s (''Equus africanus asinus''), [[mule]]s, [[sheep]] (''Ovis aries''), [[pig]]s (''Sus scrofa domesticus''), [[goat]]s (''Capra aegagrus hircus'') and [[dog]]s (''Canis lupus familiaris''). They also feed on the carcasses of introduced game species such as [[wild boar]]s (''Sus scrofa''), [[rabbit]]s (''Oryctolagus cuniculus''), [[fox]]es (''Vulpes vulpes'') and [[red deer]] (''Cervus elaphus''). For condors who live around the coast, the diet consists mainly of beached carcasses of marine mammals, largely [[cetacean]]s.<ref name=\"Smithsonian\"/><ref name=\"ADW\"/> They will also raid the nests of smaller birds to feed on the eggs.<ref>{{cite web\n | title =Andean Condor (''Vultur Gryphus'')\n | publisher = [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]\n | url = http://animals.nationalgeographic.com/animals/birds/andean-condor.html\n | accessdate = 2007-01-10}}</ref> Andean condors have been observed to do some hunting of small, live animals, such as [[rodent]]s, [[bird]]s and [[rabbit]]s, which (given their lack of powerful, grasping feet or developed hunting technique) they usually kill by jabbing repeatedly with their bill.<ref name= ADW>[http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Vultur_gryphus.html ADW: Vultur gryphus: INFORMATION]. Animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu. Retrieved on 2012-12-19.</ref>\n[[File:Andean Condor skeleton.jpg|thumb|Andean condor skeleton ([[Museum of Osteology]])]]\nCoastal areas provide a constant food supply, and in particularly plentiful areas, some Andean condors limit their foraging area to several kilometers of beach-front land.<ref name=\"Haemig \">{{cite web\n |last=Haemig \n |first=PD \n |title=Ecology of Condors \n |publisher=Ecology Online Sweden \n |year=2007 \n |url=http://www.ecology.info/condors.htm \n |accessdate=March 30, 2009 \n}}</ref> They locate carrion by spotting it or by following other scavengers, such as [[corvid]]s or other vultures.<ref name=\"snyder\">{{cite book\n |author1=Snyder, Noel F. R.  |author2=Helen Snyder\n | title =Raptors of North America: Natural History and Conservation\n | publisher =Voyageur Press\n | page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780760325827/page/45 45]\n | year =2006\n | url= https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780760325827\n |url-access=registration  | isbn = 0-7603-2582-0}}</ref> It may follow New World vultures of the genus ''[[Cathartes]]''\u2014the [[turkey vulture]] (''C. aura''), the [[lesser yellow-headed vulture]] (''C. burrovianus''), and the [[greater yellow-headed vulture]] (''C. melambrotus'')\u2014to carcasses. The ''Cathartes'' vultures forage by smell, detecting the scent of [[Ethanethiol|ethyl mercaptan]], a gas produced by the beginnings of decay in dead animals. These smaller vultures cannot rip through the tougher hides of these larger animals with the efficiency of the larger condor, and their interactions are often an example of [[mutual dependence]] between species.<ref name=\"Dietland\">{{cite book\n | last =Muller-Schwarze\n | first =Dietland\n | title =Chemical Ecology of Vertebrates\n | publisher =Cambridge University Press\n | page=350\n | year =2006\n | url= https://books.google.com/?id=HaaFlUw4goIC&pg=PA1\n | isbn = 0-521-36377-2}}</ref> [[Black vulture]]s (''Coragyps atratus''), [[king vulture]]s (''Sarcoramphus papa'') and even mammalian scavengers may sometimes track ''Cathartes'' vultures for carcasses but the condor is invariably dominant among the scavengers in its range.<ref>[http://www.ecology.info/condors.htm Ecology of Condors: the California Condor and Andean Condor]. Ecology.info. Retrieved on 2012-12-19.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecology.info/condors.htm |title=Ecology of Condors |accessdate=2006-10-05 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001235133/http://www.ecology.info/condors.htm |archivedate=2006-10-01 }}. ecology.info.</ref> Andean condors are intermittent eaters in the wild, often going for a few days without eating, then gorging themselves on several pounds at once, sometimes to the point of being unable to lift off the ground. Because its feet and talons are not adapted to grasping, it must feed while on the ground.<ref name=\"Patagonia\"/> Like other carrion-feeders, it plays an important role in its [[ecosystem]] by disposing of carrion which would otherwise be a breeding ground for disease.<ref name=\"cotton\">{{cite journal\n |last=Gomez \n |title=The role of greater yellow-headed vultures Cathartes melambrotus as scavengers in neotropical forest \n |journal=Ibis \n |volume=136 \n |issue=2 \n |pages=193\u2013196 \n |year=1994 \n |url=http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=3646491&q=Cathartes+melambrotus&uid=791396595&setcookie=yes \n |accessdate=2008-01-06 \n |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1994.tb01084.x \n |first1=Luis G. \n |last2=Houston \n |first2=David C. \n |last3=Cotton \n |first3=Peter \n |last4=Tye \n |first4=Alan \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080129233040/http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=3646491&q=Cathartes+melambrotus&uid=791396595&setcookie=yes \n |archivedate=29 January 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\n===Longevity===\nBeing a slowly-maturing bird with no known natural predators in adulthood, an Andean condor is a long-lived bird. Longevity and mortality rates are not known to have been extensively studied in the wild. Some estimations of lifespans of wild birds has exceeded 50 years. In 1983, the [[Guinness Book of World Records]] considered the longest-lived bird of any species with a confirmed lifespan was an Andean condor that died after surviving 72 years in captivity, having been captured from the wild as a juvenile of undetermined age.<ref name=\"Wood\"/> Several species of [[parrot]] have been reported to live for perhaps over 100 years in captivity, but these (at least in 1983) were not considered authenticated.<ref name=\"Wood\"/> Another early captive-held specimen of condor reportedly lived for 71 years.<ref name=\"Wood\"/> However, these lifespans have been exceeded by a male, nicknamed \"Thaao\", that was kept at [[Beardsley Zoo]] in [[Connecticut]]. Thaao was born in captivity in 1930 and died on January 26, 2010, making him 79 years of age.<ref>[http://beardsleyzoo.org/node/150 Zoo Family Mourns Death of Oldest Living Andean Condor in Captivity | Connecticut's Beardsley Zoo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520105325/http://www.beardsleyzoo.org/node/150 |date=2012-05-20 }}. Beardsleyzoo.org (2010-01-26). Retrieved on 2012-12-19.</ref> This would be the greatest verified age ever known for a bird.<ref name=\"Wood\"/>\n\n==Relationship with humans==\n\n===Conservation status===\n[[File:Vultur gryphus -Taronga Zoo, Australia-8a.jpg|thumb|left|Adult male at [[Taronga Zoo]], Australia]]\nThe Andean condor is considered [[Near Threatened|near threatened]] by the [[IUCN]] and the Peruvian [[Conservation organizations|Conservation Organization]].<ref name=IUCN/> It was first placed on the United States [[Endangered Species]] list in 1970,<ref>{{cite web|title=Species Profile: Andean Condor |publisher=United States Department of Fish and Wildlife |url=http://ecos.fws.gov/speciesProfile/SpeciesReport.do?spcode=B03Y |accessdate=2007-10-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303165337/http://ecos.fws.gov/speciesProfile/SpeciesReport.do?spcode=B03Y |archivedate=March 3, 2009 }}</ref> a status which is assigned to an animal that is in danger of extinction throughout all or a significant portion of its range.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Endangered Species Program \n |publisher=United States Department of Fish and Wildlife \n |url=http://www.fws.gov/Endangered/wildlife.html \n |accessdate=2007-10-16 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070921072436/http://www.fws.gov/Endangered/wildlife.html \n |archivedate=2007-09-21 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> Threats to its population include loss of habitat needed for foraging, secondary poisoning from animals killed by hunters and persecution.<ref name=\"Reading\">{{cite book\n | last =Reading\n | first =Richard P.\n | author2 =Miller, Brian\n | title =Endangered Animals: A Reference Guide to Conflicting Issues\n | publisher =Greenwood Press\n | year =2000\n | page =16\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=f_AWCtX29-kC&pg=PA16\n | isbn = 0-313-30816-0}}</ref> It is threatened mainly in the northern area of its range, and is extremely rare in Venezuela and Colombia, where it has undergone considerable declines in recent years.<ref>{{cite book\n | last =Beletsky\n | first =Les\n | title =Birds of the World\n | publisher =JHU Press\n | year =2006\n | page =70\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=50_95BRVIjkC\n | isbn =0-8018-8429-2 }}</ref> Because it is adapted to very low mortality and has correspondingly low reproductive rates, it is extremely vulnerable to human persecution,<ref name=\"BirdLife\">{{cite web|title=Species factsheet: Vultur Gryphus |year=2004 |publisher=BirdLife International |url=http://www.redlist.org/search/details.php?species=40258 |accessdate=2008-01-04 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060305172904/http://www.redlist.org/search/details.php?species=40258 |archivedate=2006-03-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> most of which stems from the fact that it is perceived as a threat by farmers due to alleged attacks on livestock.<ref name=\"Tait\">{{cite book\n | last =Tait\n | first =Malcolm\n | title =Going, Going, Gone: Animals and Plants on the Brink of Extinction\n | publisher =Sterling Publishing\n | year =2006\n | page =[https://archive.org/details/goinggoinggone00thin/page/22 22]\n | url =https://archive.org/details/goinggoinggone00thin\n | url-access =registration\n | isbn = 1-84525-027-3}}</ref> Education programs have been implemented by conservationists to dispel this misconception.<ref name=\"Roach\"/> Reintroduction programs using captive-bred Andean condors, which release birds hatched in North American zoos into the wild to bolster populations,<ref name=\"Roach\">{{cite web\n | last =Roach\n | first =John\n | title =Peru's Andean Condors Are Rising Tourist Attraction\n | work = National Geographic News\n | publisher = [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]\n | date = 2004-07-22\n | url = http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2004/07/0722_040722_andeancondor.html\n | accessdate = 2007-01-10}}</ref> have been introduced in Argentina, Venezuela, and Colombia. The first captive-bred Andean condors were released into the wild in 1989.<ref>{{cite web\n |author=Conservation and Research for Endangered Species \n |title=Andean Condor Reintroduction Program \n |publisher=Zoological Society of San Diego \n |url=http://cres.sandiegozoo.org/projects/rb_condor_andean.html \n |accessdate=2007-01-10 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010112901/http://cres.sandiegozoo.org/projects/rb_condor_andean.html \n |archivedate=2006-10-10 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> When raising condors, human contact is minimal; chicks are fed with glove puppets which resemble adult Andean condors in order to prevent the chicks from [[imprinting (psychology)|imprinting]] on humans, which would endanger them upon release as they would not be wary of humans.<ref name=\"Pullin\"/> The condors are kept in aviaries for three months prior to release, where they acclimatize to an environment similar to that which they will be released in.<ref name=\"Pullin\">{{cite book\n | last = Pullin\n | first = Andrew S.\n | title = Conservation Biology\n | publisher = Cambridge University Press\n | year = 2002\n | page = 234\n | url = https://books.google.com/?id=ED-8V8cE67UC&pg=PA234\n | isbn = 0-521-64482-8}}</ref> Released condors are tracked by satellite in order to observe their movements and to monitor whether they are still alive.<ref name=\"SanDiego\"/>\n\nIn response to the capture of all the wild individuals of the California condor, in 1988 the [[US Fish and Wildlife Service]] began a reintroduction experiment involving the release of captive Andean condors into the wild in [[California]]. Only females were released to prevent it becoming an [[invasive species]]. The experiment was a success, and all the Andean condors were recaptured and re-released in South America before the reintroduction of the California condors took place.<ref name=\"USFW\">{{cite web | title = California condor, (Gymnogyps californianus) | publisher= U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service| url = http://www.fws.gov/species/species_accounts/bio_cond.html| accessdate = 2007-08-14}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, local authorities of the [[Ancasmarca]] region rescued two Andean condors that were caged and displayed in a local market as an attraction for tourists.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.andina.com.pe/agencia/noticia-rescatan-dos-condores-andinos-eran-exhibidos-a-turistas-calca-cusco-509987.aspx Rescatan dos c\u00f3ndores andinos que eran exhibidos a turistas en Calca Cusco], ''Andina.com.pe'', 12 June 2014</ref>\n\n===Role in culture===\n[[File:Chancay Sleeved Tunic with Flying Condors.png|thumb|[[Chancay culture|Chancay]] textile with flying condors, 1200-1400 AD]]\nThe Andean condor is a national symbol of Argentina, Bolivia, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru and [[Andean Region, Venezuela|Venezuelan Andes]] states. It is the [[List of national birds|national bird]] of Bolivia, Chile, Colombia, and Ecuador.<ref>{{cite web\n | last =MacDonald\n | first =Tina\n | author2 = MacDonald, Duncan\n | title =National Birds\n | url =http://www.camacdonald.com/birding/CountryIndex.htm\n | accessdate = 2007-10-06 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071006063912/http://www.camacdonald.com/birding/CountryIndex.htm#A| archivedate= 6 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> It plays an important role in the [[folklore]] and [[mythology]] of the [[South American]] Andean regions,<ref name=\"Tait\"/> and has been represented in Andean art from c. 2500 BCE onward,<ref name=\"Werness\">{{cite book\n | last =Werness\n | first =Hope B.\n | title =The Continuum Encyclopedia of Animal Symbolism in Art\n | publisher =Continuum International Publishing Group\n | year =2004\n | page =103\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=fr2rANLrPmoC\n | isbn =0-8264-1525-3 }}</ref> and they are a part of indigenous Andean religions.<ref name=\"Howard-Malverde\">{{cite book\n | last =Howard-Malverde\n | first =Rosaleen\n | title =Creating Context in Andean Cultures\n | publisher =Oxford University Press\n | year =1997\n | page =16\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=t7ybxALxNfwC&pg=PA16\n | isbn =0-19-510914-7 }}</ref> In Andean mythology, the Andean condor was associated with the sun deity,<ref>{{cite book\n | last = Mundkur\n | first =Balaji\n | title =The Cult of the Serpent\n | publisher =SUNY Press\n | year =1983\n | page =129\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=PDkuiPhZJr0C\n | isbn =0-87395-631-1 }}</ref> and was believed to be the ruler of the upper world.<ref>{{cite book\n |author1=Mills, Alice |author2=Parker, Janet |author3=Stanton, Julie | title =Mythology: Myths, Legends and Fantasies\n | publisher =New Holland Publishers\n | year =2006\n | page =493\n | isbn =1-77007-453-8}}</ref> The Andean condor is considered a symbol of power and health by many Andean cultures, and it was believed that the bones and organs of the Andean condor possessed medicinal powers, sometimes leading to the hunting and killing of condors to obtain its bones and organs.<ref name=\"SanDiego\">{{cite web\n | title = Andean Condor\n | publisher = Zoological Society of San Diego\n | url = http://www.sandiegozoo.org/animalbytes/t-andean_condor.html\n | accessdate = 2007-01-10}}</ref><ref name=\"CleMet2\">{{cite web\n |title=History of the Andean Condor \n |publisher=Cleveland Metroparks Zoo \n |url=http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/history.htm \n |accessdate=2007-01-10 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219195345/http://www.clemetzoo.com/rttw/condor/history.htm \n |archivedate=19 December 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> In some versions of Peruvian bullfighting, a condor is tied to the back of a bull, where it pecks at the animal as bullfighters fight it. The condor generally survives and is set free.<ref>{{cite book| last =Kokotovic| first =Misha| title = The Colonial Divide in Peruvian Narrative:Social Conflict and Transculturation | publisher = Sussex Academic Press| year = 2007| page =49| isbn =978-1-84519-184-9 }}</ref>\n\nIn Peru, they are occasionally shot, but more often revered and used for ceremonial purposes. The Yawar Fiesta is a celebration, the pinnacle of which is the tying of an Andean condor to the back of a bull, allowing the condor to kill the bull with its talons before being released. This ceremony is a symbolic representation of the power of the Andean peoples (the condor) over the Spanish (the bull).<ref>{{cite book| last =Arguedas| first =Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda| title = Yawar Fiesta| translator =  Frances Horning Barraclough| publisher = NorthWood, Inc.| year = 2002| isbn =1-55971-019-5 }}</ref> There is also a ceremony known as the ''arranque del condor'' in which a live Andean condor is suspended from a frame and is punched to death by horsemen as they ride by.<ref>{{cite book| last = Mackenzie| first = John P.S.| title = Birds of Prey| publisher = Waveland Pr Inc.| year = 2002| location = Toronto| page = [https://archive.org/details/yawarfiesta00jose/page/30 30]| isbn = 1-57766-245-8| url = https://archive.org/details/yawarfiesta00jose/page/30}}</ref>\n\n[[Condorito]] is a Chilean comic book and comic strip that features an anthropomorphic condor living in a fictitious town named Pelotillehue, a typical small Chilean provincial town. He is meant to be a representation of the Chilean people.\n\nThe Andean condor is a popular figure on [[postage stamp|stamps]] in many countries, appearing on one for Ecuador in 1958, Argentina in 1960, Peru in 1973, Bolivia in 1985, Colombia in 1992, Chile in 2001, and [[Venezuela]] in 2004.<ref name=\"Stamp \">{{cite web | title =Andean Condor | publisher =Bird Stamps | url = http://www.bird-stamps.org/cspecies/2800600.htm | accessdate = 2008-01-15}}</ref> It has also appeared on the coins and banknotes of Colombia and Chile.<ref>{{cite web | title =A Field Guide to the Birds on Banknotes | publisher =Krause Publications | url = http://members.tripod.com/~fieldguide/bobn.html | accessdate = 2008-01-16}}</ref> The condor is featured in several [[coat of arms|coats of arms]] of Andean countries as a symbol of [[Andes mountains]].\n\nThe Andean condor is depicted on the logo of [[Avianca]] and [[Aerolineas Argentinas]], which are two of the largest airlines in South America. \n{{gallery\n|title=National coat of arms\n|width=120 |height=100\n|align=center\n|File:Coat of arms of Bolivia.svg|[[Coat of arms of Bolivia|Coat of arms]] of [[Bolivia]].\n|File:Coat of arms of Chile.svg|[[Coat of arms of Chile|Coat of arms]] of [[Chile]].\n|File:Coat of arms of Colombia.svg|[[Coat of arms of Colombia|Coat of arms]] of [[Colombia]].\n|File:Coat of arms of Ecuador.svg|[[Coat of arms of Ecuador|Coat of arms]] of [[Ecuador]].\n|File:Escudo de la Rep\u00fablica Peruana (1821-1825).png|First [[Coat of arms of Peru|Coat of arms]] of [[Peru]].\n|File:Coat of arms of Venezuela (1812).svg|[[Coat of arms of Venezuela|Former coat of arms]] of [[Venezuela]].\n}}\n{{gallery\n|title=Others coat of arms\n|width=120 |height=100\n|align=center\n|File:Escudo de Pichincha.gif|Coat of arms of [[Pichincha Province]], [[Ecuador]].\n|File:Escudo de Chimborazo.svg|Coat of arms of [[Chimborazo Province]], [[Ecuador]].\n|File:Coat of arms of M\u00e9rida State.svg|Coat of arms of [[M\u00e9rida (state)|State of M\u00e9rida]], [[Venezuela]].\n|File:Imperial standard of the ethnocacerist movement.jpg|Imperial standard of the [[Movimiento Etnocacerista|Ethnocacerist Movement]], [[Peru]].\n|File:Escudo-UNAM-escalable.svg|[[National Autonomous University of Mexico]], depicting a condor and [[golden eagle]].\n|File:Uncuyo.jpg|[[National University of Cuyo]], [[Argentina]].\n}}\n{{gallery\n|title=Condor in popular culture\n|width=120 |height=100\n|align=center\n|File:Vultur gryphus Chili XIX.jpg|Hunting for condor. Chile, 1854.<ref>[http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.wdl/clsabn.3979 Atlas de la historia fisica y politica de Chile]. [Laminas, Volumen 1], 1854.</ref>\n|File:CondorLassoLyd.jpg|Argentinian [[gaucho]]s lassoing a condor, 1895.\n|File:60 cent Chile Condor.jpg|Stamp of Chile, 60 centavos, 1935.\n||[[Aero C\u00f3ndor]], an airline that flies over the Nazca lines in Peru.\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|33em}}\n* {{citation|author1=Richard P. Reading|author2=Brian Miller|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f_AWCtX29-kC&pg=PA16|title=Endangered Animals: A Reference Guide to Conflicting Issues|chapter=Andean Condor|p=[https://archive.org/details/endangeredanimal0000unse_m4q9/page/16 16]|date=2000|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-03-1330-816-1|ref={{sfnref|Richard P. Reading|Brian Miller|2000}}|url=https://archive.org/details/endangeredanimal0000unse_m4q9/page/16}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons+cat|Vultur gryphus|Vultur_gryphus}}\n{{Wikispecies|Vultur gryphus}}\n* [http://www.vulture-territory.com/andean.html Vulture Territory Facts and Characteristics: Andean condor]\n* ARKive \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20060720164351/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/birds/Vultur_gryphus/ images and movies of the Andean condor ''(Vultur gryphus)'']\n* [http://www.imagesandmusic.nl/dhtml/Condors.htm Video of Peruvian condors]\n* [http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=3822&m=0 BirdLife Species Factsheet]\n* [http://www.ecologia.info/condor-dos-andes.htm Andean condor]\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/andean-condor-vultur-gryphus Andean condor videos] on the Internet Bird Collection\n* [http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-colombia-condors30-2009aug30-pictures,0,377184.photogallery Scientists Work to Repopulate Colombia's Skies with Condors] \u2013 slideshow by ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]''\n* [http://www.bioandina.org.ar Proyecto Conservaci\u00f3n C\u00f3ndor Andino de Argentina], Organizado por la Fundaci\u00f3n Bioandina Argentina.\n*[http://www.ecology.info/condors.htm Ecology of condors]\n\n{{Vulture}}\n{{Symbols of Colombia}}\n{{Bolivia symbols}}\n{{Featured article}}\n{{Portalbar|Biology|Animals|Birds|Mythology|Latin America|Bolivia|Chile|Colombia}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q170598}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:condor, Andean}}\n[[Category:Cathartidae|Andean condor]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Andes|*]]\n[[Category:New World vultures]]\n[[Category:P\u00e1ramo fauna]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Argentina]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Colombia]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Chile]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Peru]]\n[[Category:Near threatened animals]]\n[[Category:Near threatened biota of South America]]\n[[Category:Extant Piacenzian first appearances|Andean condor]]\n[[Category:Pliocene birds of South America|Andean condor]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|Andean condor]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus|Andean condor]]\n", "name_user": "Frybulous", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andean_condor"}
